 younger witches start producing shake-drinks, and to make them sell Mabel adds addictive powdered mandrake shoots from the kitchen, causing chaotic demands for more.\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Worst Witch (2017 TV series)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 45\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n|Title           = Maud's Magical Make-over\n|DirectedBy      = Dermot Boyd\n|WrittenBy       = Scott Payne\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|2|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/03/02|title=BBC TV Guide|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n|Viewers         = 0.150\n|ShortSummary    = Maud spurns Mildred after she is persuaded by Miss Hempnettle to invite Enid to be deputy in the head girl competition. Maud moves in with Felicity, after a bunk room bat invasion, and Maud discovers Felicity uses a secret coolness potion. Transforming herself, Maud wins new fans but causes friction. Enid discovers Miss Hempnettle cheated her potion enhanced race timings. Mabel shares a mind reading potion with her chums, and eventually uses it on her Mum, Miss Tapioca, and realises her Mum is lovingly proud of her. Maud and Felicity squabble and spill the potion, then Maud, realising her error, causes all forms of coolness to fail at a party in the forest with boys from Amulets. Now non-cool, the party goers still get on.\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Worst Witch (2017 TV series)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 46\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n|Title           = The Crystal Lake\n|DirectedBy      = Dermot Boyd\n|WrittenBy       = Neil Jones\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|9|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/03/09|title=BBC TV Guide|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n|Viewers         = 0.122\n|ShortSummary    = Clumsy Mr. Daisy, the new art-science teacher arrives at Cackles upsetting Mabel's sweet stall. Mildred is conned into visiting the \"fortune telling\" Crystal Lake by an evil old crone, Jessica Juniper, masquerading as a girl from Pentangles in the magic mirror. In the forest Mildred meets Clarice, Sybil and Beatrice, who were conned too. At the lake Mildred is attacked by the crone, and finally performs protection spell and is rescued by Maud and Miss Hardbroom. Feeling irresponsible she resigns as head girl contender, but, on seeing Ethel's future in Mr. Daisy's flask, she asks to rejoin. Meanwhile Enid is tricked by Miss Hempnettle into acquiring Miss Drill's special speed potion.\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Worst Witch (2017 TV series)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 47\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n|Title           = Enid's Last Race\n|DirectedBy      = Dermot Boyd\n|WrittenBy       = Paul Gerstenberger\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|16|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/03/16|title=BBC TV Guide|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n|Viewers         =\n|ShortSummary    = A disheartened Enid leaves Cackles Academy after being tricked into stealing Miss Drill's speed potion formula. She rehearses with her eager mother for \"The Deadly Nightshades and family\" show. Miss Drill does not blame Enid and (along with Mildred) persuades her to take part in the Witch World Games qualifiers. Meanwhile Miss Tapioca, Mr Daisy, and students rustle up ingredients for Miss Drill's potion which helps Enid to win, despite sneaky tricks by Miss Hempnettle. Enid accepts a place at the prestigious Mount Broom sporting academy now with the encouragement of her mother. In a sub-plot Ethel undermines Azura as a school ambassador to the Magic Council.\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Worst Witch (2017 TV series)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 48\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n|Title           = Mildred the Detective\n|DirectedBy      = Dermot Boyd\n|WrittenBy       = Kirstie Falkous & Neil Jones\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|23|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/03/23|title=BBC TV Guide|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n|Viewers         =\n|ShortSummary    = Ethel accuses Mildred of taking her head girl badges. A locating crystal leads Ethel to find them on the roof. Many other strange events occur around the academy like the broom store, kitchen and library all in a mess. Miss Cackle assigns Mildred and Ethel the head-girl-competition task of discovering the prankster. Meanwhile Fenella is too controlling in her dining etiquette project (plus sabotage by the prankster) results in the coven leaving her. Mildred sees an unattached shadow of Azura's silhouette, leading to the revelation Azura had cast a spell to rid herself of scary dark shadows: her own became detached causing the events. Mildred volunteers to take the blame, and Miss Hardbroom says this is evidence of head girl material. Meanwhile Mr Daisy is up to something secretive in a shed, but what?\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Worst Witch (2017 TV series)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 49\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 10\n|Title           = A Witch in Time\n|DirectedBy      = Lindy Heymann\n|WrittenBy       = Scott Payne\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|30|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/03/30|title=BBC TV Guide|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n|Viewers         =\n|ShortSummary    = Mildred and Ethel compete in the Head Girl competition Triathlon, Mildred wins chanting and flying but looses on control of her familiar Tabby. Worried her vision of Ethel making all the students disappear if she becomes head girl, Mildred uses a sandtimer to go back in time four times. Her three initial attempts all end in disaster (her dog raids the kitchen, Maud looses her voice, and next time injured). Fourthly, at Mr. Daisy's behest \"A great witch relies on her wits, not just her magic,\" Mildred wins the Triathlon. Meanwhile Mr Daisy's secret Patented Potions Machine is revealed and is sabotaged by Mabel, who eventually relents when Miss Hardbroom intends to sack him for incompetence.\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Worst Witch (2017 TV series)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 50\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 11\n|Title           = Grounded\n|DirectedBy      = Lindy Heymann\n|WrittenBy       = Paul Gerstenberger\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|6|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/04/06|title=BBC TV Guide|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n|Viewers         =\n|ShortSummary    = The arrival of a magical comet is announced. With Mildred and Ethel getting ready for the final head girl challenge (to create a new spell) Mildred starts to suffer from magical burnout. Knowing this Maud, Izzy and Mrs Cackle decide to send her to rest at Izzy's farm to watch the comet. Upon arriving Mildred's attempts at magic go wrong to the point of her magic completely failing. After a bit of digging it is found that Mildred needs her family's grounding stone to restore her magic, and since she has no idea where it is, Izzy's dad hatch's a plan to use the comet to create a new one.\nBack at the school Ethel tries to disqualify Mildred from the head girl competition by snitching on a half-heard conversation between Mildred and Professor Daisy when returning his sandtimer. Maud and Azura try to delay Ethel, this only works for a short while before Ethel brings Miss Hardbroom into it. This leads to a confrontation with Mr Daisy who ultimately protects Mildred by claiming he was the one to loop time. And come the end of term will be fired.\nBack at the farm Mildred and Izzy's attempts to create a new grounding stone ultimately fail, when all is assumed lost Mildred's true grounding stone is found as Izzy's dad (Spike Jones played by Alun Raglan) was given it by Mrs Hubble many years ago in Morroco. Mildred restores her magic and goes back to the academy with a good idea for her Spell.\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Worst Witch (2017 TV series)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 51\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 12\n|Title           = The Witching Hour: Part 1\n|DirectedBy      = Lindy Heymann\n|WrittenBy       = Neil Jones\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|13|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/04/13|title=BBC TV Guide|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n|Viewers         =\n|ShortSummary    = Ethel and Mildred perform their newly designed spells in the final round of the Head Girl competition. Mildred's spell apparently goes wrong and turns Headmistress Miss Cackle into shattered glass. Mildred is sent to The Correctional School for Undesirable Witches, Wormwood, where she is befriended by Camilla Clove (played by Madeleine Edmondson) and menaced by the cruel jailer Miss Splinter (played by Sue Vincent). Meanwhile Maud analyses playback and realises someone else caused Miss Cackle's demise and deliberately gets herself sent to Wormwood too with a plan to free Mildred. Ethel was doing Agatha (Ada's evil twin) Cackle's bidding and tricked Felicity into sabotaging Mildred's spell. Ethel frees Agatha. Mildred and Maud make their escape from Wormwood.\nIn a sub-plot, an attempt to comfort (the soon to be dismissed) Mr Daisy with a Happiness Potion goes wrong, when he dances in an over familiar way with Miss Hardbroom.\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Worst Witch (2017 TV series)\n|EpisodeNumber   = 52\n|EpisodeNumber2  = 13\n|Title           = The Witching Hour: Part 2\n|DirectedBy      = Lindy Heymann\n|WrittenBy       = Neil Jones\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|20|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2020/04/20|title=BBC TV Guide|website=bbc.co.uk|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n|Viewers         =\n|ShortSummary    = Agatha Cackle, impersonating headmistress Ada, promotes Ethel to head girl, and at the school assembly tricks everyone else into the Banishment plane of existence, including Mildred's mum (who had been messaged by Maud). Agatha locks Mr. Daisy away and thwarts Miss Hardbroom with a magic restricting broach. She also demands the Great Wizard hands over his title.\nMildred's mum organises tower building with junk in the banishment plane, and they escape. \n\nMildred and Maud search for the magic reversal word to reverse the banishment and in the process discover Mr. Daisy locked away. He agrees to use his potion machine, so while Mildred and Maud delay Agatha with distractions, his machine's potion restores Miss Cackle. She in turn saves Mildred's Mum with the secret word. Agatha banishes herself.\n\nMildred learns Izzy Jones is her sister and Spike is her dad, who her mum (Julie) met in Morrocco just before she was born. Mildred and Ethel make peace just before Mildred is confirmed as head girl.\n|LineColor       = #904000\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Production and casting==\nIn November 2014, it was announced that a new series of The Worst Witch was in development with the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a607329/the-worst-witch-writer-reveals-new-tv-adaptation-is-in-development/|title=The Worst Witch writer reveals new TV adaptation is in development|work=Digital Spy|last=Alexander|first=Susannah|date=2 November 2014|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> The cast of the show was announced in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a812479/heres-your-first-look-at-the-spooky-worst-witch-tv-remake/|title=Here's your first look at the spooky Worst Witch TV remake, featuring stars from Game of Thrones and Downton Abbey|work=Digital Spy|last=Anderton|first=Joe|date=31 October 2016|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' actress [[Bella Ramsey]] was cast as Mildred and said filming the series \"was really good\", but there were some challenging elements and described learning the stunts as \"hard.\"<ref name=\"Bella Ramsey casting\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/dec/18/worst-witch-children-tv-adaptation|title=Harry Potter for girls? I\u2019m not that kind of Worst Witch, says TV\u2019s new Mildred Hubble|work=Guardian|last=Conlan|first=Tara|date=25 July 2017|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> Ramsey drew similarities between herself and Mildred.<ref name=\"Bella Ramsey casting\"/> Meibh Campbell played the role of Maud Spellbody for series 1, but was replaced by Megan Hughes from series 2.<ref name=\"Megan Hughes casting\">{{cite news|url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/15428751.Oxfordshire_schoolgirl_set_to_become_national_star_in_new_series_of_The_Worst_Witch/|title=Oxfordshire schoolgirl Megan Hughes is set to become a national star in new series of The Worst Witch|work=Oxford Mail|last=Hughes|first=Pete|date=25 July 2017|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> Of her casting, Hughes said working on the show is \"great and I [Hughes] love the experience\" and that she is \"so grateful for the opportunity.\" Hughes had two auditions before being offered the part of Maud.<ref name=\"Megan Hughes casting\"/> Hughes' mother, Claire, added that Hughes has an \"amazing time\" and is \"really happy, really positive\" throughout filming.<ref name=\"Megan Hughes casting\"/> Tamara Smart gained the part of Enid Nightshade after four months of auditioning, which she described as \"very long\" yet \"nerve racking but at the same time very exciting.\" Smart was excited about the \"amazing experience\" when she got the part.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.borehamwoodtimes.co.uk/news/14725970.Barnet_schoolgirl_is_flying_high_at_landing_star_role_in_CBBC_show/|title=Barnet schoolgirl is flying high at landing star role in CBBC show|work=Borehamwood Times|date=6 September 2016|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> Jenny Richardson and Miriam Petche were cast as sisters Ethel and Esmerelda Hallow.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/14947530.Drama_pupil_from_Leatherhead_to_star_in_The_Worst_Witch_reboot/|title=Drama pupil from Leatherhead to star in The Worst Witch reboot|work=Your Local Guardian|last=Dickerson|first=Rachel|date=5 December 2016|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/mark_jermin_mgt/status/733620874746732545 Mark Jermin Management on Twitter: HUGE well done to Miriam Petche who will be playing the role of Esmerelda in new CBBC remake of THE WORST WITCH!<!--Bot Generated Title-->]</ref> Tallulah Milligan, the daughter of ''[[Coronation Street]]'' and ''[[Waterloo Road (TV series)|Waterloo Road]]'' actress [[Angela Griffin]], was cast as Drusilla Paddock. Griffin said Milligan \"absolutely loves\" working on the show.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/jul/15/angela-griffin-shes-ace-my-mum-a-grounded-down-to-earth-yorkshirewoman|title=Angela Griffin: \u2018She\u2019s ace, my mum \u2013 a grounded, down-to-earth Yorkshirewoman\u2019|work=Guardian|last=Gray|first=Susan|date=16 July 2016|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> Dagny Rollins plays the role of Felicity Foxglove.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/leanne-brown-angela-griffin-cbbc-12310052|title=Leanne Brown and Angela Griffin turn out for special CBBC Worst Witch screening|work=Manchester Evening News|date=14 December 2016|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Worst Witch is filmed at [[Peckforton Castle]], [[Peckforton]] [[Cheshire]], [[England]] and [[Burg Hohenzollern]], [[Swabian Alps]], [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worstwitch/15-facts|title=CBBC brings The Worst Witch to life for a new generation|work=BBC|date=11 December 2016|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> The second series is also filmed at [[Adlington Hall]], [[Adlington, Cheshire|Adlington]], [[Cheshire]], using their grand hall, minstrel's gallery and their countryside and woods backdrop.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://marketingcheshire.co.uk/news/adlington-hall-gardens-turns-witching-academy/|title=Adlington Hall & Gardens Turns Into A Witching Academy|work=Marketing Cheshire|year=2018|accessdate=12 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme | b09m8lyz | The Worst Witch}}\n* [https://www.netflix.com/title/80130521''The Worst Witch''] on [[Netflix]]\n* {{IMDb title|5721172|The Worst Witch}}\n\n{{The Worst Witch}}\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Worst Witch, The}}\n[[Category:BBC children's television programmes]]\n[[Category:ZDF television series]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft in television]]\n[[Category:Wizards in television]]\n[[Category:British supernatural television programmes]]\n[[Category:2017 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:The Worst Witch]]\n[[Category:Television about magic]]\n[[Category:British television programmes based on children's books]]\n[[Category:2017 German television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s German television series]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Netflix children's programming]]\n", "name_user": "QivisNeaf", "label": "safe", "comment": "Number of episodes from 41 to 52 in info bos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Worst_Witch_(2017_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "The Philadelphia Story (play)", "text_new": "{{short description|1939 play by Philip Barry}}\n{{About|the play|the film adaptation|The Philadelphia Story (film)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox play\n| name       = The Philadelphia Story\n| image      = philstoryplay.jpg\n| image_size = 180px\n| caption    = First edition\n| writer     = [[Philip Barry]]\n| characters =\n| genre      = Comedy\n| setting    = The suburbs of [[Philadelphia]] in the 1930s\n| premiere   = {{Start date|df=yes|1939|03|28}}\n| place      = [[Shubert Theatre (Broadway)|Shubert Theatre]], New York City\n| orig_lang  = English\n| subject    =  Love, marriage, divorce\n| web        =\n}}\n'''''The Philadelphia Story''''' is a 1939 American comic [[Play (theatre)|play]] by [[Philip Barry]]. It tells the story of a [[socialite]] whose wedding plans are complicated by the simultaneous arrival of her ex-husband and an attractive journalist. Written as a vehicle for [[Katharine Hepburn]], its success marked a reversal of fortunes for the actress, who was one of the film stars deemed \"[[Box Office Poison (magazine article)|box office poison]]\" in 1938.\n\n==Production==\nThe character of Tracy Lord was inspired by [[Helen Hope Montgomery Scott]], a Philadelphia socialite known for her hijinks, who married a friend of playwright [[Philip Barry]].<ref>Irvine, Ian [http://www.reelclassics.com/Movies/Philstory/tracylord-article.htm \"The Real Philadelphia Story\"] at [http://www.reelclassics.com ReelClassics.com]</ref> Barry wrote ''The Philadelphia Story'' specifically for [[Katharine Hepburn]], who ended up not only starring in but also financially backing the play, forgoing a salary in return for a percentage of the play's profits.<ref name=tcmarticle /> The play was a great success on Broadway, and was Hepburn's first great triumph after a number of Hollywood failures had led the Independent Theatre Owners of America to publicly deem her and a number of other film stars \"[[Box Office Poison (magazine article)|box office poison]]\".\n\nProduced by the [[Theatre Guild]], ''The Philadelphia Story'' opened on March 28, 1939, at the [[Shubert Theatre (New York City)|Shubert Theatre]] in New York City, and closed on March 30, 1940.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Golden |first1=Herb |title=The Philadelphia Story (review) |journal=Variety |date=November 26, 1940 |url=https://variety.com/1940/film/reviews/the-philadelphia-story-1200413300/ |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> The three-act comedy was directed by [[Robert B. Sinclair]], with lighting and scenery by Robert Edmond Jones.<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\">{{cite news |last=Atkinson |first=Brooks |authorlink=Brooks Atkinson |date=29 March 1939 |title=The Play: Katharine Hepburn Appearing in Philip Barry's 'The Philadelphia Story' for the Theatre Guild |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9804E6D7133CE73ABC4151DFB5668382629EDE |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=10 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-1.jpg|Katharine Hepburn\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-2.jpg|Vera Allen, [[Dan Tobin]], Katharine Hepburn and [[Lenore Lonergan]]\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-3.jpg|Katharine Hepburn\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-4.jpg|Katharine Hepburn\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-5.jpg|[[Joseph Cotten]] and Katharine Hepburn\n</gallery>\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Hepburn-FC-Stage-1939.jpg|thumb|260px|right|Katharine Hepburn in the [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] stage production of ''The Philadelphia Story'']]\n* [[Lenore Lonergan]] as Dinah Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Vera Allen as Margaret Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Katharine Hepburn]] as Tracy Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Dan Tobin]] as Alexander Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Owen Coll as Thomas<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Forrest Orr as William Tracy<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Shirley Booth]] as Elizabeth Imbrie<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Van Heflin]] as Macauley Connor<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Frank Fenton (actor)|Frank Fenton]] as George Kittredge<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Joseph Cotten]] as C. K. Dexter Haven<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Nicholas Joy as Seth Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Myrtle Tannahill as May<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Lorraine Bate as Elsie<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Hayden Rorke]] as Mac<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Film===\nHoping to create a film vehicle for herself which would erase the label, Hepburn accepted the film rights to the play from [[Howard Hughes]], who had purchased them as a gift for her. She then convinced [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]]'s [[Louis B. Mayer]] to buy them from her for only $250,000 in return for Hepburn having veto over producer, director, screenwriter, and cast.<ref name=tcmarticle>Melear, Mary Anne [http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title.jsp?stid=12778&category=Articles \"The Philadelphia Story\" (TCM article)]</ref><ref name=tcmnotes>TCM [http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title.jsp?stid=12778&category=Notes Notes]</ref><ref>All Movie [http://www.allmovie.com/cg/avg.dll?p=avg&sql=1:38000 Overview]</ref>\n\nIn 1940 the play was [[The Philadelphia Story (film)|adapted to film]], in a [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] picture directed by [[George Cukor]] with Hepburn as the star, and starring [[Cary Grant]] as C.K. Dexter Haven and [[James Stewart]] as Macaulay Connor.\n\nIn 1956, it was adapted to a Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer [[musical film]] version, ''[[High Society (1956 film)|High Society]]'' with [[Grace Kelly]] in the Tracy Lord role, [[Bing Crosby]] as C.K. Dexter Haven and [[Frank Sinatra]] as Macaulay Connor.\n\n===Radio===\nRadio adaptations of ''The Philadelphia Story'' include a half-hour presentation on ''The Prudential Family Hour of Stars'' (26 February 1950), starring [[Sarah Churchill (actress)|Sarah Churchill]], [[Norma Jean Nilsson]], [[Gerald Mohr]] and [[Gene Kelly]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=The+Prudential+Family+Hour+Of+Stars |title=The Prudential Family Hour of Stars  |publisher=RadioGOLDINdex |access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref> An hour-long adaptation was broadcast 17 August 1952, on ''Best Plays'', with a cast including [[Joan Alexander]], [[Betty Furness]], [[Myron McCormick]] and Vera Allen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=Best+Plays |title=Best Plays  |publisher=RadioGOLDINdex |access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\n''The Philadelphia Story'' was adapted for the second season of the [[NBC]]-TV series, ''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]''. Starring [[Barbara Bel Geddes]] (Tracy Lord), [[Richard Derr]] (Macauley Connor) and [[Leslie Nielsen]] (C. K. Dexter Haven), the one-hour live program aired 4 December 1950.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ctva.biz/US/Anthology/RobertMontgomeryPresents_02_%281950-51%29.htm |title=Robert Montgomery Presents |publisher=Classic Television Archive |access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 1954, a live 60-minute adaptation of the play was broadcast on the [[CBS]]-TV series, ''[[The Best of Broadway]]''. The cast included [[Mary Astor]] (Margaret Lord), [[Dorothy McGuire]] (Tracy Lord), [[Charles Winninger]] (Uncle Willie), [[Neva Patterson]] (Liz Imbrie), [[Richard Carlson (actor)|Richard Carlson]] (Mike Connor), [[Dick Foran]] (George Kittredge), [[John Payne (actor)|John Payne]] (C.K. Dexter Haven) and [[Herbert Marshall]] (Seth Lord).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ctva.biz/US/Anthology/BestOfBroadway.htm |title=Best of Broadway |publisher=Classic Television Archive |access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nA [[The Philadelphia Story (1959 film)|two-hour adaptation]] aired on [[NBC]]-TV on 7 December 1959, directed by [[Fielder Cook]] and starring [[Gig Young]] (C.K. Dexter Haven), [[Diana Lynn]] (Tracy Lord), [[Christopher Plummer]] (Mike Connor), [[Ruth Roman]] (Liz Imbrie), [[Mary Astor]] (Margaret Lord), [[Don DeFore]] (George Kittredge), [[Alan Webb (actor)|Alan Webb]] (Seth Lord), and [[Leon Janney]] (Sidney Kidd). The instrumental theme for this version, \"[[Tracy's Theme]]\", was released as a single by [[Robert Mersey]] under the name \"Spencer Ross\" and became a Top 20 hit.\n\n==Copyright==\nCopyright for ''The Philadelphia Story'' was registered in 1939 by Barry and his wife, portrait artist [[Ellen Semple Barry]],<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Library of Congress]] |first=Copyright Office |date=1939 |title=Catalog of Copyright Entries. Part 1. Group 3. Dramatic Composition and Motion Pictures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=41ljAAAAIAAJ|location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Government Printing Office |page=39 }}</ref> and was renewed by her in 1967.<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Library of Congress]] |first=Copyright Office |date=1967 |title=Catalog of Copyright Entries 3D Ser Vol 21 Pts 3\u20134 Dramas and Works Prepared for Oral Delivery |url=https://archive.org/stream/catalogofcop196732134libr#page/146/mode/1up |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Government Printing Office |page=146 }}</ref> Her estate retains copyright to the play.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blake |first=Jason |date=2 November 2013|title=Copyright closes the book on Philadelphia Story|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/theatre/copyright-closes-the-book-on-philadelphia-story-20131101-2wrxi.html |newspaper=[[The Age]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Philadelphia Story (play)}}\n* {{IBDB show|7066|The Philadelphia Story}}\n* {{ibdb title|12441|The Philadelphia Story}}\n* [https://archive.org/download/BestPlays/BestPlays52-08-1711ThePhiladelphiaStory.mp3 1952 ''Best Plays'' radio adaptation] at [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philadelphia Story}}\n[[Category:Plays by Philip Barry]]\n[[Category:1939 plays]]\n[[Category:Broadway plays]]\n[[Category:Comedy plays]]\n[[Category:Plays set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American plays adapted into films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1939 play by Philip Barry}}\n{{About|the play|the film adaptation|The Philadelphia Story (film)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox play\n| name       = The Philadelphia Story\n| image      = philstoryplay.jpg\n| image_size = 180px\n| caption    = First edition\n| writer     = [[Philip Barry]]\n| characters =\n| genre      = Comedy\n| setting    = The suburbs of [[Philadelphia]] in the 1930s\n| premiere   = {{Start date|df=yes|1939|03|28}}\n| place      = [[Shubert Theatre (Broadway)|Shubert Theatre]], New York City\n| orig_lang  = English\n| subject    =  Love, marriage, divorce\n| web        =\n}}\n'''''The Philadelphia Story''''' is a 1939 American comic [[Play (theatre)|play]] by [[Philip Barry]]. It tells the story of a [[socialite]] whose wedding plans are complicated by the simultaneous arrival of her ex-husband and an attractive journalist. Written as a vehicle for [[Katharine Hepburn]], its success marked a reversal of fortunes for the actress, who was one of the film stars deemed \"[[Box Office Poison (magazine article)|box office poison]]\" in 1938.\n\n==Production==\nThe character of Tracy Lord was inspired by [[Helen Hope Montgomery Scott]], a Philadelphia socialite known for her hijinks, who married a friend of playwright [[Philip Barry]].<ref>Irvine, Ian [http://www.reelclassics.com/Movies/Philstory/tracylord-article.htm \"The Real Philadelphia Story\"] at [http://www.reelclassics.com ReelClassics.com]</ref> Barry wrote ''The Philadelphia Story'' specifically for [[Katharine Hepburn]], who ended up not only starring in but also financially backing the play, forgoing a salary in return for a percentage of the play's profits.<ref name=tcmarticle /> The play was a great success on Broadway, and was Hepburn's first great triumph after a number of Hollywood failures had led the Independent Theatre Owners of America to publicly deem her and a number of other film stars \"[[Box Office Poison (magazine article)|box office poison]]\".\n\nProduced by the [[Theatre Guild]], ''The Philadelphia Story'' opened on March 28, 1939, at the [[Shubert Theatre (New York City)|Shubert Theatre]] in New York City, and closed on March 30, 1940.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Golden |first1=Herb |title=The Philadelphia Story (review) |journal=Variety |date=November 26, 1940 |url=https://variety.com/1940/film/reviews/the-philadelphia-story-1200413300/ |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> The three-act comedy was directed by [[Robert B. Sinclair]], with lighting and scenery by Robert Edmond Jones.<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\">{{cite news |last=Atkinson |first=Brooks |authorlink=Brooks Atkinson |date=29 March 1939 |title=The Play: Katharine Hepburn Appearing in Philip Barry's 'The Philadelphia Story' for the Theatre Guild |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9804E6D7133CE73ABC4151DFB5668382629EDE |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=10 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-1.jpg|Katharine Hepburn\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-2.jpg|Vera Allen, [[Dan Tobin]], Katharine Hepburn and [[Lenore Lonergan]]\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-3.jpg|Katharine Hepburn\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-4.jpg|Katharine Hepburn\nFile:Philadelphia-Story-Stage-5.jpg|[[Joseph Cotten]] and Katharine Hepburn\n</gallery>\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Hepburn-FC-Stage-1939.jpg|thumb|260px|right|Katharine Hepburn in the [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] stage production of ''The Philadelphia Story'']]\n* [[Lenore Lonergan]] as Dinah Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Vera Allen as Margaret Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Katharine Hepburn]] as Tracy Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Dan Tobin]] as Alexander Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Owen Coll as Thomas<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Forrest Orr as William Tracy<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Shirley Booth]] as Elizabeth Imbrie<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Van Heflin]] as Macauley Connor<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Frank Fenton (actor)|Frank Fenton]] as George Kittredge<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Joseph Cotten]] as C. K. Dexter Haven<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Nicholas Joy as Seth Lord<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Myrtle Tannahill as May<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* Lorraine Bate as Elsie<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n* [[Hayden Rorke]] as Mac<ref name=\"NYT Atkinson\"/>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Film===\nHoping to create a film vehicle for herself which would erase the label, Hepburn accepted the film rights to the play from [[Howard Hughes]], who had purchased them as a gift for her. She then convinced [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]]'s [[Louis B. Mayer]] to buy them from her for only $250,000 in return for Hepburn having veto over producer, director, screenwriter, and cast.<ref name=tcmarticle>Melear, Mary Anne [http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title.jsp?stid=12778&category=Articles \"The Philadelphia Story\" (TCM article)]</ref><ref name=tcmnotes>TCM [http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title.jsp?stid=12778&category=Notes Notes]</ref><ref>All Movie [http://www.allmovie.com/cg/avg.dll?p=avg&sql=1:38000 Overview]</ref>\n\nIn 1940 the play was [[The Philadelphia Story (film)|adapted to film]], in a [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] picture directed by [[George Cukor]] with Hepburn as the star, and starring [[Cary Grant]] as C.K. Dexter Haven and [[James Stewart]] as Macaulay Connor.\n\nIn 1956, it was adapted to a Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer [[musical film]] version, ''[[High Society (1956 film)|High Society]]'' with [[Grace Kelly]] in the Tracy Lord role, [[Bing Crosby]] as C.K. Dexter Haven and [[Frank Sinatra]] as Macaulay Connor.\n\n===Radio===\nRadio adaptations of ''The Philadelphia Story'' include a half-hour presentation on ''The Prudential Family Hour of Stars'' (26 February 1950), starring [[Sarah Churchill (actress)|Sarah Churchill]], [[Norma Jean Nilsson]], [[Gerald Mohr]] and [[Gene Kelly]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=The+Prudential+Family+Hour+Of+Stars |title=The Prudential Family Hour of Stars  |publisher=RadioGOLDINdex |access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref> An hour-long adaptation was broadcast 17 August 1952, on ''Best Plays'', with a cast including [[Joan Alexander]], [[Betty Furness]], [[Myron McCormick]] and Vera Allen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://radiogoldindex.com/cgi-local/p2.cgi?ProgramName=Best+Plays |title=Best Plays  |publisher=RadioGOLDINdex |access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\n''The Philadelphia Story'' was adapted for the second season of the [[NBC]]-TV series, ''[[Robert Montgomery Presents]]''. Starring [[Barbara Bel Geddes]] (Tracy Lord), [[Richard Derr]] (Macauley Connor) and [[Leslie Nielsen]] (C. K. Dexter Haven), the one-hour live program aired 4 December 1950.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ctva.biz/US/Anthology/RobertMontgomeryPresents_02_%281950-51%29.htm |title=Robert Montgomery Presents |publisher=Classic Television Archive |access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 1954, a live 60-minute adaptation of the play was broadcast on the [[CBS]]-TV series, ''[[The Best of Broadway]]''. The cast included [[Mary Astor]] (Margaret Lord), [[Dorothy McGuire]] (Tracy Lord), [[Charles Winninger]] (Uncle Willie), [[Neva Patterson]] (Liz Imbrie), [[Richard Carlson (actor)|Richard Carlson]] (Mike Connor), [[Dick Foran]] (George Kittredge), [[John Payne (actor)|John Payne]] (C.K. Dexter Haven) and [[Herbert Marshall]] (Seth Lord).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ctva.biz/US/Anthology/BestOfBroadway.htm |title=Best of Broadway |publisher=Classic Television Archive |access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nA [[The Philadelphia Story (1959 film)|two-hour adaptation]] aired on [[NBC]]-TV on 7 December 1959, directed by [[Fielder Cook]] and starring [[Gig Young]] (C.K. Dexter Haven), [[Diana Lynn]] (Tracy Lord), [[Christopher Plummer]] (Mike Connor), [[Ruth Roman]] (Liz Imbrie), [[Mary Astor]] (Margaret Lord), [[Don DeFore]] (George Kittredge), [[Alan Webb (actor)|Alan Webb]] (Seth Lord), and [[Leon Janney]] (Sidney Kidd). The instrumental theme for this version, \"[[Tracy's Theme]]\", was released as a single by [[Robert Mersey]] under the name \"Spencer Ross\" and became a Top 20 hit.\n\n==Copyright==\nCopyright for ''The Philadelphia Story'' was registered in 1939 by Barry and his wife, portrait artist [[Ellen Semple Barry]],<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Library of Congress]] |first=Copyright Office |date=1939 |title=Catalog of Copyright Entries. Part 1. Group 3. Dramatic Composition and Motion Pictures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=41ljAAAAIAAJ|location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Government Printing Office |page=39 }}</ref> and was renewed by her in 1967.<ref>{{cite book |last=[[Library of Congress]] |first=Copyright Office |date=1967 |title=Catalog of Copyright Entries 3D Ser Vol 21 Pts 3\u20134 Dramas and Works Prepared for Oral Delivery |url=https://archive.org/stream/catalogofcop196732134libr#page/146/mode/1up |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Government Printing Office |page=146 }}</ref> Her estate retains copyright to the play.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blake |first=Jason |date=2 November 2013|title=Copyright closes the book on Philadelphia Story|url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/theatre/copyright-closes-the-book-on-philadelphia-story-20131101-2wrxi.html |newspaper=[[The Age]}}/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Philadelphia Story (play)}}\n* {{IBDB show|7066|The Philadelphia Story}}\n* {{ibdb title|12441|The Philadelphia Story}}\n* [https://archive.org/download/BestPlays/BestPlays52-08-1711ThePhiladelphiaStory.mp3 1952 ''Best Plays'' radio adaptation] at [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Philadelphia Story}}\n[[Category:Plays by Philip Barry]]\n[[Category:1939 plays]]\n[[Category:Broadway plays]]\n[[Category:Comedy plays]]\n[[Category:Plays set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American plays adapted into films]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "format cite template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Philadelphia_Story_(play)"}
{"title_page": "Online social movement", "text_new": "Social movements are loosely organised efforts to push for a particular goal.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/260204710|title=A dictionary of sociology|date=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Scott, John, 1949-, Marshall, Gordon.|isbn=978-0-19-953300-8|edition=3rd ed. rev|location=Oxford|oclc=260204710}}</ref> In many cases, these movements seek to counter the mainstream public, claiming there is a wrong that ought to be righted.<ref name=\":2\">Tufekci, Zeynep. {{Citation|last=|first=|title=Twitter and Tear Gas The Power and Fragility of Networked Protest.|date=2017|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/989057566|volume=|pages=|others=|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-21512-0|oclc=|access-date=}}</ref> The first social movements occurred through protests and civil disobedience, but with the rise of the internet, social movements have gone online. Online social movements have since gained momentum in the 20th and 21st century. The organisational structures and strategies behind social movements have changed as a result of the online world, utilizing technology and the internet to mobilize more people in a shorter period of time.\n\n[[Online community|Online communities]] build off [[social movement]]s, enabling the connection of persons worldwide to develop a base and gain awareness of issues. Online social movements gained momentum in the late 20th century and early 21st century<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobilizingideas.wordpress.com/2012/08/01/social-movements-how-people-make-history/|title=Social Movements: How People Make History|last=Ideas|first=Mobilizing|date=2012-08-01|website=Mobilizing Ideas|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref> as new generations sought social change. With access to the internet and the fast-growing [[World Wide Web]], online social movements brought awareness to issues both political and social. Online social movements have been praised and criticized; the former for its ability to raise awareness to important causes, and the latter for its ability to perpetuate problems like [[slacktivism]]. Although online activism has received criticism, it has had real impacts on social movements.\n\n====== History of Online Social Movements ======\nThe earliest social movements were minimally related to the internet. For instance, Charles Tilly recognizes the first social movements in Britain and the US in the 1750s and 1760s, after the 7 Years War. [[John Wilkes]] led the \"Wilkes and Liberty\" movement to achieve legal and parliamentary reform. Across the Atlantic, the Boston merchants and the activists in the [[Sons of Liberty]] initiated the opposition to the British that eventually lead to the Declaration of Independence in 1776.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Tilly, Charles 1929-2008 Verfasser.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1126812829|title=Social movements, 1768-2018|isbn=978-0-367-07607-8|oclc=1126812829}}</ref>\n\nThe mentality behind these was spurred on by sovereignty within British politics through the Reformation and informed John Wilkes and his followers about alternative societal rule. Thus, in 1768, members of the English lower class began to mobilize underneath Wilkes\u2019 movement against the sovereignty of the ruling class.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Cash, Arthur.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/952732211|title=John Wilkes : the Scandalous Father of Civil Liberty.|date=2008|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-300-10871-0|oclc=952732211}}</ref> On May 10, 1768, Wilkes\u2019 supporters and the king\u2019s soldiers at St. George\u2019s field began fighting, resulting in about six to eleven protesters dead.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Rudbeck|first=Jens|date=2012-10-05|title=Popular sovereignty and the historical origin of the social movement|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s11186-012-9180-x|journal=Theory and Society|volume=41|issue=6|pages=581\u2013601|doi=10.1007/s11186-012-9180-x|issn=0304-2421}}</ref> This event sparked speculation about where sovereignty lies. The rise of the Wilkes movement marked the beginning of a new phase in British politics where the notion of popular sovereignty became dominant.<ref name=\":7\" /> Wilkes and his followers consistently challenged the leading authority through actions taken outside of parliament and on the basis of contesting laws. They created something that was so new that it laid the groundwork for political struggles to come: social movements.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nThese situations, while different in nature from social movements we experience today, started the idea of mass-gathering to contest an issue. Modern examples of social movements include the Movement of the Unemployed in the 1930s, the Free Speech and Civil Rights Movements in the 1960s, the lower-profile 1990s movements and the many movements in the 21st century.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nSocial movements have evolved to a more dynamic, organized, effective, and prominent state than ever before, in part due to social movements presence on social media. The earliest online social movements began right after the Internet revolution. While the Arab Springs are commonly associated with the earliest online movements, in reality, social movements began through email. In 1990, software company Lotus and credit bureau Equifax gained access to names, addresses and purchasing behavior of 120 million Americans in CD-ROM format. In response, nearly 30,000 consumers organised through emails and message boards in protest, halting the release of the database by 1991.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gurak, Laura J.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/40927039|title=Persuasion and privacy in cyberspace : the online protests over Lotus Marketplace and the Clipper Chip.|date=1999|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-300-07864-1|oclc=40927039}}</ref>\n\nMany people have conflicting views on social media and its effectiveness when put to the task of activism. Interestingly, Pew Research Centre found that some 64% of Americans feel that the statement \u2018social media help give a voice to underrepresented groups\u2019 describes these sites very or somewhat well. But a larger share say social networking sites distract people from issues that are truly important (77% feel this way), and 71% agree with the assertion that \u2018social media makes people believe they\u2019re making a difference even when they really are not really making change.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/internet/2018/07/11/activism-in-the-social-media-age/|title=Activism in the Social Media Age|last=NW|first=1615 L. St|last2=Suite 800Washington|date=2018-07-11|website=Pew Research Center: Internet, Science & Tech|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|last3=Inquiries|first3=DC 20036USA202-419-4300 {{!}} Main202-857-8562 {{!}} Fax202-419-4372 {{!}} Media}}</ref> The debate on whether social media has added or retracted to the function of social movements as compared to historical precedence remains at the forefront of modern discussions on these issues.\n\n== Examples of Online Movements ==\n{{See also|List of social movements}}\nSocial movements advance their work through the media. It is easier, less costly as well as time-consuming to link collective behavior as real-time communication can occur vastly and simultaneously via social media.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Thompson|first1=John|title=The Media and Modernity: A Social Theory of the Media|url=https://archive.org/details/mediamodernityso00thom|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0804726795|edition=0|year=1995}}</ref> These movements exist in a range of different locales covering a wide breadth of topics.\n\n'''EXAMPLES: POLITICAL MOVEMENTS'''\n\n'''[[2009 Iranian presidential election protests]]:''' Protests against the highly controversial [[2009 Iranian presidential election|2009 Iranian presidential election results]] in support of opposition candidates [[Mir-Hossein Mousavi]] and [[Mehdi Karroubi]], occurred in major cities nationwide from 2009 into early 2010. The protests were titled '''[[Iranian Green Movement]]''' by its proponents, reflecting Mousavi's campaign theme, and Persian Awakening, Persian Spring or Green Revolution, reflecting the \"[[Persian people|Persian identity]]\" of Iranians and the so-called \"[[colour revolution]]\" theme. Protests began the night of 12 June 2009, following the announcement that incumbent President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad won nearly 63% of the vote, despite several reported irregularities.<ref>{{Citation|title=Bradshaw, Peter Nicholas, (born 19 June 1962), film critic, The Guardian, since 1999|date=2007-12-01|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.8497|work=Who's Who|publisher=Oxford University Press|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1037/e560442009-001|title=OJJDP News newsletter for May/June 2009|date=2009|website=PsycEXTRA Dataset|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yarshater|first=Ehsan|date=January 1989|title=Communication|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/00210868908701726|journal=Iranian Studies|volume=22|issue=1|pages=62\u201365|doi=10.1080/00210868908701726|issn=0021-0862}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Egyptian revolution of 2011]]:''' The Egyptian revolution of 2011, also known as the January 25 Revolution, started on 25 January 2011 and spread across [[Egypt]]. The date was set by various youth groups to coincide with the annual Egyptian \"Police holiday\" as a statement against increasing police brutality during the last few years of Mubarak's presidency. It consisted of demonstrations, marches, occupations of plazas, non-violent [[civil resistance]], acts of [[civil disobedience]] and strikes. Millions of protesters from a range of [[socio-economic]] and religious backgrounds demanded the overthrow of [[Egyptian President]] [[Hosni Mubarak]]. Violent clashes between security forces and protesters resulted in at least 846 people killed and over 6,000 injured.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u0643\u0631\u0628\u0648\u0633\u0629|first=\u0639\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0646\u064a|date=December 2017|title=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0638\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u0633\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0635\u0631\u064a \u0628\u0639\u062f \u062b\u0648\u0631\u0629 25 \u064a\u0646\u0627\u064a\u0631 2011 \u0628\u064a\u0646 \u062a\u062d\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0625\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u062d\u0643\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0633\u0643\u0631|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.12816/0045136|journal=\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0641\u0643\u0631|issue=16|pages=323\u2013343|doi=10.12816/0045136|issn=1112-8623}}</ref> Protesters retaliated by burning over 90 police stations across the country.<ref>{{Citation|title=Godwin, Joseph, (born 7 July 1964), Director, BBC Academy and BBC Birmingham, since 2015|date=2011-12-01|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.u253970|work=Who's Who|publisher=Oxford University Press|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Arab Spring]]:''' The Arab Spring was a series of anti-government protests, uprisings, and armed rebellions that spread across much of the Arab world in the early 2010s. It began in response to oppressive regimes and a low [[standard of living]], starting with protests in [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/11/feb/1080.html|title=Uprisings in the Region and Ignored Indicators|website=www.payvand.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The protests then spread to five other countries: [[Libya]], [[Egypt]], [[Yemen]], [[Syria]] and [[Bahrain]], where either the regime was toppled or major uprisings and social violence occurred, including riots, civil wars or insurgencies. Sustained street demonstrations took place in [[Morocco]], [[Iraq]], [[Algeria]], [[Iranian Khuzestan]], [[Lebanon]], [[Jordan]], [[Kuwait]], [[Oman]] and [[Sudan]]. Minor protests occurred in [[Djibouti]], [[Mauritania]], the [[Palestinian National Authority]], [[Saudi Arabia]], and the [[Southern Provinces|Moroccan-occupied Western Sahara]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ruthven|first=Malise|url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2016/06/23/how-to-understand-isis/|title=How to Understand ISIS|date=2016-06-23|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en|issn=0028-7504}}</ref>\n\n'''EXAMPLES: GENDER, RACE, SEXUALITY MOVEMENTS'''\n\n'''[[Black Lives Matter|#BlackLivesMatter]]:''' Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international [[activist]] movement, originating in the [[African-American]] community, that campaigns against violence and [[Institutional racism|systemic racism]] towards [[black people]]. BLM regularly holds [[protest]]s speaking out against [[Police use of deadly force in the United States|police killings]] of black people, and broader issues such as [[racial profiling]], [[Police brutality in the United States|police brutality]], and [[Race in the United States criminal justice system|racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/drawing-distinctions-antifa-the-alt-right-and-black-lives-matter/538320/|title=How to Distinguish Between Antifa, White Supremacists, and Black Lives Matter|last=Friedersdorf|first=Conor|date=2017-08-31|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> In 2013, the movement began with the use of the [[hashtag]] #BlackLivesMatter on [[social media]] after [[Trial of George Zimmerman|the acquittal]] of [[George Zimmerman]] in [[Shooting of Trayvon Martin|the shooting death]] of African-American teen [[Trayvon Martin]] in February 2012. The movement became nationally recognized for street demonstrations following the 2014 deaths of two African Americans.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Day|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/19/blacklivesmatter-birth-civil-rights-movement|title=#BlackLivesMatter: the birth of a new civil rights movement|date=2015-07-19|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/how-the-black-lives-matter-movement-changed-america-one-year-later/|title=How a death in Ferguson sparked a movement in America|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Me Too movement|'''#MeToo:''']] The Me Too (or #MeToo) movement, with a large variety of related local or international names, is a movement against [[sexual harassment]] and [[sexual assault]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/women/news/2018/01/31/445669/politics-policy-turning-corner-sexual-harassment/|title=From Politics to Policy: Turning the Corner on Sexual Harassment|last=Frye|first=Jocelyn|date=2018-01-31|website=Center for American Progress|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/time-person-of-the-year-2017-silence-breakers/|title=TIME Person of the Year 2017: The Silence Breakers|last=Edwards|first=Stephanie Zacharek, Eliana Dockterman, Haley Sweetland|website=Time|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/me-founder-tarana-burke-responds-asia-argento-report-1135904|title=Tarana Burke Responds to Asia Argento Report: \"There Is No Model Survivor\"|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The phrase \"Me Too\" was initially used in this context on [[social media]] in 2006, on [[Myspace]], by sexual harassment survivor and activist [[Tarana Burke]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2017/10/19/the-woman-behind-me-too-knew-the-power-of-the-phrase-when-she-created-it-10-years-ago/|title=The woman behind \u2018Me Too\u2019 knew the power of the phrase when she created it \u2014 10 years ago|last=Ohlheiser|first=Abby|date=October 19, 2017|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Similar to other social justice and empowerment movements based upon breaking silence, the purpose of \"Me Too\", as initially voiced by Burke as well as those who later adopted the tactic, is to empower women through empathy and strength in numbers, especially young and vulnerable women, by visibly demonstrating how many women have survived sexual assault and harassment, especially in the workplace.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-october-2017-htmlstory.html|title=Today in Entertainment: Wendy Williams collapses during her live show; 'House of Cards' halts production in wake of Kevin Spacey accusations|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbeshumanresourcescouncil/2017/12/20/sexual-harassment-in-the-workplace-in-a-metoo-world/|title=Council Post: Sexual Harassment In The Workplace In A #MeToo World|last=Serres|first=Nicole Smartt|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Following the exposure of the widespread [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse allegations|sexual-abuse allegations]] against [[Harvey Weinstein]] in early October 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sexual-misconduct/metoo-hashtag-becomes-anti-sexual-harassment-assault-rallying-cry-n810986|title=#MeToo: Alyssa Milano promotes hashtag that becomes anti-harassment rallying cry|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/frontline/film/weinstein/|title=Weinstein|website=FRONTLINE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> the movement began to spread [[Viral phenomenon|virally]] as a [[hashtag]] on social media.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/time-person-of-the-year-2017-silence-breakers-choice/|title=Why the Silence Breakers Are TIME's Person of the Year 2017|last=Felsenthal|first=Edward|website=Time|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Carlsen|first=Audrey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/10/23/us/metoo-replacements.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/10/23/us/metoo-replacements.html|title=#MeToo Brought Down 201 Powerful Men. Nearly Half of Their Replacements Are Women.|date=2018-10-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-11|last2=Salam|first2=Maya|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Miller|first3=Claire Cain|last4=Lu|first4=Denise|last5=Ngu|first5=Ash|last6=Patel|first6=Jugal K.|last7=Wichter|first7=Zach}}</ref>\n\n'''EXAMPLES: OTHER MOVEMENTS'''\n\n[[March for Our Lives|#MarchForOurLives:]] The '''March for Our Lives''' ('''MFOL''') was a [[Student activism|student-led]] [[Demonstration (protest)|demonstration]] in support of legislation to prevent [[gun violence in the United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marchforourlives.com/terms-of-use/|title=Terms of Use|website=March For Our Lives|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> It took place in [[Washington, D.C.]], on March 24, 2018, with over 880 sibling events throughout the [[United States]] and around the world,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325022850/https://event.marchforourlives.com/event/march-our-lives-events/search/|title=March for Our Lives|date=2018-03-25|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2018/02/18/florida-student-survivors-announce-march-for-our-lives-heres-a-time-to-talk-about-gun-control/|title=Florida student survivors announce \"March For Our Lives\": Here's a time to talk about gun control|date=2018-02-18|website=Salon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Carlsen|first=Audrey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/03/22/us/politics/march-for-lives-demonstrations.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/03/22/us/politics/march-for-lives-demonstrations.html|title=March for Our Lives: Maps of the More Than 800 Protests Around the World|date=2018-03-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-11|last2=Patel|first2=Jugal K.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/opinion/editorials/take-assault-weapons-ban-to-the-people/|title=Take assault-weapons ban to the people|date=2018-03-21|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5214706/march-for-our-lives-us-photos/|title=These Photos Show How Big the March For Our Lives Crowds Were Across The Country|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> and was planned by [[Never Again MSD]] in collaboration with the [[nonprofit organization]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cooper|first=Kelly-Leigh|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43105699|title=American teens demand 'Never Again'|date=2018-02-18|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB}}</ref> The event followed the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting|Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] a month earlier, which was described by several media outlets as a possible [[Tipping point (sociology)|tipping point]] for [[gun control]] legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2018/02/17/we-last-mass-shooting-florida-students-might-tipping-point-gun-debate/347992002/|title='We will be the last mass shooting': Florida students want to be tipping point in gun debate|last=Miller|first=Susan|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-march-for-our-lives-photographs-from-washington-dc|title=The Fearless, Outraged Young Protesters at the March for Our Lives in Washington, D.C.|last=Petrusich|first=Amanda|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5167305/florida-shooting-teachers-gun-control-activism/|title=Teachers Are Fighting for Gun Control After Parkland|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Protesters urged for [[universal background check]]s on all [[gun sale]]s, raising the federal age of gun ownership and possession to 21,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/susan-jones/activist-david-hogg-slams-republicans-cowards-stupid-sharks-want-sell-more|title=Student Gun-Control Activist David Hogg Slams Republicans As 'Cowards'|date=2018-02-28|website=CNSNews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> closing of the [[gun show loophole]], a restoration of the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban|1994 Federal Assault Weapons Ban]], and a [[High-capacity magazine ban|ban on the sale of high-capacity magazines]] and [[bump stocks]] in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/march-for-our-lives-rally-2551821925.html|title=Everything You Need to Know About the March for Our Lives|date=2018-03-23|website=PAPER|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Turnout was estimated to be between 1.2 and 2 million people in the United States,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-gun-death-murder-risk-statistics-2018-3|title=The odds that a gun will kill the average American may surprise you|last=Gould|first=Dave Mosher, Skye|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/march-our-lives-how-many-2-million-90-voting-district-860841|title=More than 2 million joined March for Our Lives protests in 90 percent of U.S. voting districts|last=EDT|first=Ryan Sit On 3/26/18 at 3:28 PM|date=2018-03-26|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/march-for-our-lives-on-the-ground-pennsylvania-avenue-81881f02-8c51-4367-9379-ed1760cbe441.html|title=Yesterday's global roar for gun control|last=Allen|first=Mike|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> making it one of the [[List of protests in the United States by size|largest protests in American history]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/3/26/17160646/march-for-our-lives-crowd-size-count|title=It\u2019s official: March for Our Lives was one of the biggest youth protests since the Vietnam War|last=Lopez|first=German|date=2018-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Impacts of Online Social Movement  ==\n\nThe impact of online movements has been substantial since the introduction of the internet. With the ever-growing medium of social media, internet activism has reached the forefront of the internet. Through the use of social networking sites such as [[Facebook]] and content-sharing sites as [[YouTube]], the opportunity for wide-scale, online social participation has increased.<ref>Rotman, D., Preece, J., Vieweg, S., Shneiderman, B., Yardi, S., Pirolli, P., Chi, E.H., Glaisyer, T. (2011). From Slacktivism to Activism: Participatory Culture in the Age of Social Media</ref>\n\n=== Benefits ===\n\nOnline social movements have been celebrated for their ability to amass large amounts of success. The online world provides the power to organise without any formal organisations, which speeds up the process of mobilisation and allows for greater scale in rapid time frames.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shirky, Clay.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/883359654|title=Here comes everybody : the power of organizing without organizations|date=2014|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-1-4406-3224-2|oclc=883359654}}</ref> This can be understood as New Power, which supports informal leadership and radical transparency, conducive for large amounts of participation by people on social media.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Heimans|first=Jeremy|url=https://hbr.org/2014/12/understanding-new-power|title=Understanding \"New Power\"|date=2014-12-01|work=Harvard Business Review|access-date=2020-04-14|last2=Timms|first2=Henry|issue=December 2014|issn=0017-8012}}</ref> Previously, the dominant form of old power limited participation in movements and leadership to a small group.<ref name=\":0\" /> Rapid mobilisation helps people overcome pluralistic ignorance, where individuals believe that they are the only person with a particular view. Instead, the online networked sphere helps reveal otherwise preferences to each other in order to discover common ground.<ref>{{Cite book|last=TUFEKCI, ZEYNEP.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1002689516|title=TWITTER AND TEAR GAS : the power and fragility of networked protest.|date=2018|publisher=YALE University Press|isbn=0-300-23417-1|oclc=1002689516}}</ref>\u00a0 The increased visibility of a movement on the internet supports a sense of camaraderie, setting and maintaining a cause, even if it is otherwise decentralised. Social media can overcome pluralistic ignorance,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Mina, An Xiao, 1983-|title=Memes to movements : how the world's most viral media is changing social protest and power|date=8 January 2019|isbn=978-0-8070-5658-5|location=Boston|oclc=1039236703}}</ref> which is the belief that your opinions are not shared by others, when in reality, they tend to be. The online world enables the synchronisation of opinions across disparate geographies, creating new norms of behavior and belief through regular repetition and affirmation of messages.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the political sphere, active online groups increase political participation by providing a framework for discussion, leading petitions, and collecting donations in order to further a political agenda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scholarsstrategynetwork.org/brief/how-social-movements-are-using-internet-change-politics|title=How Social Movements are Using the Internet to Change Politics {{!}} Scholars Strategy Network|website=www.scholarsstrategynetwork.org|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref> This alignment of values has often results in the potential to organise, such as fund raising in the ALS Ice Bucket Challenge that raised $100 million in just 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alsa.org/news/media/press-releases/ice-bucket-challenge-082914.html|title=The ALS Association Expresses Sincere Gratitude to Over Three Million Donors|website=ALSA.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-14}}</ref>\nOnline movements are able to sustain attention across boundaries, physical and temporal. For instance, during the Egyptian Revolution in 2011, Facebook\u2019s event function allowed for people to organise protests, which would then be acted out upon in real-life. Similarly, the Occupy movement was able to gather an online following around the world through the Tumblr blog, titled \u201cWe are the 99%\u201d. The function of being able to post on a shared website supported the gathering of different narratives, unifying people. In fact, online social movements epitomises the notion of \u201cmany yeses, one no\u201d.<ref name=\":2\" /> This motto highlights how the online world brings together diverse voices against something they all feel strongly about, by acting as integrating screens since people use these devices to connect with others, rather than to isolate themselves. In many ways, social media has created networks conducive for unification across different identities, supporting intersectional approaches to fighting injustice. For instance, the [[Zapatistas]] attempted to emphasise their inclusivity of the movement, which had begun as somewhat of a peasants revolt. The leader of the movement, Marcos, was famously presented in numerous identities, of different exploited and marginalised minorities who are saying \u201cEnough\u201d to their situation:<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Marcos|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/professionals-of-hope-the-selected-writings-of-subcomandante-marcos/oclc/1004260843|title=Professionals of hope: the selected writings of Subcomandante Marcos|last2=Jauregui|first2=Gabriela|date=2017|isbn=978-0-9967786-5-7|oclc=1004260843}}</ref><blockquote>\u201cYes, Marcos is gay. Marcos is gay in San Francisco, black in South Africa, an Asian in Europe, a Chicano in San Ysidro, an anarchist in Spain, a Palestinian in Israel, a Mayan Indian in the streets of San Cristobal, a Jew in Germany, a Gypsy in Poland, a Mohawk in Quebec, a pacifist in Bosnia, a single woman on the subway at 10pm, a peasant without land, a gang member in the slums, an unemployed worker, an unhappy student and, of course, a Zapatista in the mountains. Marcos is all the exploited, marginalised, oppressed minorities resisting and saying 'Enough.' He is every minority who is now beginning to speak, and every majority that must shut up and listen. He is every untolerated group searching for a way to speak. Everything that makes power and the good consciences of those in power uncomfortable\u2014this is Marcos.\u201d -Subcommandant Marcos, from Social Justice E-Zine #27 <ref name=\":3\" /></blockquote>Social media is also able to provide a creative milieu that is conducive for narrative building. Memes, in particular, have proven to be a useful tool when it comes to repeat certain ideas so that they enter the public consciousness and are able to retain attention. Often, the large numbers of people online allow for intentional overproduction.<ref name=\":2\" /> Amanda D. Lotz noted that this is a key strategy, where multiple shows and commercials are created in order to compete, so that the most effective version can succeed, while the others disappear.<ref name=\":2\" /> In online social movements, hashtag culture functions by having many people copy each other and come up with new permutations, allowing for the most successful version to spread.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSocial media platforms are harder to censor than real-life organisation of movements. Ethan Zuckerman advanced the [[Cute cat theory of digital activism|Cute Cat Theory of Digital Activism]], which explains the relative lack of censorship online. Zuckerman posits that the web is used primarily for innocuous purposes, such as connecting with families and friends and posting pictures of cats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethanzuckerman.com/blog/2007/12/03/cute-cat-theory-the-china-corollary/|title=Cute Cat Theory: The China Corollary {{!}} \u2026 My heart\u2019s in Accra|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> However, the affordances that social media provides activists nurtures a community that engages in political criticism. Still, these activists are able to hide behind the largely mundane uses of the internet, since censorship by governments would appear especially draconian. For instance, the Twitter ban in Turkey by Prime Minister Tayyip Erdogan who intended to \u201cwipe out\u201d the social media platform was met with furious outrage from the population, experts and the global community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-election-idUSBREA2K0NK20140321|title=Furious reaction, political split after Turkey bans Twitter|date=2014-03-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en}}</ref> Similarly when ex-Tunisian President Ben Ali attempted to ban Facebook in 2010, his move backfired because so many Tunisians used Facebook to connect with family, friends and acquaintances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/01/12/the-limits-of-silencing-tunisia/|title=The limits of silencing Tunisia|last=Bounenni|first=Bassam|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Detriments ===\n\nNevertheless, there are numerous critiques posed against online social movements.\n\nMost frequently, the limited capacity for tangible change is often raised. For social movements to be successful, there need to be network internalities, which are durable networks ideal for organised action.<ref name=\":2\" /> These networks are the result of long-term challenges that are collectively overcome, which supports trust building. This process requires the investment of time and energy in order for members of a social movement to learn how to cooperate to achieve their goals.\n\nZeynep Tufekci introduces the Mount Everest metaphor in her comparison of the [[Civil Rights Movement]]\u2019s achievements with the [[Arab Spring]]\u2019s relative limited scope of change, especially in Egypt.<ref name=\":2\" /> Zeynep draws a comparison between social media and Sherpas. Previously, climbing Mount Everest was a challenging task. However, with Sherpas, more people were capable of doing so, and this led to a spike in mountaineering tourism. Nevertheless, these individuals remained unprepared for the reality of scaling the mountain, resulting in a spike in deaths. Similarly, social media has enabled more social movements to spread and enter the public sphere. However, there has not been long-term training and building of network internalities which is necessary to sustain these movements.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Civil Rights Movement had undergone strenuous planning and organisation, which has resulted in leaders who were able to represent the cause, such as Martin Luther King. In contrast, online social movements tend to be more short-lived. For instance, [[Kony 2012]] brought attention to child soldiers being forced into Joseph Kony\u2019s [[Lord\u2019s Resistance Army]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/03/problem-stop-kony/330661/|title=The Problems with 'Stop Kony'|last=Abad-Santos|first=Alexander|date=2012-03-08|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> However, the small organisation that directed the video, Invisible Children, was incapable of managing the sheer volume of attention received. Without the network internalities present in the Civil Rights Movement, the director [[Jason Russell]] had a major breakdown and the social movement dissipated.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Curtis|first=Polly|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/apr/19/kony-2012-nirvana-missed-chance|title=Kony 2012: nirvana of online campaigning or missed chance?|date=2012-04-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThere is also the concern of a lack of clear leadership in online social movements. This means that there might be a challenge in finding representatives to negotiate within the movement and with adversaries. These individuals might have little in common beyond the initial movement. For instance, [[Tahrir Square]] protesters could not deviate tactically from their initial demand, which was to overthrow the Hosni Mubarak regime. Hence, there was a tactical freeze, where tactics could not be adjusted and new demands were not articulated by the social movement. Even the creator of \u201cWe are All Khaled Said\u201d, the main Facebook page of the Egyptian Revolution, Wael Ghonim was in no position to concede anything. Ghonim was neither an elected leader, nor an informal one, which denied him legitimacy to engage in negotiations.<ref name=\":2\" /> Similarly, in the [[Occupy movement]], there was an attempt to empower all protestors to be leaders of the movement. However, as a \u201cleaderful\u201d movement, there was a lack of ability to identify a clear representative to negotiate since there were too many perspectives.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Costanza-Chock|first=Sasha|date=2012-08-01|title=Mic Check! Media Cultures and the Occupy Movement|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/14742837.2012.710746|journal=Social Movement Studies|volume=11|issue=3-4|pages=375\u2013385|doi=10.1080/14742837.2012.710746|issn=1474-2837}}</ref>\n\nOnline social movements, while effective in unifying people, might also amplify the tendency to tribalism. In particular, more people having access to social media might democratise the risk of promoting violence, especially where institutions are not stable and there can be large amounts of distrust and disinformation. For instance, while social media had helped Sri Lanka ease the path to its first democratic elections in 2015 after years of civil war, communal hatreds began to overrun the news feeds, which are the primary portal of news and information for many users.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Taub|first=Amanda|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/21/world/asia/facebook-sri-lanka-riots.html|title=Where Countries Are Tinderboxes and Facebook Is a Match|date=2018-04-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|last2=Fisher|first2=Max|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== The Future ==\n\nAlthough the future of online movements is hard to predict, there are some clear directions where they could certainly lead towards. [[Vanessa DiMauro]], a community builder and researcher in decision-making, believes that the biggest trend concerning online communities in the near future is private online communities. While these large networks that we encounter and use on a daily basis have provided us with a productive and collaborative experience, they have also increased to unmanageable sizes. To become a learning environment, these groups need to be much smaller and manageable. This is where the idea and trend of private online communities could potentially be the future of online communities.<ref>[[Vanessa DiMauro|DiMauro, V.]] (2011). The Future Of Online Community. Retrieved from http://www.leadernetworks.com/2011/10/future-of-online-community.html</ref>\n\n== Online Social Movements and Commercial Social Media Platforms ==\nSince the late 2000s, increased use of commercial social media platforms by social movements has been reported. According to Lopes, \"Social Media websites such as Facebook, Twitter, YouTube, and the various online blogs have arguably given a voice to individuals that otherwise would not be heard.\" [https://www.creighton.edu/fileadmin/user/CCAS/departments/PoliticalScience/Journal_of_Political_Research__JPR_/2014_JSP_papers/Lopes_JPR.pdf] However, the adoption of these commercial platforms has concerned analysts as they highlighted asymmetrical relationships between the for-profit aims of social media and the copy-left values that drive many online movements. According to Fenton, \"Claims for the extension and re-invention of activism need to be considered in the context of the material social and political world of inequality, injustice and corporate dominance.\"[http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/1742766507086852] For example, \"in his analysis of the Purple Movement (Popolo Viola) in Italy and its extensive use of Facebook, [http://westminsterresearch.wmin.ac.uk/14714/ Coretti (2014)] demonstrates that, while the myth of the network as open and inclusive persists, it acts as a disguise for the communication protocols of commercial social networking platforms that may well enable large-scale mobilization but ultimately, through their very functionality, encourage organizational centralization and fragmentation in social movements\" (Fenton, 2016, p.&nbsp;184).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Misunderstanding-the-Internet-2nd-Edition/Curran-Fenton-Freedman/p/book/9781138906228|title=Misunderstanding the Internet: 2nd Edition (Paperback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> The proprietary nature of the design of platforms such as Facebook pages fails to provide movements with the necessary instruments in terms of a shared democratic management of their resources. Moreover, the inability to manage Facebook pages and groups according to commonly agreed values promotes vertical power structures within movements, contributing to controversial management of Facebook pages and to internal divisions that significantly hinder the potential of protest.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coretti|first=Lorenzo|date=June 2015|title=The rise and fall of collective identity in networked movements: communication protocols, Facebook, and the anti-Berlusconi protest|journal=Information, Communication & Society|volume=18|issue=8|pages=951\u2013967|doi=10.1080/1369118X.2015.1043317}}</ref>\n\n== Important figures ==\n* [[Shaun King]]; a Twitter-based civil rights activist. \n* [[DeRay Mckesson|DeRay McKesson]]; Twitter- and Instagram-based civil rights activist, known for his involvement in the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement.\n* [[Colin Kaepernick]]; American football quarterback known for his involvement in the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement and causing controversy for kneeling rather than standing for the national anthem, a symbolic act in protest of the unjust and oppressive treatment of people of color in the United States.\n* [[Rachel Dolezal]]; civil rights activist that caused controversy after her Caucasian parents disclosed that she was a Caucasian woman passing as black.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/13/us/rachel-dolezal-naacp-president-accused-of-lying-about-her-race.html|title=Black or White? Woman's Story Stirs Up a Furor|last=P\u00e9rez-pe\u00f1a|first=Richard|date=2015-06-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-13|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Received backlash on various social media platforms for claiming she was a victim of hate crimes as an African American woman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3921964/rachel-dolezal-howard-university/|title=Rachel Dolezal Will Break Her Silence on Tuesday|website=Time|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref>\n* [[Van Jones]]; civil rights activist and creator of various initiatives such as #YesWeCode, which is meant to give aid to minorities in technology fields.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Slacktivism]]\n* [[Internet activism]]\n* [[Accelerated pluralism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Social movements]]\n[[Category:Internet activism]]\n", "text_old": "Social movements are loosely organised efforts to push for a particular goal.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/260204710|title=A dictionary of sociology|date=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Scott, John, 1949-, Marshall, Gordon.|isbn=978-0-19-953300-8|edition=3rd ed. rev|location=Oxford|oclc=260204710}}</ref> In many cases, these movements seek to counter the mainstream public, claiming there is a wrong that ought to be righted.<ref name=\":2\">Tufekci, Zeynep. {{Citation|last=|first=|title=Twitter and Tear Gas The Power and Fragility of Networked Protest.|date=2017|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/989057566|volume=|pages=|others=|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-21512-0|oclc=|access-date=}}</ref> The first social movements occurred through protests and civil disobedience, but with the rise of the internet, social movements have gone online. Online social movements have since gained momentum in the 20th and 21st century. The organisational structures and strategies behind social movements have changed as a result of the online world, utilizing technology and the internet to mobilize more people in a shorter period of time.\n\n[[Online community|Online communities]] build off [[social movement]]s, enabling the connection of persons worldwide to develop a base and gain awareness of issues. Online social movements gained momentum in the late 20th century and early 21st century<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobilizingideas.wordpress.com/2012/08/01/social-movements-how-people-make-history/|title=Social Movements: How People Make History|last=Ideas|first=Mobilizing|date=2012-08-01|website=Mobilizing Ideas|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref> as new generations sought social change. With access to the internet and the fast-growing [[World Wide Web]], online social movements brought awareness to issues both political and social. Online social movements have been praised and criticized; the former for its ability to raise awareness to important causes, and the latter for its ability to perpetuate problems like [[slacktivism]]. Although online activism has received criticism, it has had real impacts on social movements.\n\n====== History of Online Social Movements ======\nThe earliest social movements were minimally related to the internet. For instance, Charles Tilly recognizes the first social movements in Britain and the US in the 1750s and 1760s, after the 7 Years War. [[John Wilkes]] led the \"Wilkes and Liberty\" movement to achieve legal and parliamentary reform. Across the Atlantic, the Boston merchants and the activists in the [[Sons of Liberty]] initiated the opposition to the British that eventually lead to the Declaration of Independence in 1776.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Tilly, Charles 1929-2008 Verfasser.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1126812829|title=Social movements, 1768-2018|isbn=978-0-367-07607-8|oclc=1126812829}}</ref>\n\nThe mentality behind these was spurred on by sovereignty within British politics through the Reformation and informed John Wilkes and his followers about alternative societal rule. Thus, in 1768, members of the English lower class began to mobilize underneath Wilkes\u2019 movement against the sovereignty of the ruling class.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Cash, Arthur.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/952732211|title=John Wilkes : the Scandalous Father of Civil Liberty.|date=2008|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-300-10871-0|oclc=952732211}}</ref> On May 10, 1768, Wilkes\u2019 supporters and the king\u2019s soldiers at St. George\u2019s field began fighting, resulting in about six to eleven protesters dead.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Rudbeck|first=Jens|date=2012-10-05|title=Popular sovereignty and the historical origin of the social movement|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s11186-012-9180-x|journal=Theory and Society|volume=41|issue=6|pages=581\u2013601|doi=10.1007/s11186-012-9180-x|issn=0304-2421}}</ref> This event sparked speculation about where sovereignty lies. The rise of the Wilkes movement marked the beginning of a new phase in British politics where the notion of popular sovereignty became dominant.<ref name=\":7\" /> Wilkes and his followers consistently challenged the leading authority through actions taken outside of parliament and on the basis of contesting laws. They created something that was so new that it laid the groundwork for political struggles to come: social movements.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nThese situations, while different in nature from social movements we experience today, started the idea of mass-gathering to contest an issue. Modern examples of social movements include the Movement of the Unemployed in the 1930s, the Free Speech and Civil Rights Movements in the 1960s, the lower-profile 1990s movements and the many movements in the 21st century.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nSocial movements have evolved to a more dynamic, organized, effective, and prominent state than ever before, in part due to social movements presence on social media. The earliest online social movements began right after the Internet revolution. While the Arab Springs are commonly associated with the earliest online movements, in reality, social movements began through email. In 1990, software company Lotus and credit bureau Equifax gained access to names, addresses and purchasing behavior of 120 million Americans in CD-ROM format. In response, nearly 30,000 consumers organised through emails and message boards in protest, halting the release of the database by 1991.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gurak, Laura J.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/40927039|title=Persuasion and privacy in cyberspace : the online protests over Lotus Marketplace and the Clipper Chip.|date=1999|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-300-07864-1|oclc=40927039}}</ref>\n\nMany people have conflicting views on social media and its effectiveness when put to the task of activism. Interestingly, Pew Research Centre found that some 64% of Americans feel that the statement \u2018social media help give a voice to underrepresented groups\u2019 describes these sites very or somewhat well. But a larger share say social networking sites distract people from issues that are truly important (77% feel this way), and 71% agree with the assertion that \u2018social media makes people believe they\u2019re making a difference even when they really are not really making change.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/internet/2018/07/11/activism-in-the-social-media-age/|title=Activism in the Social Media Age|last=NW|first=1615 L. St|last2=Suite 800Washington|date=2018-07-11|website=Pew Research Center: Internet, Science & Tech|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|last3=Inquiries|first3=DC 20036USA202-419-4300 {{!}} Main202-857-8562 {{!}} Fax202-419-4372 {{!}} Media}}</ref> The debate on whether social media has added or retracted to the function of social movements as compared to historical precedence remains at the forefront of modern discussions on these issues.\n\n== Examples of Online Movements ==\n{{See also|List of social movements}}\nSocial movements advance their work through the media. It is easier, less costly as well as time-consuming to link collective behavior as real-time communication can occur vastly and simultaneously via social media.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Thompson|first1=John|title=The Media and Modernity: A Social Theory of the Media|url=https://archive.org/details/mediamodernityso00thom|url-access=registration|isbn=978-0804726795|edition=0|year=1995}}</ref> These movements exist in a range of different locales covering a wide breadth of topics.\n\n'''EXAMPLES: POLITICAL MOVEMENTS'''\n\n'''[[2009 Iranian presidential election protests]]:''' Protests against the highly controversial [[2009 Iranian presidential election|2009 Iranian presidential election results]] in support of opposition candidates [[Mir-Hossein Mousavi]] and [[Mehdi Karroubi]], occurred in major cities nationwide from 2009 into early 2010. The protests were titled '''[[Iranian Green Movement]]''' by its proponents, reflecting Mousavi's campaign theme, and Persian Awakening, Persian Spring or Green Revolution, reflecting the \"[[Persian people|Persian identity]]\" of Iranians and the so-called \"[[colour revolution]]\" theme. Protests began the night of 12 June 2009, following the announcement that incumbent President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad won nearly 63% of the vote, despite several reported irregularities.<ref>{{Citation|title=Bradshaw, Peter Nicholas, (born 19 June 1962), film critic, The Guardian, since 1999|date=2007-12-01|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.8497|work=Who's Who|publisher=Oxford University Press|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1037/e560442009-001|title=OJJDP News newsletter for May/June 2009|date=2009|website=PsycEXTRA Dataset|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yarshater|first=Ehsan|date=January 1989|title=Communication|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/00210868908701726|journal=Iranian Studies|volume=22|issue=1|pages=62\u201365|doi=10.1080/00210868908701726|issn=0021-0862}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Egyptian revolution of 2011]]:''' The Egyptian revolution of 2011, also known as the January 25 Revolution, started on 25 January 2011 and spread across [[Egypt]]. The date was set by various youth groups to coincide with the annual Egyptian \"Police holiday\" as a statement against increasing police brutality during the last few years of Mubarak's presidency. It consisted of demonstrations, marches, occupations of plazas, non-violent [[civil resistance]], acts of [[civil disobedience]] and strikes. Millions of protesters from a range of [[socio-economic]] and religious backgrounds demanded the overthrow of [[Egyptian President]] [[Hosni Mubarak]]. Violent clashes between security forces and protesters resulted in at least 846 people killed and over 6,000 injured.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u0643\u0631\u0628\u0648\u0633\u0629|first=\u0639\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0646\u064a|date=December 2017|title=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0638\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u0633\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0635\u0631\u064a \u0628\u0639\u062f \u062b\u0648\u0631\u0629 25 \u064a\u0646\u0627\u064a\u0631 2011 \u0628\u064a\u0646 \u062a\u062d\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0625\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u062d\u0643\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0633\u0643\u0631|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.12816/0045136|journal=\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0641\u0643\u0631|issue=16|pages=323\u2013343|doi=10.12816/0045136|issn=1112-8623}}</ref> Protesters retaliated by burning over 90 police stations across the country.<ref>{{Citation|title=Godwin, Joseph, (born 7 July 1964), Director, BBC Academy and BBC Birmingham, since 2015|date=2011-12-01|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.u253970|work=Who's Who|publisher=Oxford University Press|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Arab Spring]]:''' The Arab Spring was a series of anti-government protests, uprisings, and armed rebellions that spread across much of the Arab world in the early 2010s. It began in response to oppressive regimes and a low [[standard of living]], starting with protests in [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/11/feb/1080.html|title=Uprisings in the Region and Ignored Indicators|website=www.payvand.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The protests then spread to five other countries: [[Libya]], [[Egypt]], [[Yemen]], [[Syria]] and [[Bahrain]], where either the regime was toppled or major uprisings and social violence occurred, including riots, civil wars or insurgencies. Sustained street demonstrations took place in [[Morocco]], [[Iraq]], [[Algeria]], [[Iranian Khuzestan]], [[Lebanon]], [[Jordan]], [[Kuwait]], [[Oman]] and [[Sudan]]. Minor protests occurred in [[Djibouti]], [[Mauritania]], the [[Palestinian National Authority]], [[Saudi Arabia]], and the [[Southern Provinces|Moroccan-occupied Western Sahara]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ruthven|first=Malise|url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2016/06/23/how-to-understand-isis/|title=How to Understand ISIS|date=2016-06-23|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en|issn=0028-7504}}</ref>\n\n'''EXAMPLES: GENDER, RACE, SEXUALITY MOVEMENTS'''\n\n'''[[Black Lives Matter|#BlackLivesMatter]]:''' Black Lives Matter (BLM) is an international [[activist]] movement, originating in the [[African-American]] community, that campaigns against violence and [[Institutional racism|systemic racism]] towards [[black people]]. BLM regularly holds [[protest]]s speaking out against [[Police use of deadly force in the United States|police killings]] of black people, and broader issues such as [[racial profiling]], [[Police brutality in the United States|police brutality]], and [[Race in the United States criminal justice system|racial inequality in the United States criminal justice system]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/drawing-distinctions-antifa-the-alt-right-and-black-lives-matter/538320/|title=How to Distinguish Between Antifa, White Supremacists, and Black Lives Matter|last=Friedersdorf|first=Conor|date=2017-08-31|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> In 2013, the movement began with the use of the [[hashtag]] #BlackLivesMatter on [[social media]] after [[Trial of George Zimmerman|the acquittal]] of [[George Zimmerman]] in [[Shooting of Trayvon Martin|the shooting death]] of African-American teen [[Trayvon Martin]] in February 2012. The movement became nationally recognized for street demonstrations following the 2014 deaths of two African Americans.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Day|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jul/19/blacklivesmatter-birth-civil-rights-movement|title=#BlackLivesMatter: the birth of a new civil rights movement|date=2015-07-19|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/how-the-black-lives-matter-movement-changed-america-one-year-later/|title=How a death in Ferguson sparked a movement in America|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Me Too movement|'''#MeToo:''']] The Me Too (or #MeToo) movement, with a large variety of related local or international names, is a movement against [[sexual harassment]] and [[sexual assault]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/women/news/2018/01/31/445669/politics-policy-turning-corner-sexual-harassment/|title=From Politics to Policy: Turning the Corner on Sexual Harassment|last=Frye|first=Jocelyn|date=2018-01-31|website=Center for American Progress|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/time-person-of-the-year-2017-silence-breakers/|title=TIME Person of the Year 2017: The Silence Breakers|last=Edwards|first=Stephanie Zacharek, Eliana Dockterman, Haley Sweetland|website=Time|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/me-founder-tarana-burke-responds-asia-argento-report-1135904|title=Tarana Burke Responds to Asia Argento Report: \"There Is No Model Survivor\"|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The phrase \"Me Too\" was initially used in this context on [[social media]] in 2006, on [[Myspace]], by sexual harassment survivor and activist [[Tarana Burke]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2017/10/19/the-woman-behind-me-too-knew-the-power-of-the-phrase-when-she-created-it-10-years-ago/|title=The woman behind \u2018Me Too\u2019 knew the power of the phrase when she created it \u2014 10 years ago|last=Ohlheiser|first=Abby|date=October 19, 2017|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Similar to other social justice and empowerment movements based upon breaking silence, the purpose of \"Me Too\", as initially voiced by Burke as well as those who later adopted the tactic, is to empower women through empathy and strength in numbers, especially young and vulnerable women, by visibly demonstrating how many women have survived sexual assault and harassment, especially in the workplace.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-october-2017-htmlstory.html|title=Today in Entertainment: Wendy Williams collapses during her live show; 'House of Cards' halts production in wake of Kevin Spacey accusations|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbeshumanresourcescouncil/2017/12/20/sexual-harassment-in-the-workplace-in-a-metoo-world/|title=Council Post: Sexual Harassment In The Workplace In A #MeToo World|last=Serres|first=Nicole Smartt|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Following the exposure of the widespread [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse allegations|sexual-abuse allegations]] against [[Harvey Weinstein]] in early October 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/sexual-misconduct/metoo-hashtag-becomes-anti-sexual-harassment-assault-rallying-cry-n810986|title=#MeToo: Alyssa Milano promotes hashtag that becomes anti-harassment rallying cry|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/frontline/film/weinstein/|title=Weinstein|website=FRONTLINE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> the movement began to spread [[Viral phenomenon|virally]] as a [[hashtag]] on social media.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/time-person-of-the-year-2017-silence-breakers-choice/|title=Why the Silence Breakers Are TIME's Person of the Year 2017|last=Felsenthal|first=Edward|website=Time|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Carlsen|first=Audrey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/10/23/us/metoo-replacements.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/10/23/us/metoo-replacements.html|title=#MeToo Brought Down 201 Powerful Men. Nearly Half of Their Replacements Are Women.|date=2018-10-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-11|last2=Salam|first2=Maya|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Miller|first3=Claire Cain|last4=Lu|first4=Denise|last5=Ngu|first5=Ash|last6=Patel|first6=Jugal K.|last7=Wichter|first7=Zach}}</ref>\n\n'''EXAMPLES: OTHER MOVEMENTS'''\n\n[[March for Our Lives|#MarchForOurLives:]] The '''March for Our Lives''' ('''MFOL''') was a [[Student activism|student-led]] [[Demonstration (protest)|demonstration]] in support of legislation to prevent [[gun violence in the United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marchforourlives.com/terms-of-use/|title=Terms of Use|website=March For Our Lives|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> It took place in [[Washington, D.C.]], on March 24, 2018, with over 880 sibling events throughout the [[United States]] and around the world,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325022850/https://event.marchforourlives.com/event/march-our-lives-events/search/|title=March for Our Lives|date=2018-03-25|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2018/02/18/florida-student-survivors-announce-march-for-our-lives-heres-a-time-to-talk-about-gun-control/|title=Florida student survivors announce \"March For Our Lives\": Here's a time to talk about gun control|date=2018-02-18|website=Salon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Carlsen|first=Audrey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/03/22/us/politics/march-for-lives-demonstrations.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/03/22/us/politics/march-for-lives-demonstrations.html|title=March for Our Lives: Maps of the More Than 800 Protests Around the World|date=2018-03-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-11|last2=Patel|first2=Jugal K.|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/opinion/editorials/take-assault-weapons-ban-to-the-people/|title=Take assault-weapons ban to the people|date=2018-03-21|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5214706/march-for-our-lives-us-photos/|title=These Photos Show How Big the March For Our Lives Crowds Were Across The Country|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> and was planned by [[Never Again MSD]] in collaboration with the [[nonprofit organization]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cooper|first=Kelly-Leigh|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-43105699|title=American teens demand 'Never Again'|date=2018-02-18|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB}}</ref> The event followed the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting|Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] a month earlier, which was described by several media outlets as a possible [[Tipping point (sociology)|tipping point]] for [[gun control]] legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2018/02/17/we-last-mass-shooting-florida-students-might-tipping-point-gun-debate/347992002/|title='We will be the last mass shooting': Florida students want to be tipping point in gun debate|last=Miller|first=Susan|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-march-for-our-lives-photographs-from-washington-dc|title=The Fearless, Outraged Young Protesters at the March for Our Lives in Washington, D.C.|last=Petrusich|first=Amanda|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5167305/florida-shooting-teachers-gun-control-activism/|title=Teachers Are Fighting for Gun Control After Parkland|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Protesters urged for [[universal background check]]s on all [[gun sale]]s, raising the federal age of gun ownership and possession to 21,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/susan-jones/activist-david-hogg-slams-republicans-cowards-stupid-sharks-want-sell-more|title=Student Gun-Control Activist David Hogg Slams Republicans As 'Cowards'|date=2018-02-28|website=CNSNews.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> closing of the [[gun show loophole]], a restoration of the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban|1994 Federal Assault Weapons Ban]], and a [[High-capacity magazine ban|ban on the sale of high-capacity magazines]] and [[bump stocks]] in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.papermag.com/march-for-our-lives-rally-2551821925.html|title=Everything You Need to Know About the March for Our Lives|date=2018-03-23|website=PAPER|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> Turnout was estimated to be between 1.2 and 2 million people in the United States,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-gun-death-murder-risk-statistics-2018-3|title=The odds that a gun will kill the average American may surprise you|last=Gould|first=Dave Mosher, Skye|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/march-our-lives-how-many-2-million-90-voting-district-860841|title=More than 2 million joined March for Our Lives protests in 90 percent of U.S. voting districts|last=EDT|first=Ryan Sit On 3/26/18 at 3:28 PM|date=2018-03-26|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/march-for-our-lives-on-the-ground-pennsylvania-avenue-81881f02-8c51-4367-9379-ed1760cbe441.html|title=Yesterday's global roar for gun control|last=Allen|first=Mike|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> making it one of the [[List of protests in the United States by size|largest protests in American history]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/3/26/17160646/march-for-our-lives-crowd-size-count|title=It\u2019s official: March for Our Lives was one of the biggest youth protests since the Vietnam War|last=Lopez|first=German|date=2018-03-26|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Impacts of Online Social Movement  ==\n\nThe impact of online movements has been substantial since the introduction of the internet. With the ever-growing medium of social media, internet activism has reached the forefront of the internet. Through the use of social networking sites such as [[Facebook]] and content-sharing sites as [[YouTube]], the opportunity for wide-scale, online social participation has increased.<ref>Rotman, D., Preece, J., Vieweg, S., Shneiderman, B., Yardi, S., Pirolli, P., Chi, E.H., Glaisyer, T. (2011). From Slacktivism to Activism: Participatory Culture in the Age of Social Media</ref>\n\n=== Benefits ===\n\nOnline social movements have been celebrated for their ability to amass large amounts of success. The online world provides the power to organise without any formal organisations, which speeds up the process of mobilisation and allows for greater scale in rapid time frames.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shirky, Clay.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/883359654|title=Here comes everybody : the power of organizing without organizations|date=2014|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-1-4406-3224-2|oclc=883359654}}</ref> This can be understood as New Power, which supports informal leadership and radical transparency, conducive for large amounts of participation by people on social media.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Heimans|first=Jeremy|url=https://hbr.org/2014/12/understanding-new-power|title=Understanding \"New Power\"|date=2014-12-01|work=Harvard Business Review|access-date=2020-04-14|last2=Timms|first2=Henry|issue=December 2014|issn=0017-8012}}</ref> Previously, the dominant form of old power limited participation in movements and leadership to a small group.<ref name=\":0\" /> Rapid mobilisation helps people overcome pluralistic ignorance, where individuals believe that they are the only person with a particular view. Instead, the online networked sphere helps reveal otherwise preferences to each other in order to discover common ground.<ref>{{Cite book|last=TUFEKCI, ZEYNEP.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1002689516|title=TWITTER AND TEAR GAS : the power and fragility of networked protest.|date=2018|publisher=YALE University Press|isbn=0-300-23417-1|oclc=1002689516}}</ref>\u00a0 The increased visibility of a movement on the internet supports a sense of camaraderie, setting and maintaining a cause, even if it is otherwise decentralised. Social media can overcome pluralistic ignorance,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Mina, An Xiao, 1983-|title=Memes to movements : how the world's most viral media is changing social protest and power|date=8 January 2019|isbn=978-0-8070-5658-5|location=Boston|oclc=1039236703}}</ref> which is the belief that your opinions are not shared by others, when in reality, they tend to be. The online world enables the synchronisation of opinions across disparate geographies, creating new norms of behavior and belief through regular repetition and affirmation of messages.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the political sphere, active online groups increase political participation by providing a framework for discussion, leading petitions, and collecting donations in order to further a political agenda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scholarsstrategynetwork.org/brief/how-social-movements-are-using-internet-change-politics|title=How Social Movements are Using the Internet to Change Politics {{!}} Scholars Strategy Network|website=www.scholarsstrategynetwork.org|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref> This alignment of values has often results in the potential to organise, such as fund raising in the ALS Ice Bucket Challenge that raised $100 million in just 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alsa.org/news/media/press-releases/ice-bucket-challenge-082914.html|title=The ALS Association Expresses Sincere Gratitude to Over Three Million Donors|website=ALSA.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-14}}</ref>\nOnline movements are able to sustain attention across boundaries, physical and temporal. For instance, during the Egyptian Revolution in 2011, Facebook\u2019s event function allowed for people to organise protests, which would then be acted out upon in real-life. Similarly, the Occupy movement was able to gather an online following around the world through the Tumblr blog, titled \u201cWe are the 99%\u201d. The function of being able to post on a shared website supported the gathering of different narratives, unifying people. In fact, online social movements epitomises the notion of \u201cmany yeses, one no\u201d.<ref name=\":2\" /> This motto highlights how the online world brings together diverse voices against something they all feel strongly about, by acting as integrating screens since people use these devices to connect with others, rather than to isolate themselves. In many ways, social media has created networks conducive for unification across different identities, supporting intersectional approaches to fighting injustice. For instance, the [[Zapatistas]] attempted to emphasise their inclusivity of the movement, which had begun as somewhat of a peasants revolt. The leader of the movement, Marcos, was famously presented in numerous identities, of different exploited and marginalised minorities who are saying \u201cEnough\u201d to their situation:<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Marcos|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/professionals-of-hope-the-selected-writings-of-subcomandante-marcos/oclc/1004260843|title=Professionals of hope: the selected writings of Subcomandante Marcos|last2=Jauregui|first2=Gabriela|date=2017|isbn=978-0-9967786-5-7|oclc=1004260843}}</ref><blockquote>\u201cYes, Marcos is gay. Marcos is gay in San Francisco, black in South Africa, an Asian in Europe, a Chicano in San Ysidro, an anarchist in Spain, a Palestinian in Israel, a Mayan Indian in the streets of San Cristobal, a Jew in Germany, a Gypsy in Poland, a Mohawk in Quebec, a pacifist in Bosnia, a single woman on the subway at 10pm, a peasant without land, a gang member in the slums, an unemployed worker, an unhappy student and, of course, a Zapatista in the mountains. Marcos is all the exploited, marginalised, oppressed minorities resisting and saying 'Enough.' He is every minority who is now beginning to speak, and every majority that must shut up and listen. He is every untolerated group searching for a way to speak. Everything that makes power and the good consciences of those in power uncomfortable\u2014this is Marcos.\u201d -Subcommandant Marcos, from Social Justice E-Zine #27 <ref name=\":3\" /></blockquote>Social media is also able to provide a creative milieu that is conducive for narrative building. Memes, in particular, have proven to be a useful tool when it comes to repeat certain ideas so that they enter the public consciousness and are able to retain attention. Often, the large numbers of people online allow for intentional overproduction.<ref name=\":2\" /> Amanda D. Lotz noted that this is a key strategy, where multiple shows and commercials are created in order to compete, so that the most effective version can succeed, while the others disappear.<ref name=\":2\" /> In online social movements, hashtag culture functions by having many people copy each other and come up with new permutations, allowing for the most successful version to spread.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nSocial media platforms are harder to censor than real-life organisation of movements. Ethan Zuckerman advanced the [[Cute cat theory of digital activism|Cute Cat Theory of Digital Activism]], which explains the relative lack of censorship online. Zuckerman posits that the web is used primarily for innocuous purposes, such as connecting with families and friends and posting pictures of cats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethanzuckerman.com/blog/2007/12/03/cute-cat-theory-the-china-corollary/|title=Cute Cat Theory: The China Corollary {{!}} \u2026 My heart\u2019s in Accra|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> However, the affordances that social media provides activists nurtures a community that engages in political criticism. Still, these activists are able to hide behind the largely mundane uses of the internet, since censorship by governments would appear especially draconian. For instance, the Twitter ban in Turkey by Prime Minister Tayyip Erdogan who intended to \u201cwipe out\u201d the social media platform was met with furious outrage from the population, experts and the global community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-election-idUSBREA2K0NK20140321|title=Furious reaction, political split after Turkey bans Twitter|date=2014-03-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en}}</ref> Similarly when ex-Tunisian President Ben Ali attempted to ban Facebook in 2010, his move backfired because so many Tunisians used Facebook to connect with family, friends and acquaintances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/01/12/the-limits-of-silencing-tunisia/|title=The limits of silencing Tunisia|last=Bounenni|first=Bassam|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Detriments ===\n\nNevertheless, there are numerous critiques posed against online social movements.\n\nMost frequently, the limited capacity for tangible change is often raised. For social movements to be successful, there need to be network internalities, which are durable networks ideal for organised action.<ref name=\":2\" /> These networks are the result of long-term challenges that are collectively overcome, which supports trust building. This process requires the investment of time and energy in order for members of a social movement to learn how to cooperate to achieve their goals.\n\nZeynep Tufekci introduces the Mount Everest metaphor in her comparison of the [[Civil Rights Movement]]\u2019s achievements with the [[Arab Spring]]\u2019s relative limited scope of change, especially in Egypt.<ref name=\":2\" /> Zeynep draws a comparison between social media and Sherpas. Previously, climbing Mount Everest was a challenging task. However, with Sherpas, more people were capable of doing so, and this led to a spike in mountaineering tourism. Nevertheless, these individuals remained unprepared for the reality of scaling the mountain, resulting in a spike in deaths. Similarly, social media has enabled more social movements to spread and enter the public sphere. However, there has not been long-term training and building of network internalities which is necessary to sustain these movements.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Civil Rights Movement had undergone strenuous planning and organisation, which has resulted in leaders who were able to represent the cause, such as Martin Luther King. In contrast, online social movements tend to be more short-lived. For instance, [[Kony 2012]] brought attention to child soldiers being forced into Joseph Kony\u2019s [[Lord\u2019s Resistance Army]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/03/problem-stop-kony/330661/|title=The Problems with 'Stop Kony'|last=Abad-Santos|first=Alexander|date=2012-03-08|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> However, the small organisation that directed the video, Invisible Children, was incapable of managing the sheer volume of attention received. Without the network internalities present in the Civil Rights Movement, the director [[Jason Russell]] had a major breakdown and the social movement dissipated.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Curtis|first=Polly|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/apr/19/kony-2012-nirvana-missed-chance|title=Kony 2012: nirvana of online campaigning or missed chance?|date=2012-04-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nThere is also the concern of a lack of clear leadership in online social movements. This means that there might be a challenge in finding representatives to negotiate within the movement and with adversaries. These individuals might have little in common beyond the initial movement. For instance, [[Tahrir Square]] protesters could not deviate tactically from their initial demand, which was to overthrow the Hosni Mubarak regime. Hence, there was a tactical freeze, where tactics could not be adjusted and new demands were not articulated by the social movement. Even the creator of \u201cWe are All Khaled Said\u201d, the main Facebook page of the Egyptian Revolution, Wael Ghonim was in no position to concede anything. Ghonim was neither an elected leader, nor an informal one, which denied him legitimacy to engage in negotiations.<ref name=\":2\" /> Similarly, in the [[Occupy movement]], there was an attempt to empower all protestors to be leaders of the movement. However, as a \u201cleaderful\u201d movement, there was a lack of ability to identify a clear representative to negotiate since there were too many perspectives.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Costanza-Chock|first=Sasha|date=2012-08-01|title=Mic Check! Media Cultures and the Occupy Movement|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/14742837.2012.710746|journal=Social Movement Studies|volume=11|issue=3-4|pages=375\u2013385|doi=10.1080/14742837.2012.710746|issn=1474-2837}}</ref>\n\nOnline social movements, while effective in unifying people, might also amplify the tendency to tribalism. In particular, more people having access to social media might democratise the risk of promoting violence, especially where institutions are not stable and there can be large amounts of distrust and disinformation. For instance, while social media had helped Sri Lanka ease the path to its first democratic elections in 2015 after years of civil war, communal hatreds began to overrun the news feeds, which are the primary portal of news and information for many users.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Taub|first=Amanda|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/21/world/asia/facebook-sri-lanka-riots.html|title=Where Countries Are Tinderboxes and Facebook Is a Match|date=2018-04-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|last2=Fisher|first2=Max|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== The Future ==\n\nThe future of online movements is hard to predict. However, there are some clear directions where they could certainly lead towards. [[Vanessa DiMauro]] believes the biggest trend concerning online communities in the near future is private online communities. While these large networks that we encounter and use on a day-to-day basis have provided us with a productive and collaborative experience they have also increased to unmanageable sizes. To become a learning environment these groups need to be much smaller and manageable. This is where the idea and trend of private online communities could potentially be the future of online communities.<ref>[[Vanessa DiMauro|DiMauro, V.]] (2011). The Future Of Online Community. Retrieved from http://www.leadernetworks.com/2011/10/future-of-online-community.html</ref>\n\n== Online Social Movements and Commercial Social Media Platforms ==\nSince the late 2000s, increased use of commercial social media platforms by social movements has been reported. According to Lopes, \"Social Media websites such as Facebook, Twitter, YouTube, and the various online blogs have arguably given a voice to individuals that otherwise would not be heard.\" [https://www.creighton.edu/fileadmin/user/CCAS/departments/PoliticalScience/Journal_of_Political_Research__JPR_/2014_JSP_papers/Lopes_JPR.pdf] However, the adoption of these commercial platforms has concerned analysts as they highlighted asymmetrical relationships between the for-profit aims of social media and the copy-left values that drive many online movements. According to Fenton, \"Claims for the extension and re-invention of activism need to be considered in the context of the material social and political world of inequality, injustice and corporate dominance.\"[http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/1742766507086852] For example, \"in his analysis of the Purple Movement (Popolo Viola) in Italy and its extensive use of Facebook, [http://westminsterresearch.wmin.ac.uk/14714/ Coretti (2014)] demonstrates that, while the myth of the network as open and inclusive persists, it acts as a disguise for the communication protocols of commercial social networking platforms that may well enable large-scale mobilization but ultimately, through their very functionality, encourage organizational centralization and fragmentation in social movements\" (Fenton, 2016, p.&nbsp;184).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/Misunderstanding-the-Internet-2nd-Edition/Curran-Fenton-Freedman/p/book/9781138906228|title=Misunderstanding the Internet: 2nd Edition (Paperback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> The proprietary nature of the design of platforms such as Facebook pages fails to provide movements with the necessary instruments in terms of a shared democratic management of their resources. Moreover, the inability to manage Facebook pages and groups according to commonly agreed values promotes vertical power structures within movements, contributing to controversial management of Facebook pages and to internal divisions that significantly hinder the potential of protest.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coretti|first=Lorenzo|date=June 2015|title=The rise and fall of collective identity in networked movements: communication protocols, Facebook, and the anti-Berlusconi protest|journal=Information, Communication & Society|volume=18|issue=8|pages=951\u2013967|doi=10.1080/1369118X.2015.1043317}}</ref>\n\n== Important figures ==\n* [[Shaun King]]; a Twitter-based civil rights activist. \n* [[DeRay Mckesson|DeRay McKesson]]; Twitter- and Instagram-based civil rights activist, known for his involvement in the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement.\n* [[Colin Kaepernick]]; American football quarterback known for his involvement in the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement and causing controversy for kneeling rather than standing for the national anthem, a symbolic act in protest of the unjust and oppressive treatment of people of color in the United States.\n* [[Rachel Dolezal]]; civil rights activist that caused controversy after her Caucasian parents disclosed that she was a Caucasian woman passing as black.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/13/us/rachel-dolezal-naacp-president-accused-of-lying-about-her-race.html|title=Black or White? Woman's Story Stirs Up a Furor|last=P\u00e9rez-pe\u00f1a|first=Richard|date=2015-06-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-13|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Received backlash on various social media platforms for claiming she was a victim of hate crimes as an African American woman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3921964/rachel-dolezal-howard-university/|title=Rachel Dolezal Will Break Her Silence on Tuesday|website=Time|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref>\n* [[Van Jones]]; civil rights activist and creator of various initiatives such as #YesWeCode, which is meant to give aid to minorities in technology fields.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Slacktivism]]\n* [[Internet activism]]\n* [[Accelerated pluralism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Social movements]]\n[[Category:Internet activism]]\n", "name_user": "Cathymeng123", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Online_social_movement"}
{"title_page": "Jocelyn Sidney, 7th Earl of Leicester", "text_new": "'''Jocelyn Sidney, 7th Earl of Leicester''' (1682 \u2013 7 July 1743) was a British [[peerage|peer]], known as '''Hon. Jocelyn Sidney''' until 1737.\n\nHe was the son of [[Robert Sidney, 4th Earl of Leicester]] and Lady Elizabeth Egerton.   He was educated at [[University College, Oxford|University College]], [[Oxford University]].<ref>Charles Mosley, editor, Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes (Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003), volume 1, page 1078.</ref>  In 1734, he was appointed Chief Porter of the [[Tower of London]] by his older brother [[John Sidney, 6th Earl of Leicester]], then [[Constable of the Tower]]. He succeeded his brother in that year, but died without legitimate issue in 1743, when the titles of Earl of Leicester and Viscount Lisle became extinct.\n\nA marriage is recorded in the parish register of Llansamlet, Glamorgan on 18th December 1716 of The Honble Joslin Sidney Esq. and Miss Elizabeth Thomas.The Peerage website quoting Burke's peerage 2003 edition records this marriage as being in February 1717, and that Elizabeth was the daughter of Lewis Thomas of Gwernllwynwith, Glamorgan and died 14th November 1747. <ref> (cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p2947.htm#i29468)</ref>. The parish register is kept at West Glamorgan Archives, Swansea and digital image of the page is available from Findmypast.co.uk where the groom has been indexed as John Sidney. Lewis Thomas of Gwernllwynchwyth (modern spelling) was portreeve of Swansea in 1703. In the Llansamlet parish register for the baptism and burial of his daughter Catherine on 16th and 17th November 1705 he was described as Lewis Thomas Esq., and his burial at Llansamlet 23 May 1711 he was also described as Lewis Thomas Esq. Burke's peerage records Lady Anne Sidney as daughter of Jocelyn Sidney and Elizabeth Thomas.\n\nJocelyn's \"illegitimate\" daughter Lady Anne Sidney married [[Henry Streatfeild]] of [[Chiddingstone]], Kent on 25 September 1752.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p17368.htm#i173677 |title=p. 17368 \u00a7  173677 <!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref>  On Sir Jocelyn's death, Henry could potentially have inherited the Penshurst Estate, but after much legal wrangling Henry and Anne only received the income from the Sidneys' Welsh properties - but these were still fairly significant.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chiddingstone.net/pages/peoplefold/streatfeild.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-06-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120142926/http://www.chiddingstone.net/pages/peoplefold/streatfeild.html |archive-date=2011-11-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[John Sidney, 6th Earl of Leicester|John Sidney]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Earl of Leicester]] | years=1737\u20131743}}\n{{s-non | reason=Extinct}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leicester, Jocelyn Sidney, 7th Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1682 births]]\n[[Category:1743 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Leicester (1618)|7th Earl of Leicester]]\n[[Category:Sidney family|Jocelyn]]\n[[Category:18th-century English people]]\n\n\n{{England-earl-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Jocelyn Sidney, 7th Earl of Leicester''' (1682 \u2013 7 July 1743) was a British [[peerage|peer]], known as '''Hon. Jocelyn Sidney''' until 1737.\n\nHe was the son of [[Robert Sidney, 4th Earl of Leicester]] and Lady Elizabeth Egerton.   He was educated at [[University College, Oxford|University College]], [[Oxford University]].<ref>Charles Mosley, editor, Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes (Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003), volume 1, page 1078.</ref>  In 1734, he was appointed Chief Porter of the [[Tower of London]] by his older brother [[John Sidney, 6th Earl of Leicester]], then [[Constable of the Tower]]. He succeeded his brother in that year, but died without legitimate issue in 1743, when the titles of Earl of Leicester and Viscount Lisle became extinct.\n\nA marriage is recorded in the parish register of Llansamlet, Glamorgan on 18th December 1716 of The Honble Joslin Sidney Esq. and Miss Elizabeth Thomas.The Peerage website quoting Burke's peerage 2003 edition records this marriage as being in February 1717, and that Elizabeth was the daughter of Lewis Thomas of Gwernllwynwith, Glamorgan and died 14th November 1747. <ref> (cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p2947.htm#i29468)</ref>. The parish register is kept at West Glamorgan Archives, Swansea and digital image of the page is available from Findmypast.co.uk where the groom has been indexed as John Sidney. Lewis Thomas of Gwernllwynchwyth (modern spelling)was portreeve of Swansea in 1703. In the Llansamlet parish register for the baptism and burial of his daughter Catherine on 16th and 17th November 1705 he was described as Lewis Thomas Esq., and his burial at Llansamlet 23 May 1711 he was also described as Lewis Thomas Esq. Burke's peerage records Lady Anne Sidney as daughter of Jocelyn Sidney and Elizabeth Thomas.\n\nJocelyn's \"illegitimate\" daughter Lady Anne Sidney married [[Henry Streatfeild]] of [[Chiddingstone]], Kent on 25 September 1752.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lundy |first=Darryl |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p17368.htm#i173677 |title=p. 17368 \u00a7  173677 <!-- Bot generated title --> |publisher= The Peerage}}{{Unreliable source?|failed=y |date=February 2013}}<!--Lundy is not a reliable source so cite Lundy's reliable source See [[WP:SAYWHEREYOUREADIT]]--></ref>  On Sir Jocelyn's death, Henry could potentially have inherited the Penshurst Estate, but after much legal wrangling Henry and Anne only received the income from the Sidneys' Welsh properties - but these were still fairly significant.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chiddingstone.net/pages/peoplefold/streatfeild.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-06-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120142926/http://www.chiddingstone.net/pages/peoplefold/streatfeild.html |archive-date=2011-11-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|en}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[John Sidney, 6th Earl of Leicester|John Sidney]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Earl of Leicester]] | years=1737\u20131743}}\n{{s-non | reason=Extinct}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leicester, Jocelyn Sidney, 7th Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1682 births]]\n[[Category:1743 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Leicester (1618)|7th Earl of Leicester]]\n[[Category:Sidney family|Jocelyn]]\n[[Category:18th-century English people]]\n\n\n{{England-earl-stub}}\n", "name_user": "JeffSA2", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jocelyn_Sidney,_7th_Earl_of_Leicester"}
{"title_page": "Scientific Advice Mechanism", "text_new": "{{Politics of the European Union mini}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\nThe '''Scientific Advice Mechanism''' is a service created by the [[European Commission]] which provides independent [[science advice]] directly to [[European Commissioner]]s to inform their decision-making.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/research/sam/index.cfm?pg=about|title=About the Scientific Advice Mechanism {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> The Mechanism consists of two parts: the '''Group of Chief Scientific Advisors''', an expert group consisting of up to seven leading scientists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> and '''SAPEA''', a consortium of five European Academy Networks collectively representing around 100 [[National academy|academies]] and learned societies across [[Europe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sapea.info/about-us/|title=About us {{!}} SAPEA|website=www.sapea.info|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nUntil 2016, science advice in the [[European Commission]] was provided by a single Chief Scientific Advisor who reported directly to the [[President of the European Commission]]. The last Chief Scientific Advisor, serving from 2012 to 2014, was [[Anne Glover (biologist)|Dame Anne Glover]].\n\nOn 1 November 2014, European Commission President [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] asked [[Carlos Moedas]], Commissioner for [[European Commissioner for Research, Innovation and Science|Research, Innovation and Science]] in his mission letter to \"make sure that Commission proposals and activities are based on sound scientific evidence and contribute best to our jobs and growth agenda\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/commissioners/sites/cwt/files/commissioner_mission_letters/moedas_en.pdf|title=Mission letter to Commissioner Moedas|last=Juncker|first=Jean-Claude|date=2014-11-01|website=European Commission|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following this, on 13 May 2015, Juncker announced the establishment of the Scientific Advice Mechanism. The first seven members of the Advisors were identified, following a European call for nominations, in January 2016.\n\nIn December 2016, SAPEA was officially launched to support the Advisors by providing scientific evidence review reports.\n\n==Structure==\n===Group of Chief Scientific Advisors===\nThe core of the Scientific Advice Mechanism is the European Commission's Group of Chief Scientific Advisors, an expert group consisting of up to seven leading scientists, selected by the European Commission assisted by an independent identification committee. The Advisors are supported by a dedicated secretariat, known as the SAM Unit, staffed by the [[Directorate-General for Research and Innovation (European Commission)|Directorate-General for Research and Innovation]] and [[Joint Research Centre]].\n\nThe Group of Chief Scientific Advisors currently consists of the following seven members:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"border:#555;\"\n|-\n! Name\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:70px;\"| Portrait\n! Role in the Group\n! Academic position\n! [[University]] or institution\n|-\n| {{sortname|Janusz|Bujnicki}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Janusz Bujnicki.jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Professor of Biology\n| [[International Institute of Molecular and Cell Biology, Warsaw]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Pearl|Dykstra}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Pearl Dykstra.jpg|thumb]]\n| Deputy chair\n| Professor of Sociology\n| [[Erasmus University Rotterdam]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Elvira|Fortunato}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Elvira Fortunato.jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Professor of Materials Science\n| [[New University of Lisbon]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Nicole|Grobert}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Nicole Grobert.jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Professor of Nanomaterials\n| [[University of Oxford]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Rolf-Dieter|Heuer}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Rolf-Dieter Heuer (EC).jpg|thumb]]\n| Chair\n| Former Director-General\n| [[CERN]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Carina|Keskitalo}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Carina Keskitalo (EC).jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Professor of Political Science\n| [[Ume\u00e5 University]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Paul|Nurse}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Sir Paul Nurse (EC).jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Director\n| [[Francis Crick Institute]]\n|}\n\nPrevious members of the Group of Chief Scientific Advisors include: \n* [[Julia Slingo]] (2015\u20132016)\n* [[Henrik Wegener]] (2015\u20132017)\n* [[C\u00e9dric Villani]] (2015\u20132017)\n\n===Science Advice for Policy by European Academies (SAPEA)===\nSAPEA brings together more than 100 [[National academy|academies]], young academies and learned societies. Its role as part of the Scientific Advice Mechanism is to provide high-quality, independent evidence to underpin the Scientific Opinions produced by the Chief Scientific Advisors. SAPEA has the ability to convene Fellows from some 40 countries across Europe, spanning the disciplines of engineering, humanities, medicine, natural sciences and social sciences.\n\nThe SAPEA consortium brings together five umbrella networks jointly representing Europe's academies:\n* [[Academia Europaea]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ae-info.org/ae/Acad_Main/Activities/SAPEA|title=Academy of Europe: SAPEA|website=www.ae-info.org|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[All European Academies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allea.org/asap-academies-sciences-advice-to-policy/|title=SAPEA: Science Advice for Policy by European Academies -|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[European Academies' Science Advisory Council]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://easac.eu/cooperation/sapea/|title=SAPEA|date=2018-01-25|website=EASAC Website|language=en|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[European Council of Applied Sciences and Engineering]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euro-case.org/index.php/sapea.html|title=SAM: Scientific Advice Mechanism|website=www.euro-case.org|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[Federation of European Academies of Medicine]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feam.eu/policy-priorities-2/sapea/|title=SAPEA {{!}} FEAM|website=www.feam.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n\nAt present, SAPEA is funded by a grant from the European Union's [[Horizon 2020]] programme through to the end of 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/id/737432|title=Cordis project database|website=cordis.europa.eu|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Scientific advice==\nThe Scientific Advice Mechanism has issued advice in the form of Scientific Opinions, explanatory notes or statements, supported by evidence review reports, on the following topics:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"border:#555;\"\n|-\n! Topic\n! Date\n! Advisors' advice\n! SAPEA evidence review\n|-\n| [[Glyphosate]]\n| {{Dts|June 2016}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/glyphosate_en]\n| none\n|-\n| Light-duty vehicle real-drive [[CO2]] emissions\n| {{Dts|November 2016}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/light-duty-vehicle-real-drive-co2-emissions_en]\n| none\n|-\n| [[Computer security|Cyber-security]] in the European [[Digital Single Market]]\n| {{Dts|March 2017}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/cybersecurity_en]\n| none\n|-\n| New techniques in [[agricultural biotechnology]]\n| {{Dts|April 2017}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/new-techniques-agricultural-biotechnology_en]\n| none\n|-\n| Food from the oceans\n| {{Dts|November 2017}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/food-oceans_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/foodfromtheoceans/]\n|-\n| Novel [[Carbon capture and utilization|carbon capture and utilisation]] technologies: research and climate aspects\n| {{Dts|May 2018}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/novel-carbon-capture-and-utilisation-technologies_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/ccu/]\n|-\n| Authorisation processes of [[pesticide|plant protection product]]s in Europe \n| {{Dts|June 2018}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/authorisation-processes-plant-protection-products-europe_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/ppp/]\n|-\n| Statement on the regulation of [[Genome editing|gene editing]]\n| {{Dts|November 2018}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/info/files/2018_11_gcsa_statement_gene_editing_2.pdf]\n| none\n|-\n| A scientific perspective on [[microplastics]] in nature and society \n| {{Dts|January 2019}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/environmental-and-health-risks-microplastic-pollution_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/microplastics/]\n|-\n| Transforming the future of ageing\n| {{Dts|July 2019}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/transforming-future-ageing_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/making-sense-of-science/]\n|-\n| Making sense of science for policy under conditions of complexity and uncertainty\n| {{Dts|July 2019}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/scientific-advice-european-policy-complex-world_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/making-sense-of-science/]\n|-\n| Towards a [[sustainable food system]] for Europe\n| {{Dts|April 2020}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/towards-sustainable-food-system_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/sustainable-food-systems/]\n|-\n| Adaptation to [[climate change]]-related health effects\n| Summer 2020\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/adaptation-climate-change-related-health-effects_en]\n| none\n|-\n| [[Biodegradable plastic|Biodegradability of plastics]] in the open environment\n| Autumn 2020\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/biodegradability-plastics-open-environment_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/biodegradability-of-plastics/]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|European Commission}}\n* [https://ec.europa.eu/research/sam/index.cfm Scientific Advice Mechanism]\n* [https://www.sapea.info SAPEA]\n\n{{Eu-directorates-general}}\n{{European Union topics}}\n\n{{improve categories|date=May 2019}}\n\n[[Category:European Commission]]\n", "text_old": "{{Politics of the European Union mini}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\nThe '''Scientific Advice Mechanism''' is a service created by the [[European Commission]] which provides independent [[science advice]] directly to [[European Commissioner]]s to inform their decision-making.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/research/sam/index.cfm?pg=about|title=About the Scientific Advice Mechanism {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> The Mechanism consists of two parts: the '''Group of Chief Scientific Advisors''', an expert group consisting of up to seven leading scientists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref> and '''SAPEA''', a consortium of five European Academy Networks collectively representing around 100 [[National academy|academies]] and learned societies across [[Europe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sapea.info/about-us/|title=About us {{!}} SAPEA|website=www.sapea.info|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nUntil 2016, science advice in the [[European Commission]] was provided by a single Chief Scientific Advisor who reported directly to the [[President of the European Commission]]. The last Chief Scientific Advisor, serving from 2012 to 2014, was [[Anne Glover (biologist)|Dame Anne Glover]].\n\nOn 1 November 2014, European Commission President [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] asked [[Carlos Moedas]], Commissioner for [[European Commissioner for Research, Innovation and Science|Research, Innovation and Science]] in his mission letter to \"make sure that Commission proposals and activities are based on sound scientific evidence and contribute best to our jobs and growth agenda\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/commissioners/sites/cwt/files/commissioner_mission_letters/moedas_en.pdf|title=Mission letter to Commissioner Moedas|last=Juncker|first=Jean-Claude|date=2014-11-01|website=European Commission|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following this, on 13 May 2015, Juncker announced the establishment of the Scientific Advice Mechanism. The first seven members of the Advisors were identified, following a European call for nominations, in January 2016.\n\nIn December 2016, SAPEA was officially launched to support the Advisors by providing scientific evidence review reports.\n\n==Structure==\n===Group of Chief Scientific Advisors===\nThe core of the Scientific Advice Mechanism is the European Commission's Group of Chief Scientific Advisors, an expert group consisting of up to seven leading scientists, selected by the European Commission assisted by an independent identification committee. The Advisors are supported by a dedicated secretariat, known as the SAM Unit, staffed by the [[Directorate-General for Research and Innovation (European Commission)|Directorate-General for Research and Innovation]] and [[Joint Research Centre]].\n\nThe Group of Chief Scientific Advisors currently consists of the following seven members:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"border:#555;\"\n|-\n! Name\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:70px;\"| Portrait\n! Role in the Group\n! Academic position\n! [[University]] or institution\n|-\n| {{sortname|Janusz|Bujnicki}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Janusz Bujnicki.jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Professor of Biology\n| [[International Institute of Molecular and Cell Biology, Warsaw]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Pearl|Dykstra}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Pearl Dykstra.jpg|thumb]]\n| Deputy chair\n| Professor of Sociology\n| [[Erasmus University Rotterdam]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Elvira|Fortunato}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Elvira Fortunato.jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Professor of Materials Science\n| [[New University of Lisbon]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Nicole|Grobert}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Nicole Grobert.jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Professor of Nanomaterials\n| [[University of Oxford]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Rolf-Dieter|Heuer}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Rolf-Dieter Heuer (EC).jpg|thumb]]\n| Chair\n| Former Director-General\n| [[CERN]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Carina|Keskitalo}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Carina Keskitalo (EC).jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Professor of Political Science\n| [[Ume\u00e5 University]]\n|-\n| {{sortname|Paul|Nurse}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/members-group-chief-scientific-advisors_en|title=Group of Chief Scientific Advisors {{!}} SAM \u2013 Research and Innovation \u2013 European Commission|website=ec.europa.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n| [[File:Sir Paul Nurse (EC).jpg|thumb]]\n| \n| Director\n| [[Francis Crick Institute]]\n|}\n\nPrevious members of the Group of Chief Scientific Advisors include: \n* [[Julia Slingo]] (2015\u20132016)\n* [[Henrik Wegener]] (2015\u20132017)\n* [[C\u00e9dric Villani]] (2015\u20132017)\n\n===Science Advice for Policy by European Academies (SAPEA)===\nSAPEA brings together more than 100 [[National academy|academies]], young academies and learned societies. Its role as part of the Scientific Advice Mechanism is to provide high-quality, independent evidence to underpin the Scientific Opinions produced by the Chief Scientific Advisors. SAPEA has the ability to convene Fellows from some 40 countries across Europe, spanning the disciplines of engineering, humanities, medicine, natural sciences and social sciences.\n\nThe SAPEA consortium brings together five umbrella networks jointly representing Europe's academies:\n* [[Academia Europaea]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ae-info.org/ae/Acad_Main/Activities/SAPEA|title=Academy of Europe: SAPEA|website=www.ae-info.org|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[All European Academies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allea.org/asap-academies-sciences-advice-to-policy/|title=SAPEA: Science Advice for Policy by European Academies -|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[European Academies' Science Advisory Council]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://easac.eu/cooperation/sapea/|title=SAPEA|date=2018-01-25|website=EASAC Website|language=en|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[European Council of Applied Sciences and Engineering]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euro-case.org/index.php/sapea.html|title=SAM: Scientific Advice Mechanism|website=www.euro-case.org|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[Federation of European Academies of Medicine]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.feam.eu/policy-priorities-2/sapea/|title=SAPEA {{!}} FEAM|website=www.feam.eu|access-date=2019-03-28}}</ref>\n\nAt present, SAPEA is funded by a grant from the European Union's [[Horizon 2020]] programme through to the end of 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cordis.europa.eu/project/id/737432|title=Cordis project database|website=cordis.europa.eu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Scientific advice==\nThe Scientific Advice Mechanism has issued advice in the form of Scientific Opinions, explanatory notes or statements, supported by evidence review reports, on the following topics:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"border:#555;\"\n|-\n! Topic\n! Date\n! Advisors' advice\n! SAPEA evidence review\n|-\n| [[Glyphosate]]\n| {{Dts|June 2016}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/glyphosate_en]\n| none\n|-\n| Light-duty vehicle real-drive [[CO2]] emissions\n| {{Dts|November 2016}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/light-duty-vehicle-real-drive-co2-emissions_en]\n| none\n|-\n| [[Computer security|Cyber-security]] in the European [[Digital Single Market]]\n| {{Dts|March 2017}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/cybersecurity_en]\n| none\n|-\n| New techniques in [[agricultural biotechnology]]\n| {{Dts|April 2017}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/new-techniques-agricultural-biotechnology_en]\n| none\n|-\n| Food from the oceans\n| {{Dts|November 2017}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/food-oceans_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/foodfromtheoceans/]\n|-\n| Novel [[Carbon capture and utilization|carbon capture and utilisation]] technologies: research and climate aspects\n| {{Dts|May 2018}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/novel-carbon-capture-and-utilisation-technologies_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/ccu/]\n|-\n| Authorisation processes of [[pesticide|plant protection product]]s in Europe \n| {{Dts|June 2018}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/authorisation-processes-plant-protection-products-europe_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/ppp/]\n|-\n| Statement on the regulation of [[Genome editing|gene editing]]\n| {{Dts|November 2018}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/sites/info/files/2018_11_gcsa_statement_gene_editing_2.pdf]\n| none\n|-\n| A scientific perspective on [[microplastics]] in nature and society \n| {{Dts|January 2019}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/environmental-and-health-risks-microplastic-pollution_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/microplastics/]\n|-\n| Transforming the future of ageing\n| {{Dts|July 2019}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/transforming-future-ageing_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/making-sense-of-science/]\n|-\n| Making sense of science for policy under conditions of complexity and uncertainty\n| {{Dts|July 2019}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/scientific-advice-european-policy-complex-world_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/making-sense-of-science/]\n|-\n| Towards a [[sustainable food system]] for Europe\n| {{Dts|April 2020}}\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/towards-sustainable-food-system_en]\n| [https://www.sapea.info/topics/sustainable-food-systems/]\n|-\n| Adaptation to [[climate change]]-related health effects\n| Summer 2020\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/adaptation-climate-change-related-health-effects_en]\n| none\n|-\n| [[Biodegradable plastic|Biodegradability of plastics]] in the open environment\n| Autumn 2020\n| [https://ec.europa.eu/info/research-and-innovation/strategy/support-policy-making/scientific-support-eu-policies/group-chief-scientific-advisors/biod