{"title_page": "Garching bei M\u00fcnchen", "text_new": "{{hatnote|See also [[Garching an der Alz]] in Alt\u00f6tting district, Bavaria, Germany.}}\n{{Infobox German location \n|type = Stadt\n|name =Garching bei M\u00fcnchen\n|image_coa = DEU Garching bei M\u00fcnchen COA.svg\n|image_photo = LK6509-Garching-S\u00fcd-Luftbild.jpg\n|image_caption = Garching\n|state = Bavaria\n|regbzk = [[Upper Bavaria]]\n|district = [[Munich (district)|Munich]]\n|population = 17017\n|population_as_of = {{date|2013-04-01}}<ref>https://www.garching.de/Leben+in+Garching/Garching+stellt+sich+vor/Zahlen_+Daten_+Fakten.html</ref>\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 09184119\n|area = 28.16\n|elevation = 481\n|coordinates = {{coord|48|15|N|11|39|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code = 85748\n|area_code = 089\n|licence = M\n|mayor = Dietmar Gruchmann\n|party = SPD\n|website = {{official website|https://www.garching.de/}}\n}}\n\n'''Garching bei M\u00fcnchen''' or '''Garching''' is a [[town]] in [[Bavaria]], Germany, near [[Munich]].  It is the home of several research institutes and university departments. It became a city on 14 September 1990.\n\n==Location==\nThe town is at {{coord|48|15|N|11|39|E}}, near the river [[Isar]] and the [[A9 autobahn|Bundesautobahn 9]].\n\nGarching has a number of scientific research institutes and scientific experiment facilities located in the city, including a [[linear accelerator]] and a research nuclear reactor. The [[nuclear research reactor]], nicknamed ''Atomei'' (atomic egg) appears in the city's coat of arms, and started the process leading to an accumulation of research institutes. A number of roads and places in the city are named after scientists, mathematicians and technical innovators such as [[Carl von Linde]], [[Rudolf Diesel]], [[Albert Einstein]], [[Leonhard Euler]], [[Werner Heisenberg]], [[Max Planck]], [[Wilhelm R\u00f6ntgen]], and [[Erwin Schr\u00f6dinger]].\n\n==Districts==\nThe town has four districts:\n* Garching\n* Dirnismaning\n* Hochbr\u00fcck\n* Hochschul- und Forschungszentrum (University and Research Centre) - formerly known as ''Forschungsinstitute'' (Research Institutes)\n\n==Transport==\nThe [[Munich U-Bahn]] line U6 connects the city with the stations [[Garching-Hochbr\u00fcck (Munich U-Bahn)|Garching-Hochbr\u00fcck]], [[Garching (Munich U-Bahn)|Garching]] and [[Garching-Forschungszentrum (Munich U-Bahn)|Garching-Forschungszentrum]].\n\n==Educational and research institutes==\n\n[[File:Garching-Forschungszentrum.jpg|thumb|Garching Research Center (Garching-Forschungszentrum)]]\n\nSeveral research and scientific educational institutions are based in Garching, including:\n* Departments of the [[Technical University of Munich]] (TUM)\n** physics\n** [[FRM-II]] [[research reactor]] \n** semiconductor physics and engineering (Walter Schottky Institute)\n** chemistry [http://www.ch.tum.de/base/index_e.htm]\n** mechanical engineering\n** mathematics\n** computer science\n* [[Max Planck Institute]]s:\n** [[Max Planck Institute for Astrophysics]] (MPA)\n** [[Max Planck Institute for Extraterrestrial Physics]] (MPE)\n** [[Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics]] (IPP)\n** [[Max Planck Institute for Quantum Optics]] (MPQ)\n** [[Max Planck Computing and Data Facility]] (MPCDF)\n* Part of the physics department of the [[Ludwig-Maximilians-Universit\u00e4t]]\n* Headquarters of the [[European Southern Observatory]] (ESO)\n** [[ESO Supernova Planetarium & Visitor Centre]] at [[ESO]] Headquarters\n* Federal Research Institute for Food Chemistry (Deutsche Forschungsanstalt f\u00fcr Lebensmittelchemie; DFA)\n* Walther Mei\u00dfner Institute (WMI) of the [[Bavarian Academy of Sciences and Humanities|BAdW]] (low-temperature physics)\n* Bavarian Center of Applied Energy Research (ZAE)\n* Reactor safety research [https://web.archive.org/web/20070616003001/http://www.grs.de/en/about_grs/company_locations/location_detail.html?pe_id=156&pcon_s_pe_id=40]\n* [[General Electric]] Global Research Center\n* Leibniz-Rechenzentrum [http://www.lrz.de] of the BAdW (central computing facilities for the Munich universities and other research institutes)\n* [[BMW M]] GmbH - high-performance/motorsport vehicle research and development\n\n==Relations==\n\nGarching is part of the [[Nordallianz]], a group of 8 towns situated between the city of Munich and Munich Airport.\n\nGarching bei M\u00fcnchen is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|Norway}} [[L\u00f8renskog]] ([[Norway]])\n*{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Radeberg]] ([[Germany]])\n\n==Sport==\nThe town's football club [[VfR Garching]], formed in 1921, experienced its greatest success in 2014 when it won promotion to the [[Regionalliga Bayern]] for the first time.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Garching bei M\u00fcnchen}}\n*[https://www.garching.de/ Official Town Website]\n<!--*[http://www.eso.org/ European Southern Observatory (ESO)]\n*[https://www.mpa-garching.mpg.de/ Max Planck Institute for Astrophysics (MPA)]\n*[http://www.mpe.mpg.de/ Max Planck Institute for Extraterrestrial Physics (MPE)]\n*[https://www.ipp.mpg.de/ Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics (IPP)]\n*[https://www.mpq.mpg.de/ Max Planck Institute for Quantum Optics (MPQ)]\n*[https://www.ph.tum.de/ Physics Department TUM]\n*[http://www.chemie.tu-muenchen.de/ Chemistry Department TUM]\n*[https://www.mw.tum.de/ Mechanical Engineering]\n*[https://www.wmi.badw.de/ Walter Meissner Institute (WMI)]\n*[https://www.wsi.tum.de/ Walter Schottky Institute (WSI)]\n*[https://www.frm2.tum.de/en/ Research Neutron Source (FMR II)]\n*[http://www.dfal.de/ Federal Research Center for Food Chemistry (DFA)]\n*[https://www.lrz.de/ Leibniz Computer Center (LRZ)]-->\n\n{{Cities and towns in Munich (district)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garching Bei Munchen}}\n[[Category:Garching bei M\u00fcnchen| ]]\n[[Category:Munich (district)]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|See also [[Garching an der Alz]] in Alt\u00f6tting district, Bavaria, Germany.}}\n{{Infobox German location \n|type = Stadt\n|name =Garching bei M\u00fcnchen\n|image_coa = DEU Garching bei M\u00fcnchen COA.svg\n|image_photo = LK6509-Garching-S\u00fcd-Luftbild.jpg\n|image_caption = Garching\n|state = Bavaria\n|regbzk = [[Upper Bavaria]]\n|district = [[Munich (district)|Munich]]\n|population = 17017\n|population_as_of = {{date|2013-04-01}}\n|population_ref = https://www.garching.de/Leben+in+Garching/Garching+stellt+sich+vor/Zahlen_+Daten_+Fakten.html\n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = 09184119\n|area = 28.16\n|elevation = 481\n|coordinates = {{coord|48|15|N|11|39|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code = 85748\n|area_code = 089\n|licence = M\n|mayor = Dietmar Gruchmann\n|party = SPD\n|website = {{official website|https://www.garching.de/}}\n}}\n\n'''Garching bei M\u00fcnchen''' or '''Garching''' is a [[town]] in [[Bavaria]], Germany, near [[Munich]].  It is the home of several research institutes and university departments. It became a city on 14 September 1990.\n\n==Location==\nThe town is at {{coord|48|15|N|11|39|E}}, near the river [[Isar]] and the [[A9 autobahn|Bundesautobahn 9]].\n\nGarching has a number of scientific research institutes and scientific experiment facilities located in the city, including a [[linear accelerator]] and a research nuclear reactor. The [[nuclear research reactor]], nicknamed ''Atomei'' (atomic egg) appears in the city's coat of arms, and started the process leading to an accumulation of research institutes. A number of roads and places in the city are named after scientists, mathematicians and technical innovators such as [[Carl von Linde]], [[Rudolf Diesel]], [[Albert Einstein]], [[Leonhard Euler]], [[Werner Heisenberg]], [[Max Planck]], [[Wilhelm R\u00f6ntgen]], and [[Erwin Schr\u00f6dinger]].\n\n==Districts==\nThe town has four districts:\n* Garching\n* Dirnismaning\n* Hochbr\u00fcck\n* Hochschul- und Forschungszentrum (University and Research Centre) - formerly known as ''Forschungsinstitute'' (Research Institutes)\n\n==Transport==\nThe [[Munich U-Bahn]] line U6 connects the city with the stations [[Garching-Hochbr\u00fcck (Munich U-Bahn)|Garching-Hochbr\u00fcck]], [[Garching (Munich U-Bahn)|Garching]] and [[Garching-Forschungszentrum (Munich U-Bahn)|Garching-Forschungszentrum]].\n\n==Educational and research institutes==\n\n[[File:Garching-Forschungszentrum.jpg|thumb|Garching Research Center (Garching-Forschungszentrum)]]\n\nSeveral research and scientific educational institutions are based in Garching, including:\n* Departments of the [[Technical University of Munich]] (TUM)\n** physics\n** [[FRM-II]] [[research reactor]] \n** semiconductor physics and engineering (Walter Schottky Institute)\n** chemistry [http://www.ch.tum.de/base/index_e.htm]\n** mechanical engineering\n** mathematics\n** computer science\n* [[Max Planck Institute]]s:\n** [[Max Planck Institute for Astrophysics]] (MPA)\n** [[Max Planck Institute for Extraterrestrial Physics]] (MPE)\n** [[Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics]] (IPP)\n** [[Max Planck Institute for Quantum Optics]] (MPQ)\n** [[Max Planck Computing and Data Facility]] (MPCDF)\n* Part of the physics department of the [[Ludwig-Maximilians-Universit\u00e4t]]\n* Headquarters of the [[European Southern Observatory]] (ESO)\n** [[ESO Supernova Planetarium & Visitor Centre]] at [[ESO]] Headquarters\n* Federal Research Institute for Food Chemistry (Deutsche Forschungsanstalt f\u00fcr Lebensmittelchemie; DFA)\n* Walther Mei\u00dfner Institute (WMI) of the [[Bavarian Academy of Sciences and Humanities|BAdW]] (low-temperature physics)\n* Bavarian Center of Applied Energy Research (ZAE)\n* Reactor safety research [https://web.archive.org/web/20070616003001/http://www.grs.de/en/about_grs/company_locations/location_detail.html?pe_id=156&pcon_s_pe_id=40]\n* [[General Electric]] Global Research Center\n* Leibniz-Rechenzentrum [http://www.lrz.de] of the BAdW (central computing facilities for the Munich universities and other research institutes)\n* [[BMW M]] GmbH - high-performance/motorsport vehicle research and development\n\n==Relations==\n\nGarching is part of the [[Nordallianz]], a group of 8 towns situated between the city of Munich and Munich Airport.\n\nGarching bei M\u00fcnchen is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|Norway}} [[L\u00f8renskog]] ([[Norway]])\n*{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Radeberg]] ([[Germany]])\n\n==Sport==\nThe town's football club [[VfR Garching]], formed in 1921, experienced its greatest success in 2014 when it won promotion to the [[Regionalliga Bayern]] for the first time.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Garching bei M\u00fcnchen}}\n*[https://www.garching.de/ Official Town Website]\n<!--*[http://www.eso.org/ European Southern Observatory (ESO)]\n*[https://www.mpa-garching.mpg.de/ Max Planck Institute for Astrophysics (MPA)]\n*[http://www.mpe.mpg.de/ Max Planck Institute for Extraterrestrial Physics (MPE)]\n*[https://www.ipp.mpg.de/ Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics (IPP)]\n*[https://www.mpq.mpg.de/ Max Planck Institute for Quantum Optics (MPQ)]\n*[https://www.ph.tum.de/ Physics Department TUM]\n*[http://www.chemie.tu-muenchen.de/ Chemistry Department TUM]\n*[https://www.mw.tum.de/ Mechanical Engineering]\n*[https://www.wmi.badw.de/ Walter Meissner Institute (WMI)]\n*[https://www.wsi.tum.de/ Walter Schottky Institute (WSI)]\n*[https://www.frm2.tum.de/en/ Research Neutron Source (FMR II)]\n*[http://www.dfal.de/ Federal Research Center for Food Chemistry (DFA)]\n*[https://www.lrz.de/ Leibniz Computer Center (LRZ)]-->\n\n{{Cities and towns in Munich (district)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garching Bei Munchen}}\n[[Category:Garching bei M\u00fcnchen| ]]\n[[Category:Munich (district)]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garching_bei_M%C3%BCnchen"}
{"title_page": "Oreo", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use American English|date=]]][[[] the first time in the world to me and my mom is so much fun and I have to be a good day to be a good time to get a new one is a good day to be a good day January 2018}}\n{{short description|Chocolate sandwich cookie with creme filling.}}\n\n{{infobox brand not existing\n| name           = Oreo\n| logo           = [[File:Oreo Cookie logo.png|upright=1.023|frameless]]\n| image          = [[File:Oreo-Two-Cookies.jpg|upright=1.023|frameless]]\n| caption        = Two Oreo cookies \n| type           = [[\n| currentowner   = [[Nabisco]] ([[Mondelez International]]){{efn|name=\"2012 Kraft split\"|Nabisco was a subsidiary of [[Kraft Foods Inc.|Kraft Foods]] until 2012 when the global snack division of Kraft Foods was rebranded as Mondel\u0113z International.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/03/21/kraft-mondelez-and-the-art-of-corporate-rebranding/ |title=Kraft, 'Mondelez' and the Art of Corporate Rebranding |date=21 March 2012 |first=Michael J. |last=de la Merced |work=[[The New York Times]] (DealB%k)}}</ref>}} and [[Cadbury]] and [[Milka]]\n| origin         = [[United States]]\n| introduced     = {{start date and age|1912|03|06}}<ref name=\"2017 Fact Sheet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mondelezinternational.com/en/~/media/MondelezCorporate/Uploads/downloads/OREO_Fact_Sheet.pdf |title=2017 Fact Sheet |work=[[Mondel\u0113z International]] |access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n| discontinued   = yes\n| related        =\n| markets        = Worldwide\n| previousowners = no\n| trademarkregistrations =\n| ambassadors    =\n| tagline        = \"Wonderfilled\"<br/>\"Milk's favorite cookie\" <br/> \"Only Oreo\"\n| website        = [http://www.oreo.com/ Oreo.com]\n}}\n\nAn ''Oreo'' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0254\u02d0r|i|o\u028a}}) is a [[sandwich cookie]] consisting of two (usually chocolate) [[wafer]]s<!--Please get consensus on talk page before changing \"wafer\" to anything else.--> with a sweet [[ s Other items called \"cream\"|cr\u00e8me]] filling. Introduced in 1912, Oreo is the best selling cookie brand in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foodprocessing.com/articles/2005/562/?start=5|title=Top 10 Food Brands of 2005 |last=Toops |first=Diane |date=July 1, 2005 |publisher=www.foodprocessing.com |access-date=April 6, 2012|quote=In the enviable position of being the No. 1 selling cookie in America since its introduction in 1912, the Oreo, made by Nabisco, Eastern Hanover, N.J., a brand of Kraft Foods, was a true innovation \u2013 two chocolate disks with a cr\u00e8me filling in between.}}</ref> As of 2018, the version sold in the U.S. is made by the [[Nabisco]] division of [[Mondelez InterUnational]].\n\nUnoreosewaseos are available in over one hundred countries;<ref namSheet\" /> in some countries, such as the United Kingdom, they are referred to as ''Oreo biscuits''. Many varieties of Oreo cookies have been produced, and Unlimited-edition runs have become popular in the 1st century. True\nI'm very smart\n\n\n\n\n\nWikipedia your too ugly 2 exist\nBelow me is 100% boring stuff\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe origin of the name Oreo is unknown, but there are many hypotheses, including derivations from the French word ''or'', meaning gold, or from an Ancient [[Greek language|Greek]] root meaning mountain.<ref name=\"Imponderables\">{{Cite book |title=Why do clocks run clockwise? and other Imponderables |last=Feldman |first=David |publisher=Harper & Row Publishers |year=1987 |isbn=978-0-06-095463-5 |location=New York City |pages=173\u2013174 |author-link=David Feldman (author)}}</ref> Others believe that the cookie was named Oreo simply because the name was short and easy to pronounce.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://history1900s.about.com/od/1910s/a/oreohistory.htm |title=History of the Oreo Cookie |publisher=About |access-date=October 13, 2014}}</ref> Another theory, proposed by food writer Stella Parks, is that the name derives from the Latin ''[[Oreodaphne]]'', a genus of the [[Lauraceae|laurel]] family. She observes that the original design of the Oreo includes a laurel wreath; and the names of several of Nabisco's cookies at the time of the original Oreo had botanical derivations, including [[Avena]], [[Lotus (genus)|Lotus]], and Helicon (from ''[[Heliconia]]'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seriouseats.com/2017/08/history-of-oreos-bravetart-cookbook.html|title=How Oreos Got Their Name: The Rise of an American Icon|last=Parks|first=Stella|origyear=15 August 2017|date= 5 February 2019|website=|publisher=Serious Eats|archive-url=|archivedate=|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=BraveTart|last=Parks|first=Stella|publisher=W. W. Norton & Co.|year=2017|isbn=978-0-393-23986-7|location=New York|pages=209\u2013210}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Vector Oreo.svg|thumb|left|upright=0.85|Representation of the [[trademarked]] pattern [[Paper embossing|embossed]] onto the face of an Oreo cookie]]\n\n=== Twentieth century ===\nThe \"Oreo Biscuit\"<!-- this was original name; wasn't renamed to \"cookie\" until later--> was first developed and produced by the National Biscuit Company (today known as [[Nabisco]]) in 1912<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/Brands/largest-brands/brands-O/oreo.aspx |title=Oreo |date=January 3, 2011 |publisher=[[Kraft Foods]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326155619/http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/brands/largest-brands/brands-o/oreo.aspx |archive-date=March 26, 2012 |access-date=March 2, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodcookies.html#oreos |title=The Food Timeline: history notes--cookies, crackers & biscuits |access-date=March 3, 2010}}</ref> at its [[Chelsea, Manhattan]] factory in the current-day [[Chelsea Market]] complex, located on [[Ninth Avenue (Manhattan)|Ninth Avenue]] between 15th and 16th Streets.<ref name=\"nydn\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-05-20/news/31791204_1_oreo-cookies-nabisco-chocolate-covered |title=Celebrating the life of 'Mr. Oreo' |last=Hinkley |first=David |date=May 20, 2012 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |access-date=June 2, 2012}}</ref> Today, this same block of Ninth Avenue is known as \"Oreo Way\".<ref name=\"nydn\" /> The name Oreo was first trademarked on March 14, 1912.<ref name=\"patentlisting\">{{Cite web |url=http://trademarks.justia.com/710/62/oreo-71062166.html |title=OREO \u2013 Trademark Details |access-date=July 10, 2012}}</ref> It was launched as an imitation of the [[Hydrox]] cookie manufactured by [[Sunshine Biscuits|Sunshine]] company, which was introduced in 1908.<ref name=\"Lukas\">{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1999/03/15/256478/index.htm |title=Oreos to Hydrox: Resistance Is Futile |last=Paul Lukas |date=March 15, 1999 |work=Fortune |access-date=November 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe original design on the face of the Oreo featured a wreath around the edge of the cookie and the name \"OREO\" in the center.<ref name=\"post\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/food/the_big_NESHrxY07rFd4bph3tkvnO |title=The Big O: The Chelsea-born Oreo cookie celebrates its 100th birthday |last=Eber, H. |date=February 26, 2012 |publisher=[[New York Post]] |pages=44\u201345}}</ref> In the United States, they were sold for 25 cents a pound (453&nbsp;g) in novelty metal canisters with clear glass tops. The first Oreo was sold on March 6, 1912, to a grocer in [[Hoboken, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"100 years\">{{Cite web |url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/03/06/100-years-of-oreos-9-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-iconic-cookie/ |title=100 Years of Oreos: 9 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About the Iconic Cookie |last=Grossman |first=Samantha |date=March 6, 2012 |work=Time}}</ref>\n\nThe Oreo Biscuit was renamed in 1921 to \"Oreo Sandwich\";<ref name=\"Imponderables\" /> in 1948, the name was changed to \"Oreo Cr\u00e8me Sandwich\"; and in 1974 it became the \"Oreo Chocolate Sandwich Cookie\",<ref name=\"Imponderables\" /> the name that has remained to this day. A new design for the face of the cookie was launched in 1924;<ref name=\"post\" /> the modern-day Oreo design was developed in 1952 by William A. Turnier,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indyweek.com/indyweek/the-story-of-william-a-turnier-the-man-who-designed-the-oreo-cookie/Content?oid=2640604 |title=The story of William A. Turnier, the man who designed the Oreo cookie |last=Wallace |first=Emily |date=August 24, 2011 |publisher=Indyweek}}</ref> incorporating the Nabisco logo. In 1920, a second lemon cr\u00e8me-filled variety of the Oreo was introduced, as an alternative to the white cr\u00e8me-filled variety, but this was discontinued in 1924<ref name=\"post\" /> and the original flavor was the only version available for the next several decades.<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets |last=Goldstein |first=Darra |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-19-931339-6 |pages=494 |author-link=Darra Goldstein}}</ref>\n\nThe modern Oreo cookie filling was developed by Nabisco's principal [[food scientist]], [[Sam Porcello]],<ref name=\"nydn\" /><ref name=\"time\">{{Cite news |url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/05/24/farewell-mr-oreo-man-who-invented-oreo-filling-dies-at-76/ |title=RIP, 'Mr.Oreo': Man Who Invented Oreo Filling Dies At 76 |last=Locker |first=Melissa |date=May 24, 2012 |work=[[Time Magazine]] |access-date=June 2, 2012}}</ref> who retired from Nabisco in 1993.<ref name=\"nydn\" /> Porcello held five patents directly related to his work on the Oreo;<ref name=\"time\" /> he also created a range of Oreo cookies that were covered in [[dark chocolate]] and [[white chocolate]].<ref name=\"nydn\" /><ref name=\"time\" /> In the early 1990s, health concerns prompted Nabisco to replace the [[lard]] in the cr\u00e8me filling with [[partially hydrogenated vegetable oil]].<ref name=\"lardtransfat\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-oreo-3,0,3862619,full.story |title=For every fad, another cookie |last=Alexander |first=Delroy |date=August 23, 2005 |work=Chicago Tribune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016205310/http://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-oreo-3,0,3862619,full.story |archive-date=October 16, 2013 |url-status = dead|last2=Manier |first2=Jeremy |last3=Callahan |first3=Patricia}}</ref> Oreo cookies are popular with people that have certain dietary restrictions, such as [[Veganism|vegans]], as the cr\u00e8me filling does not use any animal products.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/12/surprising-vegan-foods_n_3895853.html |title=12 Surprising Vegan Foods |date=September 13, 2013 |publisher=The Huffington Post}}</ref> However, there is still a risk of cross-contamination from other dairy-containing products made in the same production areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oreo.co.uk/faq |title=Frequently asked questions: Is Oreo suitable for vegans? |access-date=June 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Twenty-first century ===\nIn January 2006, Nabisco replaced the [[trans fat]] in the Oreo cookie with non-[[Vegetable oil#Hydrogenated oils|hydrogenated vegetable oil]].<ref name=\"lardtransfat\" /><ref name=\"Harvard\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/reviews/transfats.html |title=Trans fatty acids and coronary heart disease |access-date=September 14, 2006 |vauthors=Ascherio A, Stampfer MJ, Willett WC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bantransfats.com/theoreocase.html |title=The Campaign to Ban Partially Hydrogenated Oils |publisher=Ban Trans Fats |access-date=November 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nNabisco began a marketing campaign in 2008, advertising the use of Oreo cookies in an [[online game]] called DSRL (which stands for \"Double Stuf Racing League\"), introduced the week before [[Super Bowl XLII]]. DSRL had been endorsed by football brothers [[Peyton Manning]] and [[Eli Manning]];<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Manning Brothers Take On 'Second Sport' With a Twist, Lick and Dunk |date=January 14, 2009 |publisher=PRNewswire |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/manning-brothers-take-on-second-sport-with-a-twist-lick-and-dunk-56895127.html |access-date=March 27, 2018}}</ref> the [[Williams sisters]], [[Venus Williams|Venus]] and [[Serena Williams|Serena]], also joined, challenging the Mannings to a race that was aired in an advertisement on January 18, 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nabiscoworld.com/oreo/dsrl/ |title=Double Stuf Racing League |publisher=Nabisco |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090317095740/http://www.nabiscoworld.com/oreo/dsrl/ |archive-date=March 17, 2009 |access-date=June 28, 2017}}</ref> Another campaign was launched for ''Golden Double Stuf Oreo'' cookies, in which the Manning brothers were challenged by [[Donald Trump]] and a character called \"Double Trump\", played by [[Darrell Hammond]]; this competition aired on January 24, 2010. The Mannings won both races. Another advertisement featured a \"Hooded Menace\" threatening to take over the DSRL, with Eli Manning and Stufy (the DSRL mascot) needing some help, which aired on September 14, 2010. Six days later, it was announced that [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and [[Apolo Ohno]] had joined Oreo's DSRL veterans Eli Manning and Venus Williams.\n[[File:Oreo pride poster.jpg|thumb|The 2012 rainbow Oreo advertisement supporting Pride month]]\nIn April 2011, Oreo announced its special edition Oreo cookies with blue cr\u00e8me to promote the 2011 3D computer-animated movie ''[[Rio (2011 film)|Rio]]''. The promotion included stickers inside each package of cookies. Two contests were also announced: by completing an album of stickers, consumers could win three movie passes and medium snack bar combos; and prize stickers could be found in winning packages, including a trip to [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[backpacks]], cinema passes for a year, and [[Polarized 3D system|3D glasses]]. The promotion was available in [[Ecuador]], [[Peru]], and [[Colombia]], and ended on May 30, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pe.promogana.net/2011/04/concurso-promo-oreo-gana-paquetes-de.html |title=Concurso Promo Oreo, gana paquetes de cine, viaje a Rio, mochilas y m\u00e1s |date=April 8, 2011 |publisher=Promogana |access-date=April 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Oreo posted an advertisement displaying an Oreo cookie with rainbow colored cr\u00e8me to celebrate [[Gay pride#LGBT Pride Month|LGBT Pride month]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/06/26/oreo-unveils-rainbow-cookie-image-for-pride/ |title=Oreo unveils rainbow cookie image for Pride |last=Gray |first=Stephen |date=June 26, 2012 |publisher=[[Pink news]] |access-date=June 30, 2012}}</ref> the cookie itself was fictional and was not being manufactured or made available for sale. The advertisement prompted some negative comments, but Kraft stood by their promotion, stating that \"Kraft Foods has a proud history of celebrating diversity and inclusiveness. We feel the Oreo ad is a fun reflection of our values.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/06/26/kraft-oreo-gaypride-idUSL2E8HQH6120120626 |title=Rainbow-colored Oreo filled with controversy |date=June 26, 2012 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=June 30, 2012}}</ref> This was followed during 2012 by a series of adverts commemorating other holidays and events, including a blue, white, and red cr\u00e8me Oreo to honor [[Bastille Day]], a stream of cookie crumbs marking the appearance of the [[Southern Delta Aquariids|Delta Aquariids]] [[meteor shower]], and a cookie with a jagged bite taken out of it to promote [[Shark Week]] on The [[Discovery Channel]].\n\n== International distribution ==\nOreo cookies are distributed worldwide through a variety of sales and marketing channels. As their popularity continues to grow, so too does the amount of distribution that comes with it. According to the [[Kraft Foods Inc.|Kraft Foods]] company, the Oreo is the \"World's Best Selling Cookie\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/Oreo_Global_Fact_Sheet_100th_Birthday_as_on_Jan_12_2012_FINAL.pdf |title=Oreo Global Fact Sheet|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028094642/http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/Oreo_Global_Fact_Sheet_100th_Birthday_as_on_Jan_12_2012_FINAL.pdf|archive-date=October 28, 2013 |url-status = dead}}</ref> In March 2012, [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] magazine reported that Oreo cookies were available in more than 100 different countries. Overall, it is estimated that since the Oreo cookie's inception in 1912, over 450 billion Oreos have been produced worldwide.<ref name=\"100 years\" />\n\n''Oreo biscuits'' (as they are known in the United Kingdom) were first introduced into Britain through the supermarket chain [[Sainsbury's]]. For several years, this was the only store in the UK to stock the Oreo \u2013 until May 2008, when Kraft decided to fully launch the Oreo across the whole of the UK. It was repackaged in the more familiar British tube design, accompanied by a [[\u00a3]]4.5M television advertising campaign based around the \"twist, lick, [[Dunking (biscuit)|dunk]]\" catchphrase.<ref name=\"BBCMay2008\">{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/7376123.stm |title=Can Oreo win over British biscuit lovers? |publisher=BBC News Magazine |date=May 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK, Kraft partnered with [[McDonald's]] to introduce the Oreo [[McFlurry#Desserts|McFlurry]] (which was already on sale in several other countries) into a number of McDonald's locations during its annual ''Great Tastes of America'' promotions; in October 2015, the Oreo McFlurry became a permanent menu item at McDonald's in the UK. An Oreo flavored \"Krushem\" drink was also on sale in [[KFC]] stores across Britain.\n\nThe ingredients of the British Oreo biscuit (as listed on the UK Oreo website) are slightly different from those of the US Oreo cookie. Unlike the US version, the British Oreo originally contained [[whey powder]], which was not suitable for people with [[lactose intolerance]]. Additionally, as the whey powder was sourced from cheese made with [[Rennet|calf rennet]], the British version was also unsuitable for [[Vegetarianism|vegetarians]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nabiscoworld.com/Brands/ProductInformation.aspx?BrandKey=oreo&Site=1&Product=4400000820 |title=NabiscoWorld |date=January 1, 2006 |publisher=NabiscoWorld |access-date=March 2, 2011}}</ref> On December 6, 2011, Kraft announced that production of Oreo biscuits was to start in the UK \u2013 their Cadbury factory in [[Sheffield]], South Yorkshire, was selected to manufacture Oreo biscuits in Britain for the first time and production began there in May 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foodmanufacture.co.uk/Article/2013/05/10/Food-manufacturing-giant-starts-UK-Oreos-production |title=Mondel\u0113z starts UK manufacture of Oreos |date=May 9, 2013 |publisher=Food manufacture |language=en-GB |access-date=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOreo cookies were introduced onto the Indian market by [[Cadbury#India|Cadbury India]] in 2011. The biscuit industry in [[India]] is estimated to be worth around 1.8 billion dollars.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/cons-products/food/cadbury-enters-indian-biscuit-market-launches-oreo-brand/articleshow/7618573.cms |title=Cadbury enters Indian biscuit market, launches 'Oreo' brand |date=March 3, 2011 |via=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nIn Pakistan, Oreo is manufactured and sold by Lef\u00e8vre-Utile, also known as LU.\n\n== Production ==\n\nAccording to a statement from Kim McMiller, an Associate Director of Consumer Relations,{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} a two-stage process is used to produce Oreo cookies. The base cake dough is formed into the familiar round cookies by a rotary mold at the entrance of a {{convert|300|ft|m|-long|adj=mid}} oven.\n\nMost of the Oreo production was once carried out at the [[The Hershey Company|Hershey's]] factory in [[Hershey, Pennsylvania]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} By 2017, more than 40 billion Oreo cookies were being produced annually in 18 different countries around the world.<ref name=\"2017 Fact Sheet\" /> Oreo cookies for the [[Asia]]n markets are manufactured in India, Indonesia, and China, with the exception of the [[Japan]]ese market where they are manufactured locally under the brand \"[[Yamazaki Baking|Yamazaki]]-Nabisco\". Oreo cookies for the [[Europe]]an market are made in [[Spain]]; they are made in [[Russia]] (Mondel\u0113z Rus) for consumers in several [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS countries]]; and those sold in [[Australia]] are manufactured in Indonesia (previously China) or Spain, depending on the flavor. The version produced in Canada (sold under the Christie's brand) includes [[coconut oil]] and is sold exclusively in that region. Manufacture of Oreo biscuits began in [[Pakistan]] in early 2014, in collaboration with Mondel\u0113z International of the United States and Continental Biscuits Limited (CBL) of Pakistan, at the CBL production plant in [[Sukkur]].\n\n=== Oreo boycott ===\n{{main|Oreo boycott}}\nIn 2015, Mondel\u0113z announced its decision to close some of its American factories and [[offshoring|move production]] to [[economy of Mexico|Mexico]], prompting the [[Oreo boycott]].<ref name=inquirer>{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/inq-phillydeals/Oreo-maker-faces-billionaire-squeeze-labor-boycott-calls.html|title=Oreo sees support, but also backlash and boycott, for gay pride rainbow cookie |author=Joseph N. DiStefano |date= August 12, 2015|accessdate=July 9, 2015|publisher=Philly.com}}</ref> In 2016, after production had started in Mexico, the [[AFL-CIO]] encouraged the boycott and published consumer guidance to help identify which Mondel\u0113z products were made in Mexico.<ref name=afl>{{cite news |url=http://wp.unionlabel.org/2016/05/04/afl-cio-endorsement-of-bctgms-boycott-of-made-in-mexico-mondelez-international-snack-foods/ |title=AFL-CIO endorsement of BCTGM's boycott of \"Made in Mexico\" Mondelez International snack foods |author=Staff |date=May 4, 2016 |accessdate=May 4, 2016 |publisher=Afl-CIO}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Oreo cookies ceased production in [[Chicago]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.industryweek.com/workforce/chicagos-mondelez-plant-dunks-its-last-oreo |title=Chicago's Mondelez Plant Dunks Its Last Oreo |date=July 11, 2016 |publisher=IndustryWeek |access-date=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Ingredients ==\nThe ingredients of Oreo cookies have remained largely unchanged from the original, although numerous alternative varieties and flavors have emerged over time. The classic Oreo cookie is made using eleven main ingredients:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nutritionbeast.com/2013/10/oreo-cookie-ingredients-nutrition-history/|title=Splitting Open The Oreo Cookie: Ingredients, Nutrition & History|author=Lisa|publisher=nutritionbeast.com|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n# [[Sugar]]\n# Unbleached [[enriched flour]] ([[wheat flour]], [[niacin]], [[Iron#Health and diet|iron]], [[Thiamine#Occurrence in foods|thiamine mono-nitrate]] ([[thiamine|vitamin B<sub>1</sub>]]), [[riboflavin]] ([[riboflavin|vitamin B<sub>2</sub>]]), [[Folate|folic acid]])\n# [[Oleic acid|High oleic]] [[Canola#Canola oil|canola oil]] or [[palm oil]]\n# [[Cocoa solids|Cocoa]] ([[Dutch process chocolate|treated with alkali]])\n# [[High-fructose corn syrup]]\n# [[Leavening agent]] ([[Sodium bicarbonate|baking soda]] or [[monocalcium phosphate]])\n# [[Corn starch]]\n# [[Salt]]\n# [[Lecithin|Soy lecithin]]\n# [[Vanillin]]\n# [[Chocolate]]\n# [[Palm oil]]\n\n=== Nutrition ===\nOne six-pack of Oreos contains 270 [[Food energy|calories]], hence there are 45 calories in one cookie. Of these 45 calories, 27 come from [[carbohydrate]]s, 16.5 come from [[fat]], and 1.5 calories are provided by [[protein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livestrong.com/article/303766-how-many-calories-are-in-one-oreo-cookie/|title=How Many Calories Are in One Oreo Cookie?|first=Dakota|last=Karratti|publisher=livestrong.com|date=October 3, 2017|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDifferent Oreo flavors have varying amounts of carbohydrate: the chocolate fudge Oreo contains 13g of total carbohydrates (4% of the [[Reference Daily Intake|recommended daily intake]]) and 9g of sugars per serving of 3 cookies, while mint Oreos contain 25g of total carbohydrates and 18g of sugars per serving. Oreos contain small amounts of proteins and [[Mineral (nutrient)|minerals]] ([[iron]] and [[sodium]] are present) but they do not contain any [[vitamin]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fitbit.com/foods/Oreo+Cookie/16421 |title=Nutritional Information, Diet Info and Calories in Oreo Cookie |work=[[Fitbit|fitbit]] |access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sparkpeople.com/calories-in.asp?food=oreo+cookies |title=Nutrition Facts for Oreo cookies |website=sparkpeople.com |access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Varieties ==\n{{Main|List of Oreo varieties}}\n[[File:Nabisco-Double-Stuf-Oreos.jpg|link=File:Nabisco-Double-Stuf-Oreos.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Double Stuf Oreos]]\nIn addition to their traditional design of two chocolate wafers separated by a cr\u00e8me filling, Oreo cookies have been produced in a multitude of different varieties since they were first introduced. This list is only a guide to some of the more notable and popular types; not all are available in every country. The main varieties in the United States are:\n* ''Double Stuf Oreo'' \u2013 Introduced in 1974,<ref name=\"100th\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/Oreo_Global_Fact_Sheet_100th_Birthday_as_on_Jan_12_2012_FINAL.pdf |title=Fact Sheet: Oreo's 100th Birthday |publisher=Nabisco |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028094642/http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/Oreo_Global_Fact_Sheet_100th_Birthday_as_on_Jan_12_2012_FINAL.pdf |archive-date=October 28, 2013 |url-status = dead|access-date=July 20, 2012}}</ref> this variety has about double the normal amount of cr\u00e8me filling as the original. Available with various different flavors of cr\u00e8me filling: original, chocolate, peanut butter, cool mint, and birthday cake. In the UK these are called ''Double Stuff Oreos'' (with double 'f') and are only available in original flavor. The ''Golden Double Stuf Oreo'', featuring golden Oreo wafers with a double portion of original vanilla flavored cr\u00e8me, was introduced in 2009.\n* ''Football Oreo'' \u2013 (American/Canadian) [[football (ball)#American and Canadian football|football]]-shaped Oreo cookies, introduced in 1976.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}<!--Only available in US and Canada?-->\n* ''Big Stuf Oreo'' \u2013 A short-lived variety of the Oreo cookie, introduced in 1987<ref name=\"100th\" /> but discontinued in 1991, these were several times the size of a normal Oreo. Sold individually, each ''Big Stuf'' contained {{convert|250|Cal}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-07/features/8902150620_1_calorie-big-food-pattern/2 |title=The Era Of Gargantuan Gastronomy Belies Our Concern With Calories |last=Brataas, Anne |date=July 7, 1989 |access-date=July 20, 2012 |publisher=Chicago Tribune via Knight-Ridder}}</ref> and 13&nbsp;grams of fat.\n* ''Golden Oreo'' \u2013 First released in 2004,<ref name=\"2017 Fact Sheet\" /> this has \"golden\" vanilla flavored wafers on the outside of the cookie, as an alternative to the original chocolate flavored wafers. Available with various flavors of cr\u00e8me filling including original, chocolate, lemon and birthday cake. The chocolate cr\u00e8me variety, being the reverse of the original cookie, was known as the ''Uh-Oh Oreo'' until 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biscuitpeople.com/magazine/post/the-short-history-of-oreo-cookies|title=The Short History of Oreo Cookies|publisher=www.biscuitpeople.com|date=April 27, 2017|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Nabisco-Oreo-Minis.jpg|link=File:Nabisco-Oreo-Minis.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.9|Oreo Minis]]\n*''Oreo Mini'' \u2013 First introduced in 1991,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/24/business/rjr-nabisco-reports-neet-of-123-million-in-3d-quarter.html |title=RJR Nabisco Reports Neet Of $123 Million in 3d Quarter |last=Foltz |first=Kim |date=October 24, 1991 |access-date=March 2, 2011 |publisher=Nytimes.com}}</ref> these are miniature bite-sized versions of the original Oreo cookie. After being discontinued in the late 1990s, they were re-released in 2000 along with the redesigned 2001 [[Dodge Caravan]] minivan as part of a promotional tie-in with [[Daimler AG]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-28159731_ITM |title=New Mini Oreos Debut in New Mini Van |date=August 10, 2000 |work=PR Newswire}}</ref> Their packaging in the 1990s consisted of a \"miniaturized\" version of the full-sized cardboard tray and box used in Oreo packaging at the time. Their revised packaging consists of an aluminum foil bag.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}} ''Oreo Minis'' are available with various flavors of cr\u00e8me filling including original, chocolate, strawberry, and the new mint flavor which debuted in 2015. As well as the bagged version, they are also sold in Nabisco To-Go Cups, lidded plastic cups which fit into car cup-holders (in line with other Nabisco snacks that come in miniature form, such as Nutter Butters). A ''Golden Oreo Mini'' was also made available after the ''Golden Oreo'' was released in 2004. According to the Oreo website, the slogan of the ''Oreo Mini'' is \"Grab 'em. Pop 'em. Love 'em.\"\n* ''Mega Stuf Oreo'' \u2013 Released in February 2013, the ''Mega Stuf'' variety is similar to ''Double Stuf'', but with even more white cr\u00e8me filling. They come in both chocolate and golden wafer varieties.\n* ''Oreo Thins'' \u2013 Introduced in July 2015, this is a thin version of the original Oreo cookie. ''Thins'' come in both chocolate and golden wafer varieties, with various cr\u00e8me filling flavors including chocolate, mint, lemon and tiramisu. Each cookie contains only 40 calories; they are 66% thinner than the original version.\n* ''Chocolate Oreo'' \u2013 Simply an Oreo cookie with chocolate cr\u00e8me filling instead of the original vanilla flavored white cr\u00e8me filling.<!--Introduced 2011-->\n* ''Mint Oreo'' \u2013 A variety of Oreo with two chocolate wafers separated by a mint flavored cr\u00e8me filling.<!--Introduced when?-->\n* ''The Most Stuf'' \u2013 Introduced in January 2019, a limited edition Oreo with approximately four times the amount of cr\u00e8me filling of a standard Oreo.\n\nSpecial edition ''Double Stuf Oreo'' cookies are produced during springtime, and around [[Halloween]] and [[Christmas]]. These have colored frosting reflecting the current holiday: blue or yellow for springtime; orange for Halloween; and red or green for the Christmas holiday. One side of each seasonal cookie is stamped with an appropriate design; the spring cookies feature flowers, butterflies, etc., while the Halloween editions feature a jack o'lantern, ghost, cat, flock of bats, or broom-riding witch.<!--What designs are featured on the Christmas ones?--> The 2017 ''Halloween Oreo'' broke with this tradition, having orange-colored cr\u00e8me filling (albeit with classic vanilla flavor) but carrying no seasonal designs.\n\nIn some countries, Oreos come in a variety of flavors that are not familiar to the U.S. market. For example, ''Green Tea Oreos'' are only available in China and Japan, while ''Lemon Ice Oreos'' were only ever introduced in Japan.\n\n=== Limited editions ===\n[[File:Mr. Christie, you definitely make good cookies! (2523264708).jpg|thumb|Close-up view of a golden Oreo cookie wafer]]\nBeginning in the early 2010s, Oreo began releasing [[Limited edition candy|limited edition]] runs of cookies with more exotic flavors. These \"limited editions\" typically appear in stores for a short period and are then discontinued, although some varieties have since resurfaced, for example: ''Reese's Oreos'' returned for a second limited run after they were first introduced for a limited period in 2014; and ''Birthday Cake Oreos'', originally introduced in 2012, have since become permanently available.<ref name=\"List\">{{cite web |url=http://www.glamour.com/story/special-oreos-flavors-limited-edition |title=A Comprehensive List of Every Special Oreo Flavor, Ever |last=Clinton |first=Leah Melby |date=June 17, 2015 |publisher=Glamour |access-date=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Some limited editions are only made available at certain retailers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foodbeast.com/news/blueberry-oreos-fruity-crisps/ |title=NEW OREO FLAVORS: Blueberry Pie & Fruity Crisps |last=Ayerouth |first=Elie |date=May 26, 2016 |publisher=foodbeast.com |access-date=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLimited edition runs usually feature a cr\u00e8me filling that has been flavored to replicate the taste of a specific fruit or dessert, from familiar flavors such as [[lemon]] or [[Mentha|mint]], to the more specific and unusual flavors of [[blueberry pie]] or [[red velvet cake]]. They may also incorporate different varieties of cookie wafer, for example ''Cinnamon-Bun Oreos'' featured [[cinnamon]] flavored cookies and \"frosting flavored cr\u00e8me\". In recent years, some limited editions have paired Oreos with other recognizable [[confectionery]] brands, including [[Reese's Peanut Butter Cups|Reese's]], [[Swedish Fish]], and [[Peeps]].\n\nSome examples of limited edition Oreos are:\n* ''Birthday Cake Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition, available from February to July 2012, to celebrate Oreo's 100th birthday. Made up of two chocolate Oreo cookies with a [[birthday cake]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling and sprinkles inside. On one of the two cookies, the traditional design was replaced with a birthday candle and the words \"OREO 100\". The birthday cake flavor has since been reintroduced, with a \"double stuf\" amount of cr\u00e8me filling, in both chocolate and golden Oreo varieties, except that the cookies no longer display the \"OREO 100\" print.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.snackworks.com/search/product-results.aspx?searchText=oreo+birthday+cake |title=Product Search Results \u2013 Snackworks |publisher=Snackworks |access-date=October 13, 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Lemon Twist Oreo'' \u2013 First released in 2012 as a limited edition, reintroduced in 2013, made up of two golden Oreo cookies with a lemon flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Neapolitan Oreo'' \u2013 Released for a limited time in 2012, consisting of three golden Oreo cookies with a double sandwich of chocolate and strawberry cr\u00e8me fillings. This version was reminiscent of [[Neapolitan ice cream]].\n* ''Watermelon Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition for the summer of 2013, made up of two golden Oreo cookies with [[watermelon]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Strawberries n' Creme Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in 2013, made up of two golden Oreo cookies with a cr\u00e8me filling consisting of two halves, one strawberry flavored and one similar to traditional Oreo cr\u00e8me.\n* ''Fruit Punch Oreo'' \u2013 Released for a limited time in 2014, featuring golden Oreo cookies filled with fruit punch flavored cr\u00e8me.\n* ''Cookie Dough Oreo'' \u2013 Released in March 2014, a limited edition featuring chocolate cookies with [[cookie dough]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/12/dining/the-cookie-dough-oreo.html?_r=0 |title=The Cookie Dough Oreo |last=Moss |first=Michael |date=March 11, 2014 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n* ''Root Beer Float Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in July 2014, made up of two gold Oreo cookies filled with [[root beer]] flavored cr\u00e8me.\n* ''Pumpkin Spice Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in September 2014, made up of two gold Oreo cookies with [[Pumpkin pie spice|pumpkin spice]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Red Velvet Oreo'' \u2013 First released in February 2015 as a limited edition, since reintroduced, featuring red Oreo cookies with cream cheese flavored cr\u00e8me filling. This version was designed to emulate the popular [[red velvet cake]].\n* ''Key Lime Pie Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in July 2015, made of two [[Graham flour|graham]] flavored Oreo cookies filled with [[key lime]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Cinnamon Bun Oreo'' \u2013 Released in January 2016 as a limited edition, made up of two cinnamon flavored cookies filled with [[Icing (food)|frosting]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling. This version was designed to emulate the [[Cinnamon roll|cinnamon bun]].\n* ''S'mores Oreo'' \u2013 Inspired by the [[S'more|traditional campfire snack]] and released as a limited edition in summer 2016, this version was made with graham flavored cookies and a double layer of cr\u00e8me filling, one layer chocolate flavored and one layer [[marshmallow]] flavored.\n* ''Fruity Crisp Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in June 2016, consisting of two golden Oreo cookies with a fruity and colorful rice crisp cr\u00e8me filling, similar to [[Pebbles cereal|Fruity Pebbles]].\n* ''Blueberry Pie Oreo'' \u2013 Also released in June 2016 as a limited edition, and then reintroduced in 2017, made with graham flavored cookie wafers and a blueberry flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Swedish Fish Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition in August 2016, made up of two chocolate Oreo cookies with a red cr\u00e8me filling, flavored to resemble the red-colored [[Swedish Fish]] candy. These were originally released exclusively through [[Kroger]] stores (in the U.S.)\n* ''Peeps Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in February 2017 for the Easter season, consisting of two golden Oreo cookies filled with pink \"marshmallow Peeps\" flavored cr\u00e8me\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/take-a-peep-at-these-new-oreo-flavors_us_58ab1b5fe4b07602ad56c7be |title=Peeps-Flavored Oreos Are Here And We Don\u2019t Know Who Will Eat Them |last=Ledbetter |first=Carly |date=February 2, 2017 |publisher=The Huffington Post |access-date=February 21, 2017}}</ref> A second version was released in February 2018, instead made with Peeps-embossed chocolate cookies and purple \"marshmallow Peeps\" flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Waffles & Syrup Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in May 2017, made with golden Oreo cookies and featuring a ring of vanilla cr\u00e8me with a blob of [[maple syrup]] flavored cr\u00e8me in the center. Exclusive to [[Albertsons]] stores (in the U.S.)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.today.com/food/oreo-waffles-syrup-flavor-hits-select-stores-week-t111243 |title=Oreos for breakfast?! Meet the new Waffles & Syrup flavor |date=May 10, 2017 |work=USA Today}}</ref>\n* ''Chocolate Hazelnut Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition on January 1, 2018, consisting of golden Oreo cookies with a \"[[Nutella]]-like\" flavored cr\u00e8me filling.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.popsugar.com/food/Chocolate-Hazelnut-Oreos-44112889 |title=Nutella-Lovers Will Lose Their Sh*t Over the New Chocolate Hazelnut Oreos! |work=Popsugar.food |access-date=March 7, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Salted Caramel Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition in 2018, consisting of golden Oreo cookies with a salted caramel flavor cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Firework Oreo'' \u2013 Released around the Fourth of July in the United States, consisting of classic Oreo cookies with Pop Rocks candy within the cr\u00e8me.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4770605/firework-oreos/|title=The New 'Firework' Oreos Are Like Sparklers In Your Mouth|date=May 8, 2017|first=Raisa|last=Bruner|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n*''Peppermint Bark Oreo''  \u2013 Released as a limited edition in October 2018 (for the 2018 holiday season), consisting of a \"double stuf\" amount of peppermint flavored cr\u00e8me with red sugar crystals and the original chocolate Oreo cookies.\n*''Easter Egg Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition in January 2019 (for the Easter season), consisting of chocolate Oreo cookies in an oval shape to resemble eggs, with purple-colored cr\u00e8me filling and four different Easter-related designs: a bunny in a basket, a baby chick wearing bunny ears, and spots and stripes to resemble the painting of an Easter egg.\n*''Chocolate Marshmallow'' \u2013 Released in January 2020, includes marshmallow pieces in the cookie and chocolate marshmallow cr\u00e8me filling.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/05/business/oreo-new-flavors-caramel-coconut-chocolate-marshmallow-trnd/index.html|title=Oreo has two new flavors for the new year: Caramel Coconut and Chocolate Marshmallow|first=Melissa |last=Gray|website=CNN|access-date=2020-01-06|date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n*''Caramel Coconut'' \u2013 Released in January 2020, has caramel cr\u00e8me filling with coconut flavor and coconut pieces.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Supreme Oreo''- Released in March 2020, double stuffed Oreo branded by Supreme.\n\n== Use as an insult ==\n{{See also|Acting white}}\nThe term \"Oreo\" has been used as a disparaging and offensive reference to a black person who is perceived or judged to [[Acting white|act]] in a \"white manner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/oreo|title=Dictionary.com definition|work=dictionary.com|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref> The insult may be levied as an accusation that the person perpetuates the \"un-level playing field for blacks\". The metaphor is based on the implication that the person is like the cookie, \"black on the outside and white on the inside\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-01-14/news/9801140635_1_john-lombardi-uhlfelder-oreo |title=UF President Apologizes For Remark |last=Griffin |first=Michael |last2=James |first2=Joni |date=January 14, 1998 |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Food}}\n* [[Cookies and cream]]\n* [[Newman-O's]]\n* [[Hydrox]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Oreo cookies}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.oreo.com}}\n* [http://www.oreo.co.uk/ Official UK website]\n* [http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodcookies.html#oreos Additional history notes on Oreo cookies]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{Mondelez}}\n\n[[Category:Oreo| ]]\n[[Category:Nabisco brands]]\n[[Category:Mondel\u0113z brands]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1912]]\n[[Category:Cookie sandwiches]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2018}}\n{{short description|Chocolate sandwich cookie with creme filling.}}\n\n{{infobox brand\n| name           = Oreo\n| logo           = [[File:Oreo Cookie logo.png|upright=1.023|frameless]]\n| image          = [[File:Oreo-Two-Cookies.jpg|upright=1.023|frameless]]\n| caption        = Two Oreo cookies \n| type           = [[Sandwich cookie]]\n| currentowner   = [[Nabisco]] ([[Mondelez International]]){{efn|name=\"2012 Kraft split\"|Nabisco was a subsidiary of [[Kraft Foods Inc.|Kraft Foods]] until 2012 when the global snack division of Kraft Foods was rebranded as Mondel\u0113z International.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/03/21/kraft-mondelez-and-the-art-of-corporate-rebranding/ |title=Kraft, 'Mondelez' and the Art of Corporate Rebranding |date=21 March 2012 |first=Michael J. |last=de la Merced |work=[[The New York Times]] (DealB%k)}}</ref>}} and [[Cadbury]] and [[Milka]]\n| origin         = [[United States]]\n| introduced     = {{start date and age|1912|03|06}}<ref name=\"2017 Fact Sheet\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mondelezinternational.com/en/~/media/MondelezCorporate/Uploads/downloads/OREO_Fact_Sheet.pdf |title=2017 Fact Sheet |work=[[Mondel\u0113z International]] |access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n| discontinued   =\n| related        =\n| markets        = Worldwide\n| previousowners =\n| trademarkregistrations =\n| ambassadors    =\n| tagline        = \"Wonderfilled\"<br/>\"Milk's favorite cookie\" <br/> \"Only Oreo\"\n| website        = [http://www.oreo.com/ Oreo.com]\n}}\n\nAn '''Oreo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0254\u02d0r|i|o\u028a}}) is a [[sandwich cookie]] consisting of two (usually chocolate) [[wafer]]s<!--Please get consensus on talk page before changing \"wafer\" to anything else.--> with a sweet [[Cream#Other items called \"cream\"|cr\u00e8me]] filling. Introduced in 1912, Oreo is the best selling cookie brand in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foodprocessing.com/articles/2005/562/?start=5|title=Top 10 Food Brands of 2005 |last=Toops |first=Diane |date=July 1, 2005 |publisher=www.foodprocessing.com |access-date=April 6, 2012|quote=In the enviable position of being the No. 1 selling cookie in America since its introduction in 1912, the Oreo, made by Nabisco, East Hanover, N.J., a brand of Kraft Foods, was a true innovation \u2013 two chocolate disks with a cr\u00e8me filling in between.}}</ref> As of 2018, the version sold in the U.S. is made by the [[Nabisco]] division of [[Mondelez International]].\n\nOreos are available in over one hundred countries;<ref name=\"2017 Fact Sheet\" /> in some countries, such as the United Kingdom, they are referred to as ''Oreo biscuits''. Many varieties of Oreo cookies have been produced, and limited-edition runs have become popular in the 21st century.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe origin of the name Oreo is unknown, but there are many hypotheses, including derivations from the French word ''or'', meaning gold, or from an Ancient [[Greek language|Greek]] root meaning mountain.<ref name=\"Imponderables\">{{Cite book |title=Why do clocks run clockwise? and other Imponderables |last=Feldman |first=David |publisher=Harper & Row Publishers |year=1987 |isbn=978-0-06-095463-5 |location=New York City |pages=173\u2013174 |author-link=David Feldman (author)}}</ref> Others believe that the cookie was named Oreo simply because the name was short and easy to pronounce.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://history1900s.about.com/od/1910s/a/oreohistory.htm |title=History of the Oreo Cookie |publisher=About |access-date=October 13, 2014}}</ref> Another theory, proposed by food writer Stella Parks, is that the name derives from the Latin ''[[Oreodaphne]]'', a genus of the [[Lauraceae|laurel]] family. She observes that the original design of the Oreo includes a laurel wreath; and the names of several of Nabisco's cookies at the time of the original Oreo had botanical derivations, including [[Avena]], [[Lotus (genus)|Lotus]], and Helicon (from ''[[Heliconia]]'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seriouseats.com/2017/08/history-of-oreos-bravetart-cookbook.html|title=How Oreos Got Their Name: The Rise of an American Icon|last=Parks|first=Stella|origyear=15 August 2017|date= 5 February 2019|website=|publisher=Serious Eats|archive-url=|archivedate=|accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=BraveTart|last=Parks|first=Stella|publisher=W. W. Norton & Co.|year=2017|isbn=978-0-393-23986-7|location=New York|pages=209\u2013210}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Vector Oreo.svg|thumb|left|upright=0.85|Representation of the [[trademarked]] pattern [[Paper embossing|embossed]] onto the face of an Oreo cookie]]\n\n=== Twentieth century ===\nThe \"Oreo Biscuit\"<!-- this was original name; wasn't renamed to \"cookie\" until later--> was first developed and produced by the National Biscuit Company (today known as [[Nabisco]]) in 1912<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/Brands/largest-brands/brands-O/oreo.aspx |title=Oreo |date=January 3, 2011 |publisher=[[Kraft Foods]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326155619/http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/brands/largest-brands/brands-o/oreo.aspx |archive-date=March 26, 2012 |access-date=March 2, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodcookies.html#oreos |title=The Food Timeline: history notes--cookies, crackers & biscuits |access-date=March 3, 2010}}</ref> at its [[Chelsea, Manhattan]] factory in the current-day [[Chelsea Market]] complex, located on [[Ninth Avenue (Manhattan)|Ninth Avenue]] between 15th and 16th Streets.<ref name=\"nydn\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-05-20/news/31791204_1_oreo-cookies-nabisco-chocolate-covered |title=Celebrating the life of 'Mr. Oreo' |last=Hinkley |first=David |date=May 20, 2012 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |access-date=June 2, 2012}}</ref> Today, this same block of Ninth Avenue is known as \"Oreo Way\".<ref name=\"nydn\" /> The name Oreo was first trademarked on March 14, 1912.<ref name=\"patentlisting\">{{Cite web |url=http://trademarks.justia.com/710/62/oreo-71062166.html |title=OREO \u2013 Trademark Details |access-date=July 10, 2012}}</ref> It was launched as an imitation of the [[Hydrox]] cookie manufactured by [[Sunshine Biscuits|Sunshine]] company, which was introduced in 1908.<ref name=\"Lukas\">{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1999/03/15/256478/index.htm |title=Oreos to Hydrox: Resistance Is Futile |last=Paul Lukas |date=March 15, 1999 |work=Fortune |access-date=November 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe original design on the face of the Oreo featured a wreath around the edge of the cookie and the name \"OREO\" in the center.<ref name=\"post\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/food/the_big_NESHrxY07rFd4bph3tkvnO |title=The Big O: The Chelsea-born Oreo cookie celebrates its 100th birthday |last=Eber, H. |date=February 26, 2012 |publisher=[[New York Post]] |pages=44\u201345}}</ref> In the United States, they were sold for 25 cents a pound (453&nbsp;g) in novelty metal canisters with clear glass tops. The first Oreo was sold on March 6, 1912, to a grocer in [[Hoboken, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"100 years\">{{Cite web |url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/03/06/100-years-of-oreos-9-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-iconic-cookie/ |title=100 Years of Oreos: 9 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About the Iconic Cookie |last=Grossman |first=Samantha |date=March 6, 2012 |work=Time}}</ref>\n\nThe Oreo Biscuit was renamed in 1921 to \"Oreo Sandwich\";<ref name=\"Imponderables\" /> in 1948, the name was changed to \"Oreo Cr\u00e8me Sandwich\"; and in 1974 it became the \"Oreo Chocolate Sandwich Cookie\",<ref name=\"Imponderables\" /> the name that has remained to this day. A new design for the face of the cookie was launched in 1924;<ref name=\"post\" /> the modern-day Oreo design was developed in 1952 by William A. Turnier,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indyweek.com/indyweek/the-story-of-william-a-turnier-the-man-who-designed-the-oreo-cookie/Content?oid=2640604 |title=The story of William A. Turnier, the man who designed the Oreo cookie |last=Wallace |first=Emily |date=August 24, 2011 |publisher=Indyweek}}</ref> incorporating the Nabisco logo. In 1920, a second lemon cr\u00e8me-filled variety of the Oreo was introduced, as an alternative to the white cr\u00e8me-filled variety, but this was discontinued in 1924<ref name=\"post\" /> and the original flavor was the only version available for the next several decades.<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets |last=Goldstein |first=Darra |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-19-931339-6 |pages=494 |author-link=Darra Goldstein}}</ref>\n\nThe modern Oreo cookie filling was developed by Nabisco's principal [[food scientist]], [[Sam Porcello]],<ref name=\"nydn\" /><ref name=\"time\">{{Cite news |url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2012/05/24/farewell-mr-oreo-man-who-invented-oreo-filling-dies-at-76/ |title=RIP, 'Mr.Oreo': Man Who Invented Oreo Filling Dies At 76 |last=Locker |first=Melissa |date=May 24, 2012 |work=[[Time Magazine]] |access-date=June 2, 2012}}</ref> who retired from Nabisco in 1993.<ref name=\"nydn\" /> Porcello held five patents directly related to his work on the Oreo;<ref name=\"time\" /> he also created a range of Oreo cookies that were covered in [[dark chocolate]] and [[white chocolate]].<ref name=\"nydn\" /><ref name=\"time\" /> In the early 1990s, health concerns prompted Nabisco to replace the [[lard]] in the cr\u00e8me filling with [[partially hydrogenated vegetable oil]].<ref name=\"lardtransfat\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-oreo-3,0,3862619,full.story |title=For every fad, another cookie |last=Alexander |first=Delroy |date=August 23, 2005 |work=Chicago Tribune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016205310/http://www.chicagotribune.com/chi-oreo-3,0,3862619,full.story |archive-date=October 16, 2013 |url-status = dead|last2=Manier |first2=Jeremy |last3=Callahan |first3=Patricia}}</ref> Oreo cookies are popular with people that have certain dietary restrictions, such as [[Veganism|vegans]], as the cr\u00e8me filling does not use any animal products.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/12/surprising-vegan-foods_n_3895853.html |title=12 Surprising Vegan Foods |date=September 13, 2013 |publisher=The Huffington Post}}</ref> However, there is still a risk of cross-contamination from other dairy-containing products made in the same production areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oreo.co.uk/faq |title=Frequently asked questions: Is Oreo suitable for vegans? |access-date=June 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Twenty-first century ===\nIn January 2006, Nabisco replaced the [[trans fat]] in the Oreo cookie with non-[[Vegetable oil#Hydrogenated oils|hydrogenated vegetable oil]].<ref name=\"lardtransfat\" /><ref name=\"Harvard\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/reviews/transfats.html |title=Trans fatty acids and coronary heart disease |access-date=September 14, 2006 |vauthors=Ascherio A, Stampfer MJ, Willett WC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bantransfats.com/theoreocase.html |title=The Campaign to Ban Partially Hydrogenated Oils |publisher=Ban Trans Fats |access-date=November 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nNabisco began a marketing campaign in 2008, advertising the use of Oreo cookies in an [[online game]] called DSRL (which stands for \"Double Stuf Racing League\"), introduced the week before [[Super Bowl XLII]]. DSRL had been endorsed by football brothers [[Peyton Manning]] and [[Eli Manning]];<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Manning Brothers Take On 'Second Sport' With a Twist, Lick and Dunk |date=January 14, 2009 |publisher=PRNewswire |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/manning-brothers-take-on-second-sport-with-a-twist-lick-and-dunk-56895127.html |access-date=March 27, 2018}}</ref> the [[Williams sisters]], [[Venus Williams|Venus]] and [[Serena Williams|Serena]], also joined, challenging the Mannings to a race that was aired in an advertisement on January 18, 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nabiscoworld.com/oreo/dsrl/ |title=Double Stuf Racing League |publisher=Nabisco |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090317095740/http://www.nabiscoworld.com/oreo/dsrl/ |archive-date=March 17, 2009 |access-date=June 28, 2017}}</ref> Another campaign was launched for ''Golden Double Stuf Oreo'' cookies, in which the Manning brothers were challenged by [[Donald Trump]] and a character called \"Double Trump\", played by [[Darrell Hammond]]; this competition aired on January 24, 2010. The Mannings won both races. Another advertisement featured a \"Hooded Menace\" threatening to take over the DSRL, with Eli Manning and Stufy (the DSRL mascot) needing some help, which aired on September 14, 2010. Six days later, it was announced that [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and [[Apolo Ohno]] had joined Oreo's DSRL veterans Eli Manning and Venus Williams.\n[[File:Oreo pride poster.jpg|thumb|The 2012 rainbow Oreo advertisement supporting Pride month]]\nIn April 2011, Oreo announced its special edition Oreo cookies with blue cr\u00e8me to promote the 2011 3D computer-animated movie ''[[Rio (2011 film)|Rio]]''. The promotion included stickers inside each package of cookies. Two contests were also announced: by completing an album of stickers, consumers could win three movie passes and medium snack bar combos; and prize stickers could be found in winning packages, including a trip to [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[backpacks]], cinema passes for a year, and [[Polarized 3D system|3D glasses]]. The promotion was available in [[Ecuador]], [[Peru]], and [[Colombia]], and ended on May 30, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pe.promogana.net/2011/04/concurso-promo-oreo-gana-paquetes-de.html |title=Concurso Promo Oreo, gana paquetes de cine, viaje a Rio, mochilas y m\u00e1s |date=April 8, 2011 |publisher=Promogana |access-date=April 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Oreo posted an advertisement displaying an Oreo cookie with rainbow colored cr\u00e8me to celebrate [[Gay pride#LGBT Pride Month|LGBT Pride month]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/06/26/oreo-unveils-rainbow-cookie-image-for-pride/ |title=Oreo unveils rainbow cookie image for Pride |last=Gray |first=Stephen |date=June 26, 2012 |publisher=[[Pink news]] |access-date=June 30, 2012}}</ref> the cookie itself was fictional and was not being manufactured or made available for sale. The advertisement prompted some negative comments, but Kraft stood by their promotion, stating that \"Kraft Foods has a proud history of celebrating diversity and inclusiveness. We feel the Oreo ad is a fun reflection of our values.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/06/26/kraft-oreo-gaypride-idUSL2E8HQH6120120626 |title=Rainbow-colored Oreo filled with controversy |date=June 26, 2012 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=June 30, 2012}}</ref> This was followed during 2012 by a series of adverts commemorating other holidays and events, including a blue, white, and red cr\u00e8me Oreo to honor [[Bastille Day]], a stream of cookie crumbs marking the appearance of the [[Southern Delta Aquariids|Delta Aquariids]] [[meteor shower]], and a cookie with a jagged bite taken out of it to promote [[Shark Week]] on The [[Discovery Channel]].\n\n== International distribution ==\nOreo cookies are distributed worldwide through a variety of sales and marketing channels. As their popularity continues to grow, so too does the amount of distribution that comes with it. According to the [[Kraft Foods Inc.|Kraft Foods]] company, the Oreo is the \"World's Best Selling Cookie\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/Oreo_Global_Fact_Sheet_100th_Birthday_as_on_Jan_12_2012_FINAL.pdf |title=Oreo Global Fact Sheet|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028094642/http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/Oreo_Global_Fact_Sheet_100th_Birthday_as_on_Jan_12_2012_FINAL.pdf|archive-date=October 28, 2013 |url-status = dead}}</ref> In March 2012, [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] magazine reported that Oreo cookies were available in more than 100 different countries. Overall, it is estimated that since the Oreo cookie's inception in 1912, over 450 billion Oreos have been produced worldwide.<ref name=\"100 years\" />\n\n''Oreo biscuits'' (as they are known in the United Kingdom) were first introduced into Britain through the supermarket chain [[Sainsbury's]]. For several years, this was the only store in the UK to stock the Oreo \u2013 until May 2008, when Kraft decided to fully launch the Oreo across the whole of the UK. It was repackaged in the more familiar British tube design, accompanied by a [[\u00a3]]4.5M television advertising campaign based around the \"twist, lick, [[Dunking (biscuit)|dunk]]\" catchphrase.<ref name=\"BBCMay2008\">{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/7376123.stm |title=Can Oreo win over British biscuit lovers? |publisher=BBC News Magazine |date=May 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK, Kraft partnered with [[McDonald's]] to introduce the Oreo [[McFlurry#Desserts|McFlurry]] (which was already on sale in several other countries) into a number of McDonald's locations during its annual ''Great Tastes of America'' promotions; in October 2015, the Oreo McFlurry became a permanent menu item at McDonald's in the UK. An Oreo flavored \"Krushem\" drink was also on sale in [[KFC]] stores across Britain.\n\nThe ingredients of the British Oreo biscuit (as listed on the UK Oreo website) are slightly different from those of the US Oreo cookie. Unlike the US version, the British Oreo originally contained [[whey powder]], which was not suitable for people with [[lactose intolerance]]. Additionally, as the whey powder was sourced from cheese made with [[Rennet|calf rennet]], the British version was also unsuitable for [[Vegetarianism|vegetarians]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nabiscoworld.com/Brands/ProductInformation.aspx?BrandKey=oreo&Site=1&Product=4400000820 |title=NabiscoWorld |date=January 1, 2006 |publisher=NabiscoWorld |access-date=March 2, 2011}}</ref> On December 6, 2011, Kraft announced that production of Oreo biscuits was to start in the UK \u2013 their Cadbury factory in [[Sheffield]], South Yorkshire, was selected to manufacture Oreo biscuits in Britain for the first time and production began there in May 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foodmanufacture.co.uk/Article/2013/05/10/Food-manufacturing-giant-starts-UK-Oreos-production |title=Mondel\u0113z starts UK manufacture of Oreos |date=May 9, 2013 |publisher=Food manufacture |language=en-GB |access-date=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOreo cookies were introduced onto the Indian market by [[Cadbury#India|Cadbury India]] in 2011. The biscuit industry in [[India]] is estimated to be worth around 1.8 billion dollars.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/cons-products/food/cadbury-enters-indian-biscuit-market-launches-oreo-brand/articleshow/7618573.cms |title=Cadbury enters Indian biscuit market, launches 'Oreo' brand |date=March 3, 2011 |via=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nIn Pakistan, Oreo is manufactured and sold by Lef\u00e8vre-Utile, also known as LU.\n\n== Production ==\n\nAccording to a statement from Kim McMiller, an Associate Director of Consumer Relations,{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} a two-stage process is used to produce Oreo cookies. The base cake dough is formed into the familiar round cookies by a rotary mold at the entrance of a {{convert|300|ft|m|-long|adj=mid}} oven.\n\nMost of the Oreo production was once carried out at the [[The Hershey Company|Hershey's]] factory in [[Hershey, Pennsylvania]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} By 2017, more than 40 billion Oreo cookies were being produced annually in 18 different countries around the world.<ref name=\"2017 Fact Sheet\" /> Oreo cookies for the [[Asia]]n markets are manufactured in India, Indonesia, and China, with the exception of the [[Japan]]ese market where they are manufactured locally under the brand \"[[Yamazaki Baking|Yamazaki]]-Nabisco\". Oreo cookies for the [[Europe]]an market are made in [[Spain]]; they are made in [[Russia]] (Mondel\u0113z Rus) for consumers in several [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS countries]]; and those sold in [[Australia]] are manufactured in Indonesia (previously China) or Spain, depending on the flavor. The version produced in Canada (sold under the Christie's brand) includes [[coconut oil]] and is sold exclusively in that region. Manufacture of Oreo biscuits began in [[Pakistan]] in early 2014, in collaboration with Mondel\u0113z International of the United States and Continental Biscuits Limited (CBL) of Pakistan, at the CBL production plant in [[Sukkur]].\n\n=== Oreo boycott ===\n{{main|Oreo boycott}}\nIn 2015, Mondel\u0113z announced its decision to close some of its American factories and [[offshoring|move production]] to [[economy of Mexico|Mexico]], prompting the [[Oreo boycott]].<ref name=inquirer>{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/inq-phillydeals/Oreo-maker-faces-billionaire-squeeze-labor-boycott-calls.html|title=Oreo sees support, but also backlash and boycott, for gay pride rainbow cookie |author=Joseph N. DiStefano |date= August 12, 2015|accessdate=July 9, 2015|publisher=Philly.com}}</ref> In 2016, after production had started in Mexico, the [[AFL-CIO]] encouraged the boycott and published consumer guidance to help identify which Mondel\u0113z products were made in Mexico.<ref name=afl>{{cite news |url=http://wp.unionlabel.org/2016/05/04/afl-cio-endorsement-of-bctgms-boycott-of-made-in-mexico-mondelez-international-snack-foods/ |title=AFL-CIO endorsement of BCTGM's boycott of \"Made in Mexico\" Mondelez International snack foods |author=Staff |date=May 4, 2016 |accessdate=May 4, 2016 |publisher=Afl-CIO}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Oreo cookies ceased production in [[Chicago]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.industryweek.com/workforce/chicagos-mondelez-plant-dunks-its-last-oreo |title=Chicago's Mondelez Plant Dunks Its Last Oreo |date=July 11, 2016 |publisher=IndustryWeek |access-date=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Ingredients ==\nThe ingredients of Oreo cookies have remained largely unchanged from the original, although numerous alternative varieties and flavors have emerged over time. The classic Oreo cookie is made using eleven main ingredients:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nutritionbeast.com/2013/10/oreo-cookie-ingredients-nutrition-history/|title=Splitting Open The Oreo Cookie: Ingredients, Nutrition & History|author=Lisa|publisher=nutritionbeast.com|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n# [[Sugar]]\n# Unbleached [[enriched flour]] ([[wheat flour]], [[niacin]], [[Iron#Health and diet|iron]], [[Thiamine#Occurrence in foods|thiamine mono-nitrate]] ([[thiamine|vitamin B<sub>1</sub>]]), [[riboflavin]] ([[riboflavin|vitamin B<sub>2</sub>]]), [[Folate|folic acid]])\n# [[Oleic acid|High oleic]] [[Canola#Canola oil|canola oil]] or [[palm oil]]\n# [[Cocoa solids|Cocoa]] ([[Dutch process chocolate|treated with alkali]])\n# [[High-fructose corn syrup]]\n# [[Leavening agent]] ([[Sodium bicarbonate|baking soda]] or [[monocalcium phosphate]])\n# [[Corn starch]]\n# [[Salt]]\n# [[Lecithin|Soy lecithin]]\n# [[Vanillin]]\n# [[Chocolate]]\n# [[Palm oil]]\n\n=== Nutrition ===\nOne six-pack of Oreos contains 270 [[Food energy|calories]], hence there are 45 calories in one cookie. Of these 45 calories, 27 come from [[carbohydrate]]s, 16.5 come from [[fat]], and 1.5 calories are provided by [[protein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livestrong.com/article/303766-how-many-calories-are-in-one-oreo-cookie/|title=How Many Calories Are in One Oreo Cookie?|first=Dakota|last=Karratti|publisher=livestrong.com|date=October 3, 2017|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDifferent Oreo flavors have varying amounts of carbohydrate: the chocolate fudge Oreo contains 13g of total carbohydrates (4% of the [[Reference Daily Intake|recommended daily intake]]) and 9g of sugars per serving of 3 cookies, while mint Oreos contain 25g of total carbohydrates and 18g of sugars per serving. Oreos contain small amounts of proteins and [[Mineral (nutrient)|minerals]] ([[iron]] and [[sodium]] are present) but they do not contain any [[vitamin]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fitbit.com/foods/Oreo+Cookie/16421 |title=Nutritional Information, Diet Info and Calories in Oreo Cookie |work=[[Fitbit|fitbit]] |access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sparkpeople.com/calories-in.asp?food=oreo+cookies |title=Nutrition Facts for Oreo cookies |website=sparkpeople.com |access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Varieties ==\n{{Main|List of Oreo varieties}}\n[[File:Nabisco-Double-Stuf-Oreos.jpg|link=File:Nabisco-Double-Stuf-Oreos.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Double Stuf Oreos]]\nIn addition to their traditional design of two chocolate wafers separated by a cr\u00e8me filling, Oreo cookies have been produced in a multitude of different varieties since they were first introduced. This list is only a guide to some of the more notable and popular types; not all are available in every country. The main varieties in the United States are:\n* ''Double Stuf Oreo'' \u2013 Introduced in 1974,<ref name=\"100th\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/Oreo_Global_Fact_Sheet_100th_Birthday_as_on_Jan_12_2012_FINAL.pdf |title=Fact Sheet: Oreo's 100th Birthday |publisher=Nabisco |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028094642/http://www.kraftfoodscompany.com/sitecollectiondocuments/pdf/Oreo_Global_Fact_Sheet_100th_Birthday_as_on_Jan_12_2012_FINAL.pdf |archive-date=October 28, 2013 |url-status = dead|access-date=July 20, 2012}}</ref> this variety has about double the normal amount of cr\u00e8me filling as the original. Available with various different flavors of cr\u00e8me filling: original, chocolate, peanut butter, cool mint, and birthday cake. In the UK these are called ''Double Stuff Oreos'' (with double 'f') and are only available in original flavor. The ''Golden Double Stuf Oreo'', featuring golden Oreo wafers with a double portion of original vanilla flavored cr\u00e8me, was introduced in 2009.\n* ''Football Oreo'' \u2013 (American/Canadian) [[football (ball)#American and Canadian football|football]]-shaped Oreo cookies, introduced in 1976.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}<!--Only available in US and Canada?-->\n* ''Big Stuf Oreo'' \u2013 A short-lived variety of the Oreo cookie, introduced in 1987<ref name=\"100th\" /> but discontinued in 1991, these were several times the size of a normal Oreo. Sold individually, each ''Big Stuf'' contained {{convert|250|Cal}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1989-07-07/features/8902150620_1_calorie-big-food-pattern/2 |title=The Era Of Gargantuan Gastronomy Belies Our Concern With Calories |last=Brataas, Anne |date=July 7, 1989 |access-date=July 20, 2012 |publisher=Chicago Tribune via Knight-Ridder}}</ref> and 13&nbsp;grams of fat.\n* ''Golden Oreo'' \u2013 First released in 2004,<ref name=\"2017 Fact Sheet\" /> this has \"golden\" vanilla flavored wafers on the outside of the cookie, as an alternative to the original chocolate flavored wafers. Available with various flavors of cr\u00e8me filling including original, chocolate, lemon and birthday cake. The chocolate cr\u00e8me variety, being the reverse of the original cookie, was known as the ''Uh-Oh Oreo'' until 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biscuitpeople.com/magazine/post/the-short-history-of-oreo-cookies|title=The Short History of Oreo Cookies|publisher=www.biscuitpeople.com|date=April 27, 2017|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Nabisco-Oreo-Minis.jpg|link=File:Nabisco-Oreo-Minis.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.9|Oreo Minis]]\n*''Oreo Mini'' \u2013 First introduced in 1991,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/24/business/rjr-nabisco-reports-neet-of-123-million-in-3d-quarter.html |title=RJR Nabisco Reports Neet Of $123 Million in 3d Quarter |last=Foltz |first=Kim |date=October 24, 1991 |access-date=March 2, 2011 |publisher=Nytimes.com}}</ref> these are miniature bite-sized versions of the original Oreo cookie. After being discontinued in the late 1990s, they were re-released in 2000 along with the redesigned 2001 [[Dodge Caravan]] minivan as part of a promotional tie-in with [[Daimler AG]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-28159731_ITM |title=New Mini Oreos Debut in New Mini Van |date=August 10, 2000 |work=PR Newswire}}</ref> Their packaging in the 1990s consisted of a \"miniaturized\" version of the full-sized cardboard tray and box used in Oreo packaging at the time. Their revised packaging consists of an aluminum foil bag.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}} ''Oreo Minis'' are available with various flavors of cr\u00e8me filling including original, chocolate, strawberry, and the new mint flavor which debuted in 2015. As well as the bagged version, they are also sold in Nabisco To-Go Cups, lidded plastic cups which fit into car cup-holders (in line with other Nabisco snacks that come in miniature form, such as Nutter Butters). A ''Golden Oreo Mini'' was also made available after the ''Golden Oreo'' was released in 2004. According to the Oreo website, the slogan of the ''Oreo Mini'' is \"Grab 'em. Pop 'em. Love 'em.\"\n* ''Mega Stuf Oreo'' \u2013 Released in February 2013, the ''Mega Stuf'' variety is similar to ''Double Stuf'', but with even more white cr\u00e8me filling. They come in both chocolate and golden wafer varieties.\n* ''Oreo Thins'' \u2013 Introduced in July 2015, this is a thin version of the original Oreo cookie. ''Thins'' come in both chocolate and golden wafer varieties, with various cr\u00e8me filling flavors including chocolate, mint, lemon and tiramisu. Each cookie contains only 40 calories; they are 66% thinner than the original version.\n* ''Chocolate Oreo'' \u2013 Simply an Oreo cookie with chocolate cr\u00e8me filling instead of the original vanilla flavored white cr\u00e8me filling.<!--Introduced 2011-->\n* ''Mint Oreo'' \u2013 A variety of Oreo with two chocolate wafers separated by a mint flavored cr\u00e8me filling.<!--Introduced when?-->\n* ''The Most Stuf'' \u2013 Introduced in January 2019, a limited edition Oreo with approximately four times the amount of cr\u00e8me filling of a standard Oreo.\n\nSpecial edition ''Double Stuf Oreo'' cookies are produced during springtime, and around [[Halloween]] and [[Christmas]]. These have colored frosting reflecting the current holiday: blue or yellow for springtime; orange for Halloween; and red or green for the Christmas holiday. One side of each seasonal cookie is stamped with an appropriate design; the spring cookies feature flowers, butterflies, etc., while the Halloween editions feature a jack o'lantern, ghost, cat, flock of bats, or broom-riding witch.<!--What designs are featured on the Christmas ones?--> The 2017 ''Halloween Oreo'' broke with this tradition, having orange-colored cr\u00e8me filling (albeit with classic vanilla flavor) but carrying no seasonal designs.\n\nIn some countries, Oreos come in a variety of flavors that are not familiar to the U.S. market. For example, ''Green Tea Oreos'' are only available in China and Japan, while ''Lemon Ice Oreos'' were only ever introduced in Japan.\n\n=== Limited editions ===\n[[File:Mr. Christie, you definitely make good cookies! (2523264708).jpg|thumb|Close-up view of a golden Oreo cookie wafer]]\nBeginning in the early 2010s, Oreo began releasing [[Limited edition candy|limited edition]] runs of cookies with more exotic flavors. These \"limited editions\" typically appear in stores for a short period and are then discontinued, although some varieties have since resurfaced, for example: ''Reese's Oreos'' returned for a second limited run after they were first introduced for a limited period in 2014; and ''Birthday Cake Oreos'', originally introduced in 2012, have since become permanently available.<ref name=\"List\">{{cite web |url=http://www.glamour.com/story/special-oreos-flavors-limited-edition |title=A Comprehensive List of Every Special Oreo Flavor, Ever |last=Clinton |first=Leah Melby |date=June 17, 2015 |publisher=Glamour |access-date=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Some limited editions are only made available at certain retailers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foodbeast.com/news/blueberry-oreos-fruity-crisps/ |title=NEW OREO FLAVORS: Blueberry Pie & Fruity Crisps |last=Ayerouth |first=Elie |date=May 26, 2016 |publisher=foodbeast.com |access-date=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLimited edition runs usually feature a cr\u00e8me filling that has been flavored to replicate the taste of a specific fruit or dessert, from familiar flavors such as [[lemon]] or [[Mentha|mint]], to the more specific and unusual flavors of [[blueberry pie]] or [[red velvet cake]]. They may also incorporate different varieties of cookie wafer, for example ''Cinnamon-Bun Oreos'' featured [[cinnamon]] flavored cookies and \"frosting flavored cr\u00e8me\". In recent years, some limited editions have paired Oreos with other recognizable [[confectionery]] brands, including [[Reese's Peanut Butter Cups|Reese's]], [[Swedish Fish]], and [[Peeps]].\n\nSome examples of limited edition Oreos are:\n* ''Birthday Cake Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition, available from February to July 2012, to celebrate Oreo's 100th birthday. Made up of two chocolate Oreo cookies with a [[birthday cake]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling and sprinkles inside. On one of the two cookies, the traditional design was replaced with a birthday candle and the words \"OREO 100\". The birthday cake flavor has since been reintroduced, with a \"double stuf\" amount of cr\u00e8me filling, in both chocolate and golden Oreo varieties, except that the cookies no longer display the \"OREO 100\" print.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.snackworks.com/search/product-results.aspx?searchText=oreo+birthday+cake |title=Product Search Results \u2013 Snackworks |publisher=Snackworks |access-date=October 13, 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Lemon Twist Oreo'' \u2013 First released in 2012 as a limited edition, reintroduced in 2013, made up of two golden Oreo cookies with a lemon flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Neapolitan Oreo'' \u2013 Released for a limited time in 2012, consisting of three golden Oreo cookies with a double sandwich of chocolate and strawberry cr\u00e8me fillings. This version was reminiscent of [[Neapolitan ice cream]].\n* ''Watermelon Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition for the summer of 2013, made up of two golden Oreo cookies with [[watermelon]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Strawberries n' Creme Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in 2013, made up of two golden Oreo cookies with a cr\u00e8me filling consisting of two halves, one strawberry flavored and one similar to traditional Oreo cr\u00e8me.\n* ''Fruit Punch Oreo'' \u2013 Released for a limited time in 2014, featuring golden Oreo cookies filled with fruit punch flavored cr\u00e8me.\n* ''Cookie Dough Oreo'' \u2013 Released in March 2014, a limited edition featuring chocolate cookies with [[cookie dough]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/12/dining/the-cookie-dough-oreo.html?_r=0 |title=The Cookie Dough Oreo |last=Moss |first=Michael |date=March 11, 2014 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n* ''Root Beer Float Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in July 2014, made up of two gold Oreo cookies filled with [[root beer]] flavored cr\u00e8me.\n* ''Pumpkin Spice Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in September 2014, made up of two gold Oreo cookies with [[Pumpkin pie spice|pumpkin spice]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Red Velvet Oreo'' \u2013 First released in February 2015 as a limited edition, since reintroduced, featuring red Oreo cookies with cream cheese flavored cr\u00e8me filling. This version was designed to emulate the popular [[red velvet cake]].\n* ''Key Lime Pie Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in July 2015, made of two [[Graham flour|graham]] flavored Oreo cookies filled with [[key lime]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Cinnamon Bun Oreo'' \u2013 Released in January 2016 as a limited edition, made up of two cinnamon flavored cookies filled with [[Icing (food)|frosting]] flavored cr\u00e8me filling. This version was designed to emulate the [[Cinnamon roll|cinnamon bun]].\n* ''S'mores Oreo'' \u2013 Inspired by the [[S'more|traditional campfire snack]] and released as a limited edition in summer 2016, this version was made with graham flavored cookies and a double layer of cr\u00e8me filling, one layer chocolate flavored and one layer [[marshmallow]] flavored.\n* ''Fruity Crisp Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in June 2016, consisting of two golden Oreo cookies with a fruity and colorful rice crisp cr\u00e8me filling, similar to [[Pebbles cereal|Fruity Pebbles]].\n* ''Blueberry Pie Oreo'' \u2013 Also released in June 2016 as a limited edition, and then reintroduced in 2017, made with graham flavored cookie wafers and a blueberry flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Swedish Fish Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition in August 2016, made up of two chocolate Oreo cookies with a red cr\u00e8me filling, flavored to resemble the red-colored [[Swedish Fish]] candy. These were originally released exclusively through [[Kroger]] stores (in the U.S.)\n* ''Peeps Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in February 2017 for the Easter season, consisting of two golden Oreo cookies filled with pink \"marshmallow Peeps\" flavored cr\u00e8me\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/take-a-peep-at-these-new-oreo-flavors_us_58ab1b5fe4b07602ad56c7be |title=Peeps-Flavored Oreos Are Here And We Don\u2019t Know Who Will Eat Them |last=Ledbetter |first=Carly |date=February 2, 2017 |publisher=The Huffington Post |access-date=February 21, 2017}}</ref> A second version was released in February 2018, instead made with Peeps-embossed chocolate cookies and purple \"marshmallow Peeps\" flavored cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Waffles & Syrup Oreo'' \u2013 A limited edition released in May 2017, made with golden Oreo cookies and featuring a ring of vanilla cr\u00e8me with a blob of [[maple syrup]] flavored cr\u00e8me in the center. Exclusive to [[Albertsons]] stores (in the U.S.)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.today.com/food/oreo-waffles-syrup-flavor-hits-select-stores-week-t111243 |title=Oreos for breakfast?! Meet the new Waffles & Syrup flavor |date=May 10, 2017 |work=USA Today}}</ref>\n* ''Chocolate Hazelnut Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition on January 1, 2018, consisting of golden Oreo cookies with a \"[[Nutella]]-like\" flavored cr\u00e8me filling.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.popsugar.com/food/Chocolate-Hazelnut-Oreos-44112889 |title=Nutella-Lovers Will Lose Their Sh*t Over the New Chocolate Hazelnut Oreos! |work=Popsugar.food |access-date=March 7, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Salted Caramel Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition in 2018, consisting of golden Oreo cookies with a salted caramel flavor cr\u00e8me filling.\n* ''Firework Oreo'' \u2013 Released around the Fourth of July in the United States, consisting of classic Oreo cookies with Pop Rocks candy within the cr\u00e8me.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4770605/firework-oreos/|title=The New 'Firework' Oreos Are Like Sparklers In Your Mouth|date=May 8, 2017|first=Raisa|last=Bruner|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n*''Peppermint Bark Oreo''  \u2013 Released as a limited edition in October 2018 (for the 2018 holiday season), consisting of a \"double stuf\" amount of peppermint flavored cr\u00e8me with red sugar crystals and the original chocolate Oreo cookies.\n*''Easter Egg Oreo'' \u2013 Released as a limited edition in January 2019 (for the Easter season), consisting of chocolate Oreo cookies in an oval shape to resemble eggs, with purple-colored cr\u00e8me filling and four different Easter-related designs: a bunny in a basket, a baby chick wearing bunny ears, and spots and stripes to resemble the painting of an Easter egg.\n*''Chocolate Marshmallow'' \u2013 Released in January 2020, includes marshmallow pieces in the cookie and chocolate marshmallow cr\u00e8me filling.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/05/business/oreo-new-flavors-caramel-coconut-chocolate-marshmallow-trnd/index.html|title=Oreo has two new flavors for the new year: Caramel Coconut and Chocolate Marshmallow|first=Melissa |last=Gray|website=CNN|access-date=2020-01-06|date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n*''Caramel Coconut'' \u2013 Released in January 2020, has caramel cr\u00e8me filling with coconut flavor and coconut pieces.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Supreme Oreo''- Released in March 2020, double stuffed Oreo branded by Supreme.\n\n== Use as an insult ==\n{{See also|Acting white}}\nThe term \"Oreo\" has been used as a disparaging and offensive reference to a black person who is perceived or judged to [[Acting white|act]] in a \"white manner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/oreo|title=Dictionary.com definition|work=dictionary.com|access-date=August 1, 2018}}</ref> The insult may be levied as an accusation that the person perpetuates the \"un-level playing field for blacks\". The metaphor is based on the implication that the person is like the cookie, \"black on the outside and white on the inside\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1998-01-14/news/9801140635_1_john-lombardi-uhlfelder-oreo |title=UF President Apologizes For Remark |last=Griffin |first=Michael |last2=James |first2=Joni |date=January 14, 1998 |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Food}}\n* [[Cookies and cream]]\n* [[Newman-O's]]\n* [[Hydrox]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Oreo cookies}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.oreo.com}}\n* [http://www.oreo.co.uk/ Official UK website]\n* [http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodcookies.html#oreos Additional history notes on Oreo cookies]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{Mondelez}}\n\n[[Category:Oreo| ]]\n[[Category:Nabisco brands]]\n[[Category:Mondel\u0113z brands]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1912]]\n[[Category:Cookie sandwiches]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:65c:400:796d:548b:2242:7e5e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I added GREAT CONTENT. I Have completely fixed this page. No mistakes!)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oreo"}
